{"title_page": "Nuela Charles", "text_new": "{{Infobox musical artist\n| name                = Nuela Charles\n| image               = Nuela Charles 2016.jpg\n| caption             = \n| image_size          =\n| background          = solo_singer\n| birth_name          = Manuela W\u00fcthrich\n| alias               = \n| birth_date          = {{Birth date and age|1985|1|19|mf=y}}\n| birth_place         = [[Kenya]]\n| origin              = [[Edmonton]], [[Alberta]], [[Canada]]\n| instrument          = [[vocals]]\n| genre               = [[Pop music|Pop]], [[soul music|soul]], [[contemporary R&B|r&b]], [[jazz]], [[hip hop music|hip hop]]\n| occupation          = [[Singing|Singer]], [[songwriter]]\n| years_active        = 2012\u2013present\n| label               = \n| associated_acts     = \n| website             = {{URL|nuelacharles.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Manuela W\u00fcthrich''' (born January 19, 1985), who goes by the stage name '''Nuela Charles''', is a Canadian, Swiss, and Kenyan [[music]]ian, who plays a style of [[soul music|soul]], [[pop music|pop]], [[contemporary R&B|r&b]], [[jazz]] and [[hip hop music]].<ref name=\"Band\">{{cite web |author=Staff |title=Nuela Charles |url=http://bandofthedayapp.com/2013/08/20/nuela-charles/ |publisher=Band of the Day |accessdate=January 16, 2017 |date=August 20, 2013}}</ref> She has released four musical works, ''Aware'' (2012), ''The Grand Hustle'' (2016), ''Distant Danger'' (2018), and ''Melt'' (2019).\n\n==Early life and background==\nCharles was born, Manuela W\u00fcthrich, on January 19,<ref name=\"Day One\">{{cite web |first=Nuela |last=Charles |title=CUZ IT'S MY BIRTHDAY Check out the shop for great deals! CD's for $5 and Shirts for $10. BOOOM |url=https://twitter.com/nuelacharles/status/424934683114483712 |publisher=[[Twitter]] |accessdate=January 16, 2017 |date=January 19, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Day Two\">{{cite web |first=Nuela |last=Charles |title=Morning after. I feel so much love! Thanks to everyone who came out last night! Love you all ! #birthday #28 |url=https://twitter.com/nuelacharles/status/293073254430683136 |publisher=[[Twitter]] |accessdate=January 16, 2017 |date=January 20, 2013}}</ref> 1985,<ref name=\"Age\">{{cite web |first=Nuela |last=Charles |title=28 years ago in Kenya. Wasn't too happy was I ? #baby #crying #kenya |url=https://twitter.com/nuelacharles/status/292459083313840128 |publisher=[[Twitter]] |accessdate=January 16, 2017 |date=January 18, 2013}}</ref> in [[Kenya]]. She graduated from [[Briercrest College and Seminary]] in 2008, and she identifies as a [[Christians|Christian]].<ref name=\"BC\">{{cite web |first=Kayla |last=Malanka |title=A new song: Singer/songwriter embraced her musical career at Briercrest |url=http://www.briercrest.ca/bcast/news/article.aspx?id=2568 |publisher=[[Briercrest College and Seminary|Briercrest]] |accessdate=January 16, 2017 |date=May 20, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Winehouse\">{{cite web |author=Chaka V. |title=In the Winehouse with\u2026Nuela Charles |url=http://www.thewinehousemag.com/in-the-winehouse-with-nuela-charles-2/ |journal=The Winehouse Mag |accessdate=January 16, 2017 |date=July 25, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Music career==\nHer music recording career started in 2012, with the [[studio album]] ''Aware'', released on October 23, 2012.<ref name=\"Edmonton Review\">{{cite web |first=Sandra |last=Sperounes |title=Album review: Nuela Charles, Aware |url=https://edmontonjournal.com/entertainment/music/album-review-nuela-charles-aware |journal=[[Edmonton Journal]] |accessdate=January 16, 2017 |date=October 17, 2012}}</ref>  She released another studio album, ''The Grand Hustle'', on November 4, 2016.<ref name=\"Edmonton Interview\">{{cite web |first=Sandra |last=Sperounes |title=Nuela Charles wrestles her doubts on The Grand Hustle |url=https://edmontonjournal.com/entertainment/music/nuela-charles-wrestles-her-doubts-on-the-grand-hustle |journal=[[Edmonton Journal]] |accessdate=January 16, 2017 |date=November 1, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Vue Story\">{{cite web |first=Stephan |last=Boissonneault |title=Nuela Charles on finding her voice, and her new album The Grand Hustle |url=http://www.vueweekly.com/nuela-charles-on-finding-her-voice-and-her-new-album-the-grand-hustle/ |journal=[[Vue Weekly]] |accessdate=January 16, 2017 |date=November 2, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Novella\">{{cite web |first=Theodora |last=Odikpo |title=Album Review: The Grand Hustle by Nuela Charles |url=http://novellamag.com/album-review-the-grand-hustle-by-nuela-charles/ |journal=Novella |accessdate=January 16, 2017 |date=November 22, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n*''Aware'' (October 23, 2012)\n*''The Grand Hustle'' (November 4, 2016)\n*''Distant Danger'' (October 19, 2018)\n*''Melt'' (November 8, 2019)\n\n==Awards & Nominations==\n{|class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n!Year\n!Organization\n!Award\n!Artist/work\n!Result\n!{{Abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n|rowspan=2|2013\n|[[Western Canadian Music Awards]]\n|Urban Recording of the Year\n|rowspan=2|''Aware''\n|style=\"background:#FDD\"|Nominated\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n|-\n|Edmonton Music Prize\n|Album of the Year\n|style=\"background:#90FF90\"|Winner\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n|-\n|2014\n|SiriusXM Canada Indies Awards\n|R&B/Soul Artist of the Year\n|rowspan=2|Nuela Charles\n|style=\"background:#FDD\"|Nominated\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n|-\n|rowspan=3|2017\n|rowspan=2|Western Canadian Music Awards\n|Urban Artist of the Year\n|style=\"background:#90FF90\"|Winner\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n|-\n|Video of the Year\n|\"Crumbling Down\"\n|style=\"background:#FDD\"|Nominated\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n|-\n|Edmonton Music Prize\n|Album of the Year\n|rowspan=2|''The Grand Hustle''\n|style=\"background:#FF0\"|Runner Up\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n|-\n|rowspan=2|2018\n|[[Juno Awards of 2018|Juno Awards]]\n|Adult Contemporary Album of the Year\n|style=\"background:#FDD\"|Nominated\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n|-\n|Edmonton Music Prize\n|Album of the Year\n|rowspan=2|''Distant Danger''\n|style=\"background:#FF0\"|Runner Up\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n|-\n|2019\n|[[Juno Awards of 2019|Juno Awards]]\n|Adult Contemporary Album of the Year\n|style=\"background:#FDD\"|Nominated\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n|-\n|rowspan=2|2020\n|Pop Awards\n|Song of the Year Award\n|\"Got It Bad\"\n|style=\"background:#90FF90\"|Winner\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pop-mag.com/2020-01-19/welcome-to-the-pop-awards-2020-the-third-annual-pop-awards/|title=Welcome to the POP AWARDS 2020, the third annual Pop Awards|date=January 19, 2020|first=Leslie|last=Addo|work=Pop Magazine|accessdate=February 20, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://pop-awards.com/2020|title=Pop Awards 2020, the 3rd annual Pop Awards |work=Pop Awards|accessdate=February 20, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Juno Awards of 2020|Juno Awards]]\n|Adult Contemporary Album of the Year\n|''Melt''\n|style=\"background:#FDD\"|Nominated\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|nuelacharles.com}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Charles, Nuela}}\n[[Category:1985 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Canadian Christians]]\n[[Category:Canadian female pop singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Swiss musicians]]\n[[Category:Swiss Christians]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of Swiss descent]]\n[[Category:Kenyan female singers]]\n[[Category:Kenyan Christians]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Edmonton]]\n[[Category:Canadian soul singers]]\n[[Category:Canadian contemporary R&B singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century women singers]]\n[[Category:Black Canadian singers]]\n[[Category:Black Canadian women]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox musical artist\n| name                = Nuela Charles\n| image               = Nuela Charles 2016.jpg\n| caption             = \n| image_size          =\n| background          = solo_singer\n| birth_name          = Manuela W\u00fcthrich\n| alias               = \n| birth_date          = {{Birth date and age|1985|1|19|mf=y}}\n| birth_place         = [[Kenya]]\n| origin              = [[Edmonton]], [[Alberta]], [[Canada]]\n| instrument          = [[vocals]]\n| genre               = [[Pop music|Pop]], [[soul music|soul]], [[contemporary R&B|r&b]], [[jazz]], [[hip hop music|hip hop]]\n| occupation          = [[Singing|Singer]], [[songwriter]]\n| years_active        = 2012\u2013present\n| label               = \n| associated_acts     = \n| website             = {{URL|nuelacharles.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Manuela W\u00fcthrich''' (born January 19, 1985), who goes by the stage name '''Nuela Charles''', is a Canadian, Swiss, and Kenyan [[music]]ian, who plays a style of [[soul music|soul]], [[pop music|pop]], [[contemporary R&B|r&b]], [[jazz]] and [[hip hop music]].<ref name=\"Band\">{{cite web |author=Staff |title=Nuela Charles |url=http://bandofthedayapp.com/2013/08/20/nuela-charles/ |publisher=Band of the Day |accessdate=January 16, 2017 |date=August 20, 2013}}</ref> She has released four musical works, ''Aware'' (2012), ''The Grand Hustle'' (2016), ''Distant Danger'' (2018), and ''Melt'' (2019).\n\n==Early life and background==\nCharles was born, Manuela W\u00fcthrich, on January 19,<ref name=\"Day One\">{{cite web |first=Nuela |last=Charles |title=CUZ IT'S MY BIRTHDAY Check out the shop for great deals! CD's for $5 and Shirts for $10. BOOOM |url=https://twitter.com/nuelacharles/status/424934683114483712 |publisher=[[Twitter]] |accessdate=January 16, 2017 |date=January 19, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Day Two\">{{cite web |first=Nuela |last=Charles |title=Morning after. I feel so much love! Thanks to everyone who came out last night! Love you all ! #birthday #28 |url=https://twitter.com/nuelacharles/status/293073254430683136 |publisher=[[Twitter]] |accessdate=January 16, 2017 |date=January 20, 2013}}</ref> 1985,<ref name=\"Age\">{{cite web |first=Nuela |last=Charles |title=28 years ago in Kenya. Wasn't too happy was I ? #baby #crying #kenya |url=https://twitter.com/nuelacharles/status/292459083313840128 |publisher=[[Twitter]] |accessdate=January 16, 2017 |date=January 18, 2013}}</ref> in [[Kenya]]. She graduated from [[Briercrest College and Seminary]] in 2008, and she identifies as a [[Christians|Christian]].<ref name=\"BC\">{{cite web |first=Kayla |last=Malanka |title=A new song: Singer/songwriter embraced her musical career at Briercrest |url=http://www.briercrest.ca/bcast/news/article.aspx?id=2568 |publisher=[[Briercrest College and Seminary|Briercrest]] |accessdate=January 16, 2017 |date=May 20, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Winehouse\">{{cite web |author=Chaka V. |title=In the Winehouse with\u2026Nuela Charles |url=http://www.thewinehousemag.com/in-the-winehouse-with-nuela-charles-2/ |journal=The Winehouse Mag |accessdate=January 16, 2017 |date=July 25, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Music career==\nHer music recording career started in 2012, with the [[studio album]] ''Aware'', released on October 23, 2012.<ref name=\"Edmonton Review\">{{cite web |first=Sandra |last=Sperounes |title=Album review: Nuela Charles, Aware |url=https://edmontonjournal.com/entertainment/music/album-review-nuela-charles-aware |journal=[[Edmonton Journal]] |accessdate=January 16, 2017 |date=October 17, 2012}}</ref>  She released another studio album, ''The Grand Hustle'', on November 4, 2016.<ref name=\"Edmonton Interview\">{{cite web |first=Sandra |last=Sperounes |title=Nuela Charles wrestles her doubts on The Grand Hustle |url=https://edmontonjournal.com/entertainment/music/nuela-charles-wrestles-her-doubts-on-the-grand-hustle |journal=[[Edmonton Journal]] |accessdate=January 16, 2017 |date=November 1, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Vue Story\">{{cite web |first=Stephan |last=Boissonneault |title=Nuela Charles on finding her voice, and her new album The Grand Hustle |url=http://www.vueweekly.com/nuela-charles-on-finding-her-voice-and-her-new-album-the-grand-hustle/ |journal=[[Vue Weekly]] |accessdate=January 16, 2017 |date=November 2, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Novella\">{{cite web |first=Theodora |last=Odikpo |title=Album Review: The Grand Hustle by Nuela Charles |url=http://novellamag.com/album-review-the-grand-hustle-by-nuela-charles/ |journal=Novella |accessdate=January 16, 2017 |date=November 22, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n*''Aware'' (October 23, 2012)\n*''The Grand Hustle'' (November 4, 2016)\n*''Distant Danger'' (October 19, 2018)\n*''Melt'' (November 8, 2019)\n\n==Awards & Nominations==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Organization\n! Award\n! Artist/work\n! Result\n! {{Abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n|rowspan=2|2013\n|[[Western Canadian Music Awards]]\n|Urban Recording of the Year\n|rowspan=2|''Aware''\n|style=\"background:#FDD\"|Nominated\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n|-\n|Edmonton Music Prize\n|Album of the Year\n|style=\"background:#90FF90\"|Winner\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n|-\n|2014\n|SiriusXM Canada Indies Awards\n|R&B/Soul Artist of the Year\n|rowspan=2|Nuela Charles\n|style=\"background:#FDD\"|Nominated\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n|-\n|rowspan=3|2017\n|rowspan=2|Western Canadian Music Awards\n|Urban Artist of the Year\n|style=\"background:#90FF90\"|Winner\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n|-\n|Video of the Year\n|\"Crumbling Down\"\n|style=\"background:#FDD\"|Nominated\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n|-\n|Edmonton Music Prize\n|Album of the Year\n|rowspan=2|''The Grand Hustle''\n|style=\"background:#FF0\"|Runner Up\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n|-\n|rowspan=2|2018\n|[[Juno Awards of 2018|Juno Awards]]\n|Adult Contemporary Album of the Year\n|style=\"background:#FDD\"|Nominated\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n|-\n|Edmonton Music Prize\n|Album of the Year\n|rowspan=2|''Distant Danger''\n|style=\"background:#FF0\"|Runner Up\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n|-\n|2019\n|[[Juno Awards of 2019|Juno Awards]]\n|Adult Contemporary Album of the Year\n|style=\"background:#FDD\"|Nominated\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n|-\n|rowspan=2|2020\n|Pop Awards\n|Song of the Year Award\n|\"Got It Bad\"\n|style=\"background:#90FF90\"|Winner\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pop-mag.com/2020-01-19/welcome-to-the-pop-awards-2020-the-third-annual-pop-awards/|title=Welcome to the POP AWARDS 2020, the third annual Pop Awards|date=January 19, 2020|first=Leslie|last=Addo|work=Pop Magazine|accessdate=February 20, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://pop-awards.com/2020|title=Pop Awards 2020, the 3rd annual Pop Awards |work=Pop Awards|accessdate=February 20, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Juno Awards of 2020|Juno Awards]]\n|Adult Contemporary Album of the Year\n|''Melt''\n|style=\"background:#FDD\"|Nominated\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n|-}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|nuelacharles.com}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Charles, Nuela}}\n[[Category:1985 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Canadian Christians]]\n[[Category:Canadian female pop singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Swiss musicians]]\n[[Category:Swiss Christians]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of Swiss descent]]\n[[Category:Kenyan female singers]]\n[[Category:Kenyan Christians]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Edmonton]]\n[[Category:Canadian soul singers]]\n[[Category:Canadian contemporary R&B singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century women singers]]\n[[Category:Black Canadian singers]]\n[[Category:Black Canadian women]]\n", "name_user": "Facevalue1", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nuela_Charles"}
{"title_page": "Mary Whitehouse", "text_new": "{{For|the British comedy show or the television film with Julie Walters|The Mary Whitehouse Experience|Filth: The Mary Whitehouse Story}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2016}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name =Mary Whitehouse\n| honorific_suffix = {{postnom|country=GBR|size=100|CBE}}\n|birth_name = Constance Mary Hutcheson\n|birth_date = {{birth date|1910|6|13|df=y}}\n|birth_place = [[Nuneaton|Nuneaton, Warwickshire]], England\n|death_date = {{death date and age|df=yes|2001|11|23|1910|6|13}}\n|death_place = [[Colchester|Colchester, Essex]], England\n|image = Mary Whitehouse on phone.jpg\n| caption = Whitehouse in 1981\n|signature =\n|parents =\n|spouse = {{marriage|Ernest Raymond Whitehouse|1940|2000|end=his death}}\n|children = 3<ref name=\"Udall\">Elizabeth Udall [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/features/3636761/Mary-WhitehouseSometimes-I-denied-she-was-my-mother.html \"Mary Whitehouse: 'Sometimes I denied she was my mother'\"], {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110629215919/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/features/3636761/Mary-WhitehouseSometimes-I-denied-she-was-my-mother.html |date=29 June 2011 }} ''The Daily Telegraph'', 27 May 2008</ref>\n|movement = [[Social conservatism]]<br />[[Nationwide Festival of Light]]\n|organization = [[Mediawatch-uk|National Viewers' and Listeners' Association]]\n|monuments =\n|alma_mater = [[Queens Park High School|Chester City Grammar School]].<br />[[MMU Cheshire|Cheshire County Teacher Training College]]\n|awards =\n}}\n'''Constance Mary Whitehouse''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|CBE}} (n\u00e9e '''Hutcheson'''; 13 June 1910 \u2013 23 November 2001) was a deranged dingbat, a[[British people|British]] [[educator]] and [[Conservatism in the United Kingdom|conservative]] [[activist]]. She campaigned against [[social liberalism]] and the mainstream British media, both of which she accused of encouraging a more [[permissive society]]. She was the founder and first president of the [[Mediawatch-UK|National Viewers' and Listeners' Association]], through which she led a longstanding campaign against the [[BBC]]. A hard-line [[Social conservatism|social conservative]], she was disparagingly termed a [[reactionary]] by her socially liberal opponents. Her motivation derived from her traditional [[Christianity|Christian]] beliefs, her aversion to the rapid social and political changes in British society of the 1960s and her work as a teacher of sex education.<ref name=\"LA Times\">{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2001/nov/26/local/me-8356|title=Mary Whitehouse, 91; Led British TV Cleanup|work=Los Angeles Times|date=26 November 2001|accessdate=5 January 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160306230659/http://articles.latimes.com/2001/nov/26/local/me-8356|archive-date=6 March 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nBorn in [[Nuneaton]], [[Warwickshire]], Whitehouse became an art teacher, at the same time becoming involved in evangelical Christian groups such as the [[Student Christian Movement of Great Britain|Student Christian Movement]] (which became increasingly more liberal leading up to and after a 1928 split with the [[Universities and Colleges Christian Fellowship]]) and [[Moral Re-Armament]]. She became a public figure via the Clean-Up TV pressure group, established in 1964, in which she was the most prominent figure. The following year she founded the National Viewers' and Listeners' Association, using it as a platform to criticise the BBC for what she perceived as a lack of accountability, and excessive use of bad language and portrayals of sex and violence in its programmes. As a result, she became an object of mockery in the media.\n\nDuring the 1970s she broadened her activities, and was a leading figure in the [[Nationwide Festival of Light]], a Christian campaign that gained mass support for a period. She initiated a successful private prosecution against ''[[Gay News]]'' on the grounds of [[blasphemous libel]], the first such case for more than 50 years. Another private prosecution was against the director of the play ''[[The Romans in Britain]]'', which had been performed at the [[Royal National Theatre|National Theatre]].\n\nWhitehouse's campaigns continue to divide opinion. Her critics have accused her of being a highly censorious figure, and her traditional moral convictions brought her into direct conflict with advocates of the [[sexual revolution]], [[feminism]], [[Children's rights#Opposition|children's rights]] and [[LGBT rights in the United Kingdom|gay rights]]. Others see her more positively and believe she was attempting to halt a decline in what they perceived as Britain's moral standards. According to Ben Thompson, the editor of an anthology of Whitehouse-related letters published in 2012: \"From ... feminist anti-pornography campaigns to the executive naming and shaming strategies of [[UK Uncut]], her ideological and tactical influence has been discernible in all sorts of unexpected places in recent years.\"<ref name=\"Thompson\">Ben Thompson [http://www.ft.com/cms/s/2/093c3726-24e1-11e2-86fb-00144feabdc0.html#axzz2Bv5X3utv \"Ban this filth!\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121112141447/http://www.ft.com/cms/s/2/093c3726-24e1-11e2-86fb-00144feabdc0.html#axzz2Bv5X3utv#axzz2Bv5X3utv |date=12 November 2012 }}, ''Financial Times'', 9 November 2012. This article is a reprint of the introduction to Ben Thompson (ed.) ''[[Ban This Filth!: Letters From the Mary Whitehouse Archive]]'', London: [[Faber & Faber]], 2012 {{ISBN|978-0571281497}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nBorn in [[Nuneaton|Nuneaton, Warwickshire]], Whitehouse was the second of four children of a \"less-than-successful businessman\" and a \"necessarily resourceful mother\".<ref name=\"Times\">Obituary, ''[[The Times (United Kingdom)|The Times]]'', 24 November 2001</ref> She won a scholarship to [[Queens Park High School|Chester City Grammar School]],<ref name=\"Telegraph\">[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/culture-obituaries/tv-radio-obituaries/6605110/Mary-Whitehouse.html Obituary], {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100606052212/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/culture-obituaries/tv-radio-obituaries/6605110/Mary-Whitehouse.html |date=6 June 2010 }} ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'', 24 November 2001</ref> where she was keen on hockey and tennis,<ref name=\"Times\"/> and after leaving she did two years of unpaid apprentice teaching at St John's School in [[Chester]], [[Cheshire]]. At the [[Manchester Metropolitan University|Cheshire County Teacher Training College]] in [[Crewe]], Cheshire, specialising in [[secondary school]] art teaching, she was involved with the [[Student Christian Movement of Great Britain|Student Christian Movement]] before qualifying in 1932. She became an art teacher at Lichfield Road School in [[Lichfield]], [[Staffordshire]], where she stayed for eight years.\n\nShe joined the Wolverhampton branch of the [[Oxford Group]], later known<!-- from 1938. --> as [[Moral Re-Armament]] (MRA), in 1935.<ref name=\"Moorehead1977\">{{cite news|last=Moorehead|first=Caroline|url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/archive/article/1977-10-31/8/1.html|title=Mrs Mary Whitehouse: A Certainty That Everything is Either Black or White|work=The Times|location=London|date=31 October 1977|accessdate=1 May 2016|page=8}} {{subscription required}}</ref> At MRA meetings, she met Ernest Raymond Whitehouse; they married in 1940 and remained married until he died in [[Colchester]], [[Essex]], aged 87, in 2000.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.findmypast.com/BirthsMarriagesDeaths.jsp |title=England and Wales Deaths 1984\u20132006 |publisher=Findmypast.com |accessdate=25 July 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090228000620/http://www.findmypast.com/BirthsMarriagesDeaths.jsp |archive-date=28 February 2009 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The couple had five sons, two of whom (twins) died in infancy.<ref name=\"Warnock\">Mary Warnock \"Whitehouse <nowiki>[</nowiki>n\u00e9e Hutcheson<nowiki>]</nowiki>, (Constance) Marywhitehouse, Mary\", ''Oxford Dictionary of National Biography''</ref>\n\nAfter raising her sons in their earliest years, Whitehouse returned to teaching in 1953. That year she broadcast on ''[[Woman's Hour]]'' on the day before the coronation of [[Elizabeth II]] \"as a loyal housewife and subject\" and wrote an extensive article on [[homosexuality]] for ''[[The Sunday Times]]''.<ref name=\"Thompson\"/> According to Thompson this concerned how a mother might \"best avoid inadvertently pressuring her sons towards that particular orientation\", and gained enough attention to be republished as a pamphlet.<ref name=\"Thompson\"/>\n\nShe taught art at Madeley Modern School in [[Madeley, Shropshire]] from 1960, taking responsibility for sex education. Shocked at the moral beliefs of her pupils, she became concerned about what she and many others perceived as declining moral standards in the British media, especially in the [[BBC]].\n\n==Clean Up TV campaign and the NVALA==\n\n===Beginnings===\nWhitehouse began her activism in 1963 with a letter to the [[BBC]]<ref name=\"Brown\">Jonathan Brown [https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/mary-whitehouse-to-some-a-crank-to-others-a-warrior-617910.html \"Mary Whitehouse: To some a crank, to others a warrior\"], {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101001223421/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/mary-whitehouse-to-some-a-crank-to-others-a-warrior-617910.html |date=1 October 2010 }} ''The Independent'', 24 November 2001</ref> requesting to see [[Hugh Greene]], the BBC's [[Director-General of the BBC|Director-General]]. Greene was out of the country at the time, so she accepted an invitation to meet [[Harman Grisewood]], his deputy,<ref>Tracey and Morrison ''Whitehouse'', London & Basingstoke: Macmillan, 1979, p.41 {{ISBN|0-333-23790-0}}</ref> a Roman Catholic who she felt listened to her with understanding.<ref name=\"Briggs\">Asa Briggs ''The History of Broadcasting in the United Kingdom, Volume 5'', Oxford: Oxford University Press, 1995, p.332, 334</ref> Over the next few months though, she continued to be dissatisfied with what she saw on television.\n\nWith Norah Buckland, the wife of a vicar, she launched the Clean Up TV Campaign in January 1964 with a manifesto appealing to the \"women of Britain\". The campaign's first public meeting, on 5 May 1964, was held in [[Birmingham Town Hall|Birmingham's Town Hall]].<ref name=\"Winter\">David Winter [https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/mary-whitehouse-755388.html Obituary], {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110913163055/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/mary-whitehouse-755388.html |date=13 September 2011 }} ''The Independent'', 24 November 2001</ref> Richard Whitehouse, one of her sons, recalled in 2008: \"Coaches arrived from all over the country. Two thousand people poured in and suddenly there was my mother on a podium inspiring them to rapturous applause. Her hands were shaking. But she didn't stop\".<ref name=\"Udall\"/>\n\nAlthough he regularly clashed with Whitehouse, the academic [[Richard Hoggart]] shared some of her opinions and was present on the platform with her at this meeting.<ref name=\"RHoggart\">Richard Hoggart [https://www.theguardian.com/media/2001/nov/24/comment.comment \"Valid arguments lost in an obsession over sex\"], {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170419003224/https://www.theguardian.com/media/2001/nov/24/comment.comment |date=19 April 2017 }} ''The Guardian'', 24 November 2001. Hoggart is mistaken here in thinking he could have referred to Dennis Potter's plays on 5 May 1964, as Potter's earliest work in this form, ''The Confidence Course'', was not transmitted until 24 February 1965.</ref> ''[[The Times]]'' commented the following day: \"Perhaps never before in the history of the Birmingham Town Hall has such a successful meeting been sponsored by such a flimsy organisation\".<ref>''The Times'', 6 May 1964, cited by Tracey and Morrison, p.44</ref>\n\n===Sir Hugh Greene at the BBC===\nGreene, knighted in January 1964,<ref>Michael Tracey ''The Production of Political Television'', London: Routledge & Kegan Paul, 1978, p.159</ref> became her ''[[wikt:b\u00eate noire|b\u00eate noire]]''. He was, according to Whitehouse, \"the devil incarnate\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lewis|first1=Paul|title=Crusader was dubbed Britain's 'Queen of Clean'|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=soVIAAAAIBAJ&sjid=MXADAAAAIBAJ&pg=6209%2C7091403|accessdate=30 March 2016|work=The New York Times|date=20 December 2001}}</ref> who \"more than anybody else ... [was] responsible for the moral collapse in this country\".<ref name=\"Barker\">Dennis Barker [https://www.theguardian.com/media/2001/nov/24/guardianobituaries.obituaries \"Mary Whitehouse: Self-appointed campaigner against the permissive society on television\"], {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170317215956/https://www.theguardian.com/media/2001/nov/24/guardianobituaries.obituaries |date=17 March 2017 }} ''The Guardian'', 24 November 2001</ref> The CUTV manifesto asserted that the BBC under Greene spread \"the propaganda of disbelief, doubt and dirt ... promiscuity, infidelity and drinking\".<ref name=\"Stubbs\">Mary Whitehouse quoted by David Stubbs [https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2008/may/24/features16.theguide12 \"The moral minority\"], {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170419003438/https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2008/may/24/features16.theguide12 |date=19 April 2017 }} ''The Guardian'', 24 May 2008</ref> In place of this, the authors argued, the Corporation's activities should \"encourage and sustain faith in God and bring Him back to the hearts of our family and national life\".<ref>Quoted in Dominic Sandbrook ''White Heat'', London: Little, Brown, 2006, p.544</ref><ref>The full manifesto is quoted by [[Roy Shaw (arts administrator)|Roy Shaw]] in [http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1111/j.1741-2005.1966.tb01015.x/abstract \"Television: Freedom and Responsibility\"], {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121102112240/http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1111/j.1741-2005.1966.tb01015.x/abstract |date=2 November 2012 }} ''New Blackfriars'', no.553, June 1966, p.453</ref> Interviewed by ''[[The Catholic Herald]]'' for its Christmas 1965 issue, Whitehouse thought the BBC loaded its programmes in favour of the 'new morality'.<ref name=\"James\">Ian James [http://archive.catholicherald.co.uk/article/24th-december-1965/5/mrs-mary-whitehouse-co-founder-of-the-clean-up-tel \"MRS. MARY WHITEHOUSE, co-founder of the Clean-up Television Campaign\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140116212629/http://archive.catholicherald.co.uk/article/24th-december-1965/5/mrs-mary-whitehouse-co-founder-of-the-clean-up-tel |date=16 January 2014 }}, ''Catholic Herald'', 24 December 1965</ref> She commented about one unnamed television programme, believing it to be \"unbalanced\" and biased, in which \"youngsters were asking questions [and] there was not a single member of the panel who was prepared to say outright that pre-marital relations were wrong. In fact, when a girl asked a clergyman, 'Do you think that fornication is sin?' he replied, 'It depends on what you mean by sin and what you mean by fornication.'\" Whitehouse thought it was a \"big hazard\" for \"present-day children\" that \"so many adults do not stand for anything\", and affirmed that it was the responsibility of the BBC to have a \"missionary role\" to compensate for this social deficiency.<ref name=\"James\"/>\n\nThe Clean Up TV petition, using the manifesto, gained 500,000 signatures. Whitehouse complained in 1993 that during Greene's period at the BBC, \"hardly a week went by without a sniping reference to me\".<ref name=\"Telegraph\"/> Whitehouse's critics responded quickly. The playwright [[David Turner (dramatist)|David Turner]] had heckled her<ref name=\"Barker\"/> at Birmingham Town Hall; his work was criticised during the meeting.<ref name=\"Briggs\"/> Within a few months, an episode of ''[[Swizzlewick]]'', a twice-weekly serial he created, featured a parody of her as Mrs Smallgood.<ref>Steve Fielding [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=QS3LAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA136 ''A State of Play: British Politics on Screen, Stage and Page, from Anthony Trollope to \"The Thick of It\"''\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150220204756/https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=QS3LAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA136 |date=20 February 2015 }}, London & New York; Bloomsbury, 2014, p.136</ref>\n\nIn a speech Greene delivered in 1965, he argued, without naming Whitehouse directly, that the critics of his liberalisation of broadcasting policy would \"attack whatever does not underwrite a set of prior assumptions\", and saw the potential for \"a dangerous form of censorship...which works by causing artists and writers not to take risks\". He defended the right of the BBC \"to be ahead of public opinion\".<ref>Reprinted in Sir Hugh Greene ''The Third Floor Front: A View of Broadcasting in the Sixties'', London: The Bodley Head, 1969, p.100-1</ref> Greene ignored Whitehouse, blocked her from participation in BBC broadcasts, and purchased a painting of Whitehouse with five breasts<ref name=\"Barker\"/> by [[James Lawrence Isherwood]].\n\nThe [[Mediawatch-UK|National Viewers' and Listeners' Association]] (now known as Mediawatch-UK) was launched to succeed CUTV in November 1965,<ref name=\"Winter\"/> replacing what they themselves perceived as CUTV's negativity with an active campaign for legislative change.<ref>Michael Tracey and David Morrison ''Whitehouse'', p.47</ref> The former cabinet minister [[Bill Deedes]], later editor of ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'', supported the group in this period and was the leading speaker at NVALA's founding conference in Birmingham on 30 April 1966,<ref name=\"Thompson36\">Thompson ''Ban This Filth'', p.36-37</ref> and acted as a contact between his parliamentary colleagues and Whitehouse.<ref>Stephen Robinson [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=2KqLM3lMA60C&pg=PT112 ''The Remarkable Lives Of Bill Deedes''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160306071839/https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=2KqLM3lMA60C&pg=PT112 |date=6 March 2016 }}, London: Little, Brown (Hatchette Digital) 2008, p.111-12</ref> [[Quintin Hogg, Baron Hailsham of St Marylebone|Quintin Hogg]], better known as Lord Hailsham,<!-- he disavowed his hereditary peerage in 1963, later he was a life peer. --> was another high-profile politician who gave his support to NVALA and Whitehouse at this time.<ref name=\"Thompson36\"/>\n\nThrough the letters she frequently sent to [[Harold Wilson]], the Prime Minister, Whitehouse caused particular difficulties for civil servants at [[10 Downing Street]].<ref name=\"Travis\">Alan Travis ''Bound and Gagged: A Secret History of Censorship in Britain'', Profile Books, 2000, p.231-2</ref> Reportedly, for some time Downing Street intentionally \"lost\" her letters to avoid having to respond to them.<ref name=\"Travis\" /> It has though been suggested that her contact with parliamentarians helped give her some leverage over the BBC which her own direct communication with the Corporation's executives could not achieve.<ref>Thompson [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=-r7k88pWzYgC&pg=RA2-PT33 ''Ban This Filth''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160307070313/https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=-r7k88pWzYgC&pg=RA2-PT33 |date=7 March 2016 }}, p.33</ref> Although accepting the differences between them, Whitehouse wrote to Wilson on 1 January 1968: \"You have always treated our approaches to you seriously and with courtesy.\"<ref>Thompson [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=-r7k88pWzYgC&pg=RA2-PT39 ''Ban This Filth''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160307070938/https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=-r7k88pWzYgC&pg=RA2-PT39 |date=7 March 2016 }}, p.39</ref>\n\n[[Geoffrey Robertson]], QC, suggests that when Greene left the BBC in 1969, contrary to the view that it was because of disagreements over the appointment of the Conservative [[Charles Hill, Baron Hill of Luton|Lord Hill]] as BBC chairman in 1967, whereby she could be given some credit for his departure, it was more to do with a political struggle between the BBC and Wilson.<ref name=\"ROBQC\">{{Cite news | title= The Mary Whitehouse Story: Mary, quite contrary | last1= Robertson | first1= Geoffrey | newspaper= Times | date= 24 May 2008 | url= http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/arts/tv-radio/article2443029.ece | location= London }} (subscription required) Also see Geoffrey Robertson [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=s0dhdH_VzJ4C&pg=PA136 ''The Justice Game''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160306041255/https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=s0dhdH_VzJ4C&pg=PA136 |date=6 March 2016 }}, London: Vintage, 1999 [1998], p.136</ref> However, Hill was prepared to meet Whitehouse at Broadcasting House.<ref>Robert Hewison ''Too Much: Art and Society in the Sixties, 1960\u201375'', New York: Oxford University Press, 1987, p.33 (Published by Methuen, London in 1986)</ref>\n\n===Television and war===\nWar coverage met with her objections. During his brief period as editor of ''[[Panorama (TV programme)|Panorama]]'' (1965\u201366),<ref>Alan Rosenthal ''The New Documentary in Action: a Casebook in Film Making'', Berkeley & Los Angeles: University of California Press, 1972, p.95, 96</ref> [[Jeremy Isaacs]] received a letter from Whitehouse complaining about his decision to repeat [[Richard Dimbleby]]'s coverage of the liberation of the [[Bergen-Belsen concentration camp|Belsen concentration camp]]. She complained about this \"filth\" being allowed on air as \"it was bound to shock and offend\". In a 1994 interview, Whitehouse continued to maintain that it was \"an awful intrusion\" and \"very off-putting\".<ref>Allison Pearson [https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/television--mary-mary-quite-contrary-1439331.html \"Television: Mary, Mary, quite contrary \"], {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121111162343/http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/television--mary-mary-quite-contrary-1439331.html |date=11 November 2012 }} ''The Independent on Sunday'', 29 May 1994. The interviews with Isaacs and Whitehouse were contained within ''The Late Show: The Mary Whitehouse Story'', which was, according to the [http://ftvdb.bfi.org.uk/sift/title/509525?view=transmission BFI Film & TV database] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121023232005/http://ftvdb.bfi.org.uk/sift/title/509525?view=transmission |date=23 October 2012 }}, transmitted on 23 May 1994. See the BFI site also [http://ftvdb.bfi.org.uk/sift/title/509525?view=synopsis for a synopsis] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121023232012/http://ftvdb.bfi.org.uk/sift/title/509525?view=synopsis |date=23 October 2012 }} of this programme.</ref>\n\nLater in 1965, the decision by the BBC not to broadcast [[Peter Watkins]]' ''[[The War Game]]'' on 6 August 1965 led to Whitehouse writing to Sir Hugh Greene and Harold Wilson on 5 September,<ref name=\"Murphy\">Patrick Murphy and John Cook \"The War Game\" in Ian Aitken [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=4r8cRrzOavEC&pg=PA974 ''The Concise Routledge Encyclopedia of the Documentary Film''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160306122344/https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=4r8cRrzOavEC&pg=PA974 |date=6 March 2016 }}, Abingdon & New York: Routledge, 2013 [2006], p,974</ref> and again to the [[Home Secretary]] [[Frank Soskice, Baron Stow Hill|Frank Soskice]] on 6 October<ref name=\"Thompson30\">Thompson [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=-r7k88pWzYgC&pg=RA2-PT30 ''Ban This Filth''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160307035054/https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=-r7k88pWzYgC&pg=RA2-PT30 |date=7 March 2016 }}, p.30</ref> In her view a decision over whether to broadcast Watkins' film should be taken by the [[Home Office]] rather than the BBC. Nuclear war was \"too serious a matter to be treated as entertainment. For a producer to be allowed, as now appears possible, to prejudice the effectiveness of our Civil Defence Services, or the ability of the British people to re-act with courage, initiative and control in a crisis, surely goes far beyond the responsibility\" which should be given to someone in this role.<ref name=\"Thompson30\"/> The letter was leaked at the time and extracts were published.<ref name=\"Murphy\"/>\n\nThe contemporary coverage of the [[Vietnam War]], \"the first 'television war'\",<ref>A much used description, see for example Daniel Hallin [http://www.museum.tv/eotvsection.php?entrycode=vietnamonte \"Vietnam on Television\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110628203924/http://www.museum.tv/eotvsection.php?entrycode=vietnamonte |date=28 June 2011 }}, The Museum of Broadcast Communications website</ref> demonstrated for Whitehouse that television was \"an ally of pacifism\".<ref name=\"RCN1970\">Mary Whitehouse 'Promoting Violence', Royal College of Nursing in the UK Professional Conference, ''The Violent Society'', 5 April 1970, quoted in Tracey and Morrison ''Whitehouse'', London: Macmillan, 1979, p.86-87, 205, n.27</ref> In a 1970 speech to the [[Royal College of Nursing]] she argued: \"However good the cause ... the horrific effects on men and terrain of modern warfare as seen on the television screen could well sap the will of a nation to safeguard its own freedom, let alone resist the forces of evil abroad.\"<ref name=\"RCN1970\"/> Trying to reconcile this \"pacifism\" with her objection to fictional violence, she saw such news coverage as \"desensitisation\"<ref name=\"RCN1970\"/> in which the media use the \"techniques of violence\" to raise \"impact\" in order \"to satisfy an apparently insatiable demand for realism\".<ref name=\"RCN1970\"/>\n\n===Programmes: comedy and drama from the mid-1960s to 1980===\nThe situation comedy ''[[Till Death Us Do Part]]'' attacked many of the things Whitehouse cherished. She objected to its profane language: \"I doubt if many people would use 121 bloodies in half-an-hour\",<ref name=\"Brown\"/> and \"Bad language coarsens the whole quality of our life. It normalises harsh, often indecent language, which despoils our communication.\"<ref name=\"Brown\"/>\n\nWhitehouse and the NVALA won a libel action against the BBC and its writer [[Johnny Speight]] in July 1967 with a full apology and substantial damages, after Speight implied in a BBC radio interview that the organisation's members and its head were fascists.<ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=2507&dat=19670728&id=HmtAAAAAIBAJ&sjid=bKMMAAAAIBAJ&pg=2186,3589259 \"Damages For Mrs Mary Whitehouse\"], ''Glasgow Herald'', 28 July 1967, p.11</ref><ref name=\"Ward\">Mark Ward [http://www.petford.net/kaleidoscope/a-family-at-war.html \"A Family at War: Till Death Do Us Part\"], {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101012071642/http://www.petford.net/kaleidoscope/a-family-at-war.html |date=12 October 2010 }} ''The Main Event'' (''Kaleidoscope'' brochure) 1996</ref> Shortly after Speight's interview, she was mocked in an episode of the series entitled \"Alf's Dilemma\" (27 February 1967). [[Alf Garnett]] is shown reading her book ''Cleaning Up TV'', and agreeing with every word,<ref name=\"Ward\"/> but the episode ends with the book being burned to exclamations of \"Unclean, unclean\".<ref>Thompson [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=-r7k88pWzYgC&pg=PR12 ''Ban This Filth''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160306062434/https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=-r7k88pWzYgC&pg=PR12 |date=6 March 2016 }}, p.12</ref>\n\nWhitehouse was critical of comedians such as [[Benny Hill]] and his use of dancers; she described [[Dave Allen (comedian)|Dave Allen]] as \"offensive, indecent and embarrassing\" after a comic account of a conversation following sexual intercourse.<ref>Patrick Newley [http://www.thestage.co.uk/features/feature.php/6898/dave-allen Obituary: Dave Allen], {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110611161306/http://www.thestage.co.uk/features/feature.php/6898/dave-allen |date=11 June 2011 }} ''The Stage'', 15 March 2005</ref> In return, comedy writers during this era saw her as possessing humorous potential. [[The Goodies]] comedy team created an episode (\"[[Gender Education]]\", 1971) with the principal objective of irritating her.<ref>{{cite news|last=Brooke-Taylor|first=Tim|url=http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/tv_and_radio/article3984004.ece|title=Why The Goodies had to 'get back' at Mary Whitehouse|work=The Times|date=24 May 2008|accessdate=16 September 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110615185532/http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/tv_and_radio/article3984004.ece|archive-date=15 June 2011|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}} (subscription required)</ref>\n\nWhitehouse criticised the work of [[Dennis Potter]] from ''[[Son of Man (play)|Son of Man]]'' (1969) onwards, arguing that the BBC was at the centre \"of a conspiracy to remove the myth of god from the minds of men\",<ref>Quoted by Boris Ford [https://books.google.com/books?id=z3I_wzri-SUC&pg=PA24&lpg=PA24&dq=%22Mary+Whitehouse%22+conspiracy+left&source=bl&ots=wWvKy6zAwE&sig=lGEiby5o0T3YmxSIlTYhE5PyNbk&hl=en&ei=T3y4TN2aIcjKjAerm8GmDg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=10&ved=0CDMQ6AEwCQ#v=onepage&q=%22Mary%20Whitehouse%22%20conspiracy%20left&f=false ''The Cambridge Cultural History of Britain: Modern Britain''], Cambridge University Press, 1992, p.24</ref> and also ''[[A Clockwork Orange (film)|A Clockwork Orange]]'' (1971). In the case of the violence in ''A Clockwork Orange'', she rejected any attempt to show a 'copycat' correlation in academic studies, but urged its acceptance as a fact arrived at by common sense.<ref>Michael Tracey and David Morrison ''Whitehouse'', p.84</ref> In December 1974, she wrote of the \"deliberate propagation\" of the idea that there is no proof of the effects of television on \"standards and behaviour\". To reject its effect, and its ability to \"declaim or pervert truth, is to deny the potency of communication itself, it is crazily to question the ability of education to affect the social conscience and to train the human mind\".<ref>Mary Whitehouse [http://archive.spectator.co.uk/article/28th-december-1974/14/television \"Television: Controlling the explosive influence\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150514200908/http://archive.spectator.co.uk/article/28th-december-1974/14/television |date=14 May 2015 }}, ''The Spectator'', 28 December 1974, p.14. The page on the website of ''The Spectator'' contains some typographical errors, these have been corrected.</ref>\n\n[[Chuck Berry]]'s [[novelty song]] \"[[My Ding-a-Ling#Critical reception|My Ding-a-Ling]]\" was one of several pop songs to receive Whitehouse's disapproval in this period. She was unsuccessful in trying to persuade the BBC to ban it,<ref>{{cite web|last=Coleman|first=Sarah|title=Morals Campaigner Mary Whitehouse|url=http://www.worldpress.org/europe/0202whitehouse.htm|work=World Press Review|accessdate=13 May 2012|date=February 2002|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120413091328/http://worldpress.org/europe/0202whitehouse.htm|archive-date=13 April 2012|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>See also Ben Thompson (ed.) ''Ban This Filth!: Letters from the Mary Whitehouse Archive'', London: Faber, 2012 cited by  [https://www.theguardian.com/books/2012/oct/26/ban-this-filth-ben-thompson-review \"Ban This Filth!: Letters from the Mary Whitehouse Archive by Ben Thompson \u2013 review\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170113163352/https://www.theguardian.com/books/2012/oct/26/ban-this-filth-ben-thompson-review |date=13 January 2017 }}, ''The Guardian'', 26 October 2012</ref> but her campaign to stop [[Alice Cooper]]'s \"[[School's Out (song)|School's Out]]\" being featured on ''[[Top of the Pops]]'' was successful.<ref>[http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b017pn6z ''Mark Lawson Talks to...'': \"Rock \u2018n\u2019 Roll legend Alice Cooper in conversation with Mark Lawson\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111227191836/http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b017pn6z |date=27 December 2011 }}, BBC Four, November 2011</ref> Cooper sent her a bunch of flowers, since he believed the publicity helped the song to reach number one.<ref>Martin Fletcher [https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/books/reviews/ban-this-filth-letters-from-the-mary-whitehouse-archive-edited-by-ben-thompson-8297791.html \"Ban This Filth! Letters from the Mary Whitehouse Archive, Edited by Ben Thompson\"], {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130121211702/http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/books/reviews/ban-this-filth-letters-from-the-mary-whitehouse-archive-edited-by-ben-thompson-8297791.html |date=21 January 2013 }} ''The Independent'', 10 November 2012</ref> In 1977, one of the regular presenters of ''Top of the Pops'' in this era, [[Jimmy Savile]], won an award from NVALA for his \"wholesome family entertainment\" on ''[[Jim'll Fix It]]''.<ref name=\"Thompson\"/>\n\nThe NVALA had around 150,000 members at its peak,<!-- much cited figure, but unclear when it dates from. --><ref>James Silver [https://www.theguardian.com/media/2007/apr/09/mondaymediasection6 \"The post-Mary Whitehouse experience\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303214652/http://www.theguardian.com/media/2007/apr/09/mondaymediasection6 |date=3 March 2016 }},  ''The Guardian'', 9 April 2007</ref> but claimed 30,000 in April 1977.<ref name=\"Salmans\">Sandra Salmans [https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1755&dat=19770407&id=shIfAAAAIBAJ&sjid=TGcEAAAAIBAJ&pg=5392,3886203 \"British Woman Carries On Crusade Against Sex and Violence in the Media\"], ''Sarasota Herald-Tribune'' (NY Times News Service), 7 April 1977</ref>\n\n===''Doctor Who''===\nThe ''[[Doctor Who]]'' series met with her heaviest disapproval between 1975 and 1977 during which time [[Philip Hinchcliffe]] produced the series.\n\nCriticising ''[[The Seeds of Doom]]'' (1976), in which [[Fourth Doctor|the Doctor]] ([[Tom Baker]]) survives an encounter with a giant carnivorous plant monster, she commented: \"Strangulation\u2014by hand, by claw, by obscene vegetable matter<ref name=\"Stubbs\"/><ref name=\"Sandbrook\">Mary Whitehouse quoted by Dominic Sandbrook ''State of Emergency, The Way We Were: Britain 1970\u201374'', London: Allen Lane, 2010, p.461-62</ref>\u2014is the latest gimmick, sufficiently close up so they get the point. And just for a little variety show the children how to make a [[Molotov cocktail]].\"<ref>The full quote is in Tracey and Morrison, p.85</ref>\n\nFollowing her complaint about ''[[The Deadly Assassin]]'' (broadcast later in 1976), Whitehouse received an apology from [[Director-General of the BBC]] [[Charles Curran (broadcaster)|Sir Charles Curran]].<!-- knighted in 1974. --> A [[Freeze-frame shot|freeze-frame]] cliffhanger ending to the third episode, in which the Doctor appeared to drown, was altered for repeat showings.<ref>Graeme Burk and Robert Smith [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=WT0FAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA148 ''Who's 50: The 50 Doctor Who Stories to Watch Before You Die\u2014An Unofficial Companion''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170419003150/https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=WT0FAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA148 |date=19 April 2017 }}, Toronto: ECW Press, 2013, p.148-49</ref>\n\nThe series' next producer, [[Graham Williams (television producer)|Graham Williams]], was told to lighten the tone and reduce the violence following Whitehouse's complaints.<ref>David J. Howe, Mark Stammers, Stephen Walker. ''Doctor Who: The Seventies''. {{ISBN|978-1852274443}}</ref> Senior television executives commented that at this time her views were not disregarded lightly.<ref name=\"BBC_Obit\">{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/tv_and_radio/1673258.stm |title=\"Whitehouse 'kept TV on its toes'\", BBC obituary, 23 November 2001 |publisher=BBC News |date=23 November 2001 |accessdate=25 July 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080530044339/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/tv_and_radio/1673258.stm |archive-date=30 May 2008 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nShe had described the serial ''[[Genesis of the Daleks]]'' (1975) as consisting of \"teatime brutality for tots\".<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/david-maloney-411226.html | title=David Maloney | work=The Independent | location=London | date=10 August 2006 | accessdate=12 May 2010 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121106091547/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/david-maloney-411226.html | archive-date=6 November 2012 | url-status=live | df=dmy-all }}</ref> Philip Hinchcliffe later remarked, \"I always felt that Mary Whitehouse thought of ''Doctor Who'' as a children's programme, for little children, and it wasn't ... so she was really coming at the show from the wrong starting-point.\"<ref name=\"Serial Thrillers\">Documentary on the DVD \"Doctor Who: [[Pyramids of Mars]]\", BBC Worldwide, 2004</ref>\n\n===After 1980===\nWhitehouse criticised the [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] adventure/drama series ''[[Robin of Sherwood]]'' (1984\u20131986). [[Simon Farquhar]], in an obituary for ''[[The Independent]]'' of the series' creator, [[Richard Carpenter (screenwriter)|Richard Carpenter]], wrote that Whitehouse \"objected to the [show's] relentless slaughter and blasphemous religious elements, but was deftly silenced by Carpenter in public when he introduced himself to her and the audience by saying \"I'm Richard Carpenter, and I'm a professional writer. And you're a professional... what?\"<ref>Simon Farquhar [https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/richard-carpenter-actor-and-writer-famed-for-catweazleand-the-ghosts-of-motley-hall-7547338.html \"Obituary: Richard Carpenter: Actor and writer famed for 'Catweazle' and 'The Ghosts of Motley Hall'\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130110041908/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/richard-carpenter-actor-and-writer-famed-for-catweazleand-the-ghosts-of-motley-hall-7547338.html |date=10 January 2013 }}, ''The Independent'', 10 March 2012</ref>\n\nWithin a week of the launch of [[Channel 4]] in November 1982, Whitehouse was objecting to swear words in the soap opera ''[[Brookside]]'' and two feature films the channel screened, ''[[Woodstock (film)|Woodstock]]'' (1970) and ''[[Network (1976 film)|Network]]'' (1976). On 25 November, she called for the resignation of the channel's chief executive Jeremy Isaacs over a scene in ''Brookside'' \"in which a young thug had tried to force a schoolgirl to have sex with him\", according to an item in ''The Times''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/archive/article/1982-11-26/3/3.html|title=Channel 4 Serial Attacked|work=The Times|location=London|date=26 November 1982|accessdate=1 May 2016|page=3}} {{subscription required}}</ref><ref>Dorothy Hobson [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=X6rdu_oU89wC&pg=PA39 ''Channel 4: The Early Years and the Jeremy Isaacs Legacy''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160306220706/https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=X6rdu_oU89wC&pg=PA39 |date=6 March 2016 }}, London: I.B Tauris, 2008, p.39, 41</ref>\n\nIn 1984, Whitehouse won a case in the [[High Court of Justice|High Court]] against John Whitney, director-general of the [[Independent Broadcasting Authority]], who had failed to forward the feature film ''[[Scum (film)|Scum]]'' (1979) for consideration by other IBA board members to decide if Channel 4 should transmit it. Based on a then-banned BBC television play, the channel had screened the theatrical remake in June 1983.<ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=2507&dat=19840414&id=zspAAAAAIBAJ&sjid=4aUMAAAAIBAJ&pg=3545,3023801 \"Whitehouse wins Scum television film court case\"], ''Glasgow Herald'', 14 April 1984, p.5</ref> The High Court decision was overturned on appeal when it reached the [[House of Lords]].<ref>Lord Thomson of Monifieth \"A Defence of the Independent Broadcasting Authority\" in Peter Catteral [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=5dIqAAAAQBAJ&pg=PT75 ''The Making of Channel 4''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160306014025/https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=5dIqAAAAQBAJ&pg=PT75 |date=6 March 2016 }}, Abingdon: Routledge, 1999 [2013], p.75</ref><ref>[http://www.scotsman.com/news/obituaries/lord-thomson-born-16-january-1921-in-stirling-died-3-october-2008-in-london-aged-87-1-1135792 \"Lord Thomson: Born: 16 January, 1921, in Stirling. Died: 3 October 2008 in London, aged 87\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141017231840/http://www.scotsman.com/news/obituaries/lord-thomson-born-16-january-1921-in-stirling-died-3-october-2008-in-london-aged-87-1-1135792 |date=17 October 2014 }}, ''The Scotsman'', 6 October 2008</ref>\n\nWhitehouse's supporters have asserted that her campaigns helped end [[Channel 4]]'s \"[[Red triangle (Channel 4)|red triangle]]\" series of films in 1986; claimed by Channel 4 to be intended to warn viewers of material liable to cause offence, the broadcasting of these films with the triangle had received criticism from opponents of Whitehouse. She was said to have had a role in the establishment of the Broadcasting Standards Council in 1988,<ref name=\"BBCobit\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/763998.stm|title=Mary Whitehouse: Moral crusader or spoilsport?|publisher=BBC News|date=23 November 2001|accessdate=16 September 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090126140538/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/763998.stm|archive-date=26 January 2009|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> which later became the Broadcasting Standards Commission and was subsumed into the [[Ofcom|Office of Communications]] in 2004.<ref>{{cite news|last=Rees-Mogg|first=William|url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/opinion/columnists/williamreesmogg/article2543538.ece|title=Was Mary Whitehouse right all along?|work=The Times|date=7 June 2010|accessdate=16 September 2015}} (subscription required)</ref>\n\nIn August 1989,<ref name=\"Thompson86\">Thompson ''[[Ban This Filth!]]'', p.86. See also Stuart Jeffries [https://www.theguardian.com/books/2012/oct/26/ban-this-filth-ben-thompson-review \"Ban This Filth!: Letters from the Mary Whitehouse Archive by Ben Thompson \u2013 review\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170113163352/https://www.theguardian.com/books/2012/oct/26/ban-this-filth-ben-thompson-review |date=13 January 2017 }}, ''[[The Guardian]]'', 26 October 2012</ref> in a broadcast of ''In the Psychiatrist's Chair'' on BBC Radio, Whitehouse confused the playwright with his hero in ''[[The Singing Detective]]''. She claimed that [[Dennis Potter]]'s mother had \"committed adultery with a strange man and that the shock of witnessing this had caused her son to be afflicted\"<ref name=\"Thompson86\"/> with [[Psoriatic arthritis|psoriatic arthropathy]]. Potter's mother won substantial damages from the BBC<ref>Mark Lawson [https://www.theguardian.com/film/2003/oct/31/1 \"Watching the detective\"], {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160927180717/https://www.theguardian.com/film/2003/oct/31/1 |date=27 September 2016 }} ''The Guardian'', 31 October 2003.</ref> and ''[[The Listener (magazine)|The Listener]]''.<ref>John R. Cook ''Dennis Potter: A Life on Screen'', Manchester University Press, 1998, p.350, n.82</ref> Whitehouse said she had a blackout at the interview's halfway point and her comments were not intentional.<ref>George W. Brandt (ed.) [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=MOQbnlogBK8C&pg=PA10 ''British Television Drama in the 1980s''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160307030651/https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=MOQbnlogBK8C&pg=PA10 |date=7 March 2016 }}, Cambridge: Cambridge University Press, 1993, p.10</ref>\n\nSome years earlier, Potter had publicly defended Whitehouse on several occasions without agreeing with her arguments.<ref>See for example ''The Guardian'', 16 February 1973, quoted in W. Stephen Gilbert ''The Life and Work of Dennis Potter'', Woodstock, NY: The Overlook Press, 1998, p.145 (originally published as ''Fight and Kick and Bite: Life and Work of Dennis Potter'', London: Hodder and Stoughton, 1995) and Ben Thompson (ed) [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=-r7k88pWzYgC&pg=RA2-PT85 ''Ban This Filth!: Letters From the Mary Whitehouse Archive''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160307063233/https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=-r7k88pWzYgC&pg=RA2-PT85 |date=7 March 2016 }}, p.85</ref>\n\nWhitehouse stepped down as President of the National Viewers and Listeners Association in May 1994. [[Michael Grade]], at the time the Chief Executive of Channel 4, reflected on her career:\n\n{{quote|I don't think she has had any effect at all. She never sees things in context. She will see something in an exploitation video and condemn it in the same breath as she will condemn a Dennis Potter classic. I respect her fortitude in fighting the battles over the years, trying to get her point of view across, but it is a point of view which would have totally destroyed British television if it had become the set of values by which we had commissioned programmes.<ref name=\"Midgley\">Simon Midgley [https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/so-has-the-mary-whitehouse-experience-been-worth-it-simon-midgley-explores-the-legacy-of-the-campaigner-who-is-retiring-at-the-age-of-83-1437749.html \"So has the Mary Whitehouse experience been worth it?\"], ''The Independent'', 22 May 1994</ref>}} At the same time [[William Rees-Mogg]], Chairman of the [[Ofcom|Broadcasting Standards Commission]],<!-- The source says 'Council', as it was originally, but the later name is better remembered. --> commented that she was \"on the whole a force for the good, an important woman\".<ref name=\"BBCobit\"/><ref name=\"Midgley\"/>\n\n==Other campaigns and private prosecutions==\n\n===Permissiveness===\nWhitehouse had taken up other campaigns against the [[permissive society]] by the early 1970s. She objected to the UK edition of ''[[The Little Red Schoolbook]]'', \"a manual of children's rights\"<ref>Jonathon Green ''All Dressed Up: The Sixties and the Counterculture'', London: Pimlico, 1999, p.349 (Originally published by Jonathan Cape in 1998)</ref> on sex, drugs and attitudes to adults, which was successfully prosecuted for obscenity in July 1971. It was originally published in Denmark where, according to Whitehouse, it had done \"incalculable damage\"<ref>''Daily Telegraph'', 29 March 1971, quote as reproduced in Tracey and Morrison, p.134</ref> and was \"a revolutionary primer\",<ref>Whitehouse (1977) p.181, quoted in Tony McEnery ''Swearing in English: Bad Language, Purity and Power From 1586 to the Present Day'', London: Routledge, 2006, p.143</ref> in which \"open rebellion against the 'system', be it school, parents or authority generally, was openly advocated, while children were constantly exhorted to collect evidence against teachers of alleged injustices or anything which was likely to enhance revolution.\"<ref>Whitehouse (1977) p.180, cited in McEnery, p.143</ref> She was \"greatly relieved\u2014for the sake of the children\" at the \u00a350 fine and \u00a3115.50 costs imposed on Richard Handyside and Geoffrey Collins, its publishers,<ref>John Sutherland ''Offensive Literature'', Junction Books, 1982, p.111, 113</ref> who also had works by [[Che Guevara]] and [[Fidel Castro]] on their small list of publications. For Whitehouse it was a \"fundamental right of a child to be a child\" and \"the duty of mature people to ensure that childhood is protected against the inroads of those who would exploit its immaturity for political, social or personal gain.\"<ref>[http://archive.spectator.co.uk/article/7th-august-1971/23/little-red-school-book Letter from Mary Whitehouse] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140402053147/http://archive.spectator.co.uk/article/7th-august-1971/23/little-red-school-book |date=2 April 2014 }}, ''The Spectator'', 6 August 1971, p.23; quoted in Tracey and Morrison, p.138</ref> A modified second edition was allowed to be published in the UK,<ref name=\"Moorhead\">Joanna Moorhead [https://www.theguardian.com/education/2014/jul/08/the-little-red-schoolbook-republished-soren-hansen \"The Little Red Schoolbook \u2013 honest about sex and the need to challenge authority\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170319200323/https://www.theguardian.com/education/2014/jul/08/the-little-red-schoolbook-republished-soren-hansen |date=19 March 2017 }}, ''The Guardian'', 8 July 2014</ref> but the original verdict in the prosecution was sustained in the [[Court of Appeal (England and Wales)|Appeal Court]] and the [[European Court of Human Rights]] (see ''[[Handyside v United Kingdom]]''). An unexpurgated edition of the book, bar one minor cut, was published in the UK during July 2014.<ref name=\"Moorhead\"/>\n\nAlong with the ([[Catholic Church|Catholic]]) Labour peer [[Frank Pakenham, 7th Earl of Longford|Lord Longford]], [[Malcolm Muggeridge]] and [[Cliff Richard]],<ref>Mark Duguid [http://www.screenonline.org.uk/people/id/463770/ \"Whitehouse, Mary (1910\u20132001)\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110628194939/http://www.screenonline.org.uk/people/id/463770/ |date=28 June 2011 }}, BFI screenonline</ref> Whitehouse was a leading figure in the [[Nationwide Festival of Light]], which protested against the commercial exploitation of sex and violence. The Festival's mass \"rally against permissiveness\" in [[Trafalgar Square]] was attended by 50,000 people in September 1971.<ref name=\"Winter\"/> On 25 August that year she had an audience with [[Pope Paul VI]] regarding 'moral pollution',<ref name=\"Brown\"/> in which she attempted to present the pontiff with ''Oz28'' and the ''Little Red School Book'', but these items found their way to an official of the Papal See instead.<ref>Sutherland ''Offensive Literature'', p.116</ref> In his Foreword to Whitehouse's book, ''Who Does She Think She Is?'' (1971), Malcolm Muggeridge wrote: \"It is literally true that but for her the total demolition of all Christian decencies and values in this country would have taken place virtually without a word of public protest.\"<ref name=\"Salmans\"/>\n\nFollowing the release on appeal of the defendants in the [[Oz (magazine)#UK obscenity trials|''Oz'' trial]], \"an unmitigated disaster for the children of our country\",<ref>''Evening Standard'', 6 November 1971, quote as reproduced in Tracey and Morrison, p.135, 207 n.6:14</ref> Whitehouse launched the Nationwide Petition for Public Decency in January 1972, which gained 1.35 million signatures by the time it was presented to [[Edward Heath]] in April 1973.<ref>Dominic Sandbrook ''State of Emergency, The Way We Were: Britain 1970\u201374'', London: Allen Lane, 2010, p.462</ref> She had around 300 speaking engagements during the period of her highest profile.<ref name=\"Barker\"/> The pornographic magazine ''Whitehouse'' was launched in 1975 by publisher [[David Sullivan (businessman)|David Sullivan]].<ref>Roy Greenslade ''Press Gang: How Newspapers Make Profits From Propaganda'', London: Macmillan, 2004 [2003], p.490</ref><ref>Jamie Doward [https://www.theguardian.com/business/2001/may/13/pressandpublishing.media \"Top shelf gathers dust\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160816082645/https://www.theguardian.com/business/2001/may/13/pressandpublishing.media |date=16 August 2016 }}, ''The Observer'', 13 May 2001</ref>\n\n=== Opposition to paedophilia and child pornography ===\nThe [[Paedophile Information Exchange]] had been asked to help the [[Albany Trust]], which received public money, to produce a booklet on paedophilia, which was to have been published by the Trust. Whitehouse mentioned the connection in a speech, asserting that public funds were being used to subsidise paedophile groups, and the Trust withdrew its support for the production of the pamphlet in 1977.<ref>{{cite news|last=Kennedy|first=Dominic|url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/news/uk/article4141527.ece|title=Groups linked to paedophile network given state grants|work=The Times|location=London|date=8 July 2014|accessdate=11 October 2015}} {{subscription required}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title = Lost Freedom: The Landscape of the Child and the British Post-War Settlement|publisher = Oxford University Press|date =28 November 2013|isbn = 9780191665097|language = en|first = Mathew|last = Thomson}}{{page needed|date=October 2015}}</ref> However, PIE itself did not receive public funding.<ref name=\"Mason\">{{cite news|last=Mason|first=Rowena|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2014/jul/07/no-evidence-home-office-funded-paedophile-group|title=No evidence that Home Office funded paedophile group, review finds|work=The Guardian|date=7 July 2014|accessdate=11 October 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303125717/http://www.theguardian.com/society/2014/jul/07/no-evidence-home-office-funded-paedophile-group|archive-date=3 March 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nHer subsequent petition against paedophilia and [[child pornography]] was signed by 1\u00bd million people.<ref name=\"Ost\">{{cite book|last=Ost|first=Suzanne|title=Child Pornography and Sexual Grooming: Legal and Societal Responses|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=MruKQz2ZdKMC&pg=PA84|publisher=Cambridge University Press|location=Cambridge|year=2009|page=84|isbn=978-0521885829|access-date=11 October 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160306204705/https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=MruKQz2ZdKMC&pg=PA84|archive-date=6 March 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Whitehouse urged the Conservative opposition to push for a bill on the subject, in the absence of interest from the Labour government. The [[private member's bill]] proposed by Conservative MP [[Cyril Townsend]] became the [[Protection of Children Act 1978]].<ref name=\"Ost\"/>\n\n===''Gay News'' and other cases of alleged blasphemy===\nWhitehouse took private prosecutions in a number of cases where official action was not forthcoming. The action against ''[[Gay News]]'' in 1977 concerned \"[[The Love That Dares to Speak Its Name]]\", a poem by [[James Kirkup]], a fellow of the [[Royal Society of Literature]],<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/culture-obituaries/books-obituaries/5314221/James-Kirkup.html Obituary: James Kirkup], {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101009172516/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/culture-obituaries/books-obituaries/5314221/James-Kirkup.html |date=9 October 2010 }} ''The Daily Telegraph'', 12 May 2009</ref> the theme of which was the sexual fantasies of a Roman centurion about the body of Jesus Christ. She was the plaintiff in a charge of [[blasphemous libel]] against ''Gay News'' (''[[Whitehouse v Lemon]]''), a trial at the [[Old Bailey]] between 4 and 7 July 1977. It was the first prosecution for the offence since 1922. \"I simply had to protect Our Lord,\" said Whitehouse at the time,<ref name=\"Adam\">Corinna Adam [http://www.newstatesman.com/node/152583 \"Protecting Our Lord\"], {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131207222059/http://www.newstatesman.com/node/152583 |date=7 December 2013 }} ''New Statesman'', 15 July 1977, in a version republished 3 February 2006</ref> Kirkup's poem being in her opinion \"the recrucifixion of Christ by 20th-century weapons\".<ref name=\"KirkupTimes\">{{cite news|url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/opinion/obituaries/article2085242.ece|title= James Kirkup: poet and translator|work=The Times|date=13 May 2009|accessdate=16 September 2015}} (subscription required)</ref> The prosecution counsel [[John Smyth (barrister)|John Smyth]], representing Whitehouse, told the jury: \"It may be said that this is a love poem\u2014it is not, it is a poem about buggery\", while the defence case was that the poem suggested all of mankind could love Jesus Christ.<ref name=\"OTD110777\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/july/11/newsid_2499000/2499721.stm|title=1977: Gay paper guilty of blasphemy, July 11|website=BBC On This Day|accessdate=2 February 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080307121819/http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/july/11/newsid_2499000/2499721.stm|archive-date=7 March 2008|url-status=live|df=dmy-all|date=1977-07-11}}</ref> The Archbishop of Canterbury [[Donald Coggan]] and Cardinal [[Basil Hume]] both declined Whitehouse's invitation for them to give evidence at the trial.<ref>Tracey & Morrison, p.12</ref>\n\nDenis Lemon, the editor and owner of ''Gay News'', published the poem in the 3\u201316 June 1976 issue<ref name=\"Tracey3\">Tracey & Morrison ''Whitehouse'', p.3</ref> on the basis that the \"message and intention of the poem was to celebrate the absolute universality of God's love\".<ref>Peter Burton [https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/obituary-denis-lemon-1415565.html Obituary: Denis Lemon], {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120613180522/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/obituary-denis-lemon-1415565.html |date=13 June 2012 }} ''The Independent'', 23 July 1994</ref> Whitehouse told Michael Tracey and David Morrison, the authors of a book about her: \"I think it shook me more than anything I had seen or come into contact with all the time I had been campaigning. ... I don't think Jesus Christ has ever been more real to me as a person than he was at that particular moment.\"<ref name=\"Tracey3\"/>\n\n''Gay News'' lost the case; the jury decided the case on a 10\u20132 majority.<ref name=\"OTD110777\"/> Lemon and his paper were fined, and Lemon received a nine-month suspended prison sentence.<ref name=\"KirkupTimes\"/> A ''[[The Guardian|Guardian]]'' editorial after the verdict said of the trial: \"No evidence was called, or allowed to be called, about the merits of the poem in literature or theology\", despite the case concerning blasphemy, or to suggest that Kirkup's intention had been to \"scandalise\" which, given the poet's \"list of serious works\", the newspaper thought should have been proven.<ref>Editorial [https://www.theguardian.com/theguardian/2012/jul/13/archive-1977-gay-blasphemy-church-law-religion \"From the archive, 13 July 1977: Editorial: Is the law on blasphemy still relevant?\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170203091315/https://www.theguardian.com/theguardian/2012/jul/13/archive-1977-gay-blasphemy-church-law-religion |date=3 February 2017 }}, ''The Guardian'', 13 July 2012 (reprint)</ref> The judge in at the prosecution, [[Alan King-Hamilton]], QC, had only allowed novelist [[Margaret Drabble]] and journalist [[Bernard Levin]] to appear as \"character\" witnesses for the newspaper.<ref name=\"KirkupTimes\"/> ''[[The Spectator]]'' editorial on 15 July commented: \"The prosecution was perverse, the verdict misguided. As for the punishments, given that this was in effect a test case, they are excessive\" and \"left the law on obscenity even more muddled and confused than it was before, and have served no useful purpose whatsoever, except to delight Mrs Whitehouse\".<ref>[http://archive.spectator.co.uk/article/16th-july-1977/3/bad-news \"Bad news\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131214095856/http://archive.spectator.co.uk/article/16th-july-1977/3/bad-news |date=14 December 2013 }}, ''The Spectator'', 15 July 1977, p.3</ref> The [[Court of Appeal of England and Wales|Court of Appeal]] and the [[Judicial functions of the House of Lords|House of Lords]] dismissed appeals, although Lemon's sentence was overturned.<ref name=\"KirkupTimes\"/>\n\n[[Geoffrey Robertson]], QC, the barrister for ''Gay News'' in the case, described Whitehouse as [[Homophobia|homophobic]] in ''The Times'' in 2008, saying: \"Her fear of homosexuals was visceral\".<ref name=\"ROBQC\"/> He describes the beliefs she reveals in her book, ''Whatever Happened to Sex?'', as \"nonsense\", such as her assertion that \"homosexuality was caused by abnormal parental sex 'during pregnancy or just after'\", saying that for her, \"being gay was like having acne: 'Psychiatric literature proves that 60 per cent of homosexuals who go for treatment get completely cured'\".<ref name=\"ROBQC\"/>\n\nWhitehouse had hoped to use the blasphemy laws against material other than Kirkup's poem, and was interested in pursuing a possible action against allegedly blasphemous content for some time.<ref name=\"Tracey4\">Tracey & Morrison ''Whitehouse'', p.4-5</ref> She had hoped that it could be used as a basis for prosecution if a planned pornographic film on the life of Jesus Christ had been made in Britain. The intended work, containing both homosexual and heterosexual content, was a project by the Danish filmmaker [[Jens J\u00f8rgen Thorsen]]. This time Whitehouse, whose organisation had commissioned a translation of the script, gained more widespread support.<ref>Tracey & Morrison ''Whitehouse'', p.11</ref> NVALA organised a publicity campaign,<ref>Sutherland ''Offensive Litearure'', p.149-50</ref> which resulted in Thorsen's intentions gaining significant public condemnation in September 1976 from leading public figures, including [[Elizabeth II|the Queen]].<ref>John Horton and Susan Mendus (eds.) [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=Zdu5_V_F1TgC&pg=RA2-PA24&lpg=RA2-PA24 ''Aspects of Toleration: Philosophical Studies''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160306120831/https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=Zdu5_V_F1TgC&pg=RA2-PA24&lpg=RA2-PA24 |date=6 March 2016 }}, Abingdon: Routledge, 1985 [2010], p.24</ref> Jensen was forced to abandon his plans.<ref name=\"Tracey4\"/>\n\nWhitehouse and a letter writing campaign from the Festival of Light, after unsuccessfully lobbying the [[British Board of Film Classification|British Board of Film Classification] to refuse the film a certificate, were successful in persuading some councils in Britain to ban screenings of ''[[Monty Python's Life of Brian]]'' (1979) in their areas on unproven grounds that the film is blasphemous.<ref>{{cite news|last=Sellers|first=Richard|url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2003/mar/28/artsfeatures1|title=Welease Bwian<!-- sic. -->|work=The Guardian|date=28 March 2003|accessdate=7 March 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161220140824/https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2003/mar/28/artsfeatures1|archive-date=20 December 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Bhaskar|first=Sanjeev|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/6679546/What-did-Life-of-Brian-ever-do-for-us.html|title=What did 'Life of Brian' ever do for us?|work=The Sunday Telegraph|date=29 November 2009|accessdate=7 March 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170301233425/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/6679546/What-did-Life-of-Brian-ever-do-for-us.html|archive-date=1 March 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Jones|first=Nelson|url=http://www.newstatesman.com/blogs/nelson-jones/2011/08/blasphemy-law-brian-religion|title=The afterlife of Brian|work=New Statesman|date=16 August 2011|accessdate=7 March 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170307205824/http://www.newstatesman.com/blogs/nelson-jones/2011/08/blasphemy-law-brian-religion|archive-date=7 March 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Nearly a decade later, a threatened campaign by Whitehouse against [[Martin Scorsese]]'s ''[[The Last Temptation of Christ (film)|The Last Temptation of Christ]]'' (1988), with the law against blasphemy still in force at the time, failed to materialise.<ref>{{cite news|last=Travis|first=Alan|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2004/oct/18/religion.world|title=Medieval law has had its day|work=The Guardian|date=18 October 2004|accessdate=7 March 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170308050704/https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2004/oct/18/religion.world|archive-date=8 March 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Brooke|first=Michael|url=http://www.screenonline.org.uk/film/id/592689/|title=The Last Temptation of Christ: How the BBFC Dealt With the Threat of a Prosecution for Blasphemy|work=BFI Screenonline|date=2003\u201314|accessdate=7 March 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170308044911/http://www.screenonline.org.uk/film/id/592689/|archive-date=8 March 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===''The Romans in Britain''===\nIn 1982 she pursued a private prosecution against [[Michael Bogdanov]], the director of a [[Royal National Theatre|National Theatre]] production of [[Howard Brenton]]'s ''[[The Romans in Britain]]'', a play that \"drew a direct parallel between the [[Roman conquest of Britain|Roman invasion]] of Celtic Britain in 54 BC and the contemporary British presence in [[Northern Ireland]]\".<ref name=\"Billington\">Michael Billington ''State of the Nation: British Theatre Since 1945'', London: Faber, 2007, p.305-6</ref> The first act contains \"a brief scene\"<ref name=\"Billington\"/> of (simulated) [[Anal sex|anal]] [[rape]]\u2014the Police had visited the production three times and found no basis for legal action.<ref name=\"Brenton\">Howard Brenton [https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2006/jan/28/theatre.stage \"Look back in anger\"], {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170319200503/https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2006/jan/28/theatre.stage |date=19 March 2017 }} ''The Guardian'', 28 January 2006</ref> In the prosecution Whitehouse's counsel claimed Section 13 of the [[Sexual Offences Act 1956]], which described the offence of \"procuring an act of gross indecency\",<ref name=\"LawsonRB\">Mark Lawson [https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2005/oct/28/theatre \"Passion play\"], {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170319200435/https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2005/oct/28/theatre |date=19 March 2017 }} ''The Guardian'', 28 October 2005</ref> was applicable. Because this was a general Act, there was no possibility of defence on the basis of artistic merit, unlike that permitted under the [[Obscene Publications Act 1959]].\n\nSince Whitehouse had not seen the play, the prosecution evidence rested on the testimony of her solicitor, Graham Ross-Cornes, who claimed he saw the actor's penis. However, cross-examination revealed that he had seen a performance of the play from the back row of the stalls, 90 feet from the stage.<ref name=\"LawsonRB\"/><ref name=\"The Justice Game\">Robertson [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=s0dhdH_VzJ4C&pg=PA177 ''The Justice Game''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160306104214/https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=s0dhdH_VzJ4C&pg=PA177 |date=6 March 2016 }}, p.177</ref> [[Jeremy Hutchinson, Baron Hutchinson of Lullington|Lord Hutchinson]], counsel for Bogdanov, was able to demonstrate the nature of the illusion performed on stage.<ref name=\"LawsonRB\"/> This was achieved by suggesting that it might have been the actor's thumb protruding from his fist, rather than his erect penis. The defence had argued that the Act did not apply to the theatre; the judge [[Christopher Staughton|Mr Justice Staughton]] then ruled that it did. After three days,<ref name=\"Billington\"/> the action was withdrawn after the prosecution counsel told Whitehouse that he was unable to continue with the case;<ref name=\"LawsonRB\"/> the litigation was ended by the Attorney General putting forward a plea of ''[[nolle prosequi]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/opinion/obituaries/article4269412.ece|title=Sir Christopher Staughton|work=The Times|date=17 November 2014|accessdate=16 September 2015}} (subscription required)</ref> Both sides claimed a victory; Whitehouse's side asserted that the important legal point had been made with the ruling on the applicability of the Sexual Offences Act, while Bogdanov said it was because she knew that he would not be convicted.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/march/18/newsid_2524000/2524269.stm |title=BBC 'On This Day', 18 March |publisher=BBC News |date=18 March 1967 |accessdate=25 July 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090321130757/http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/march/18/newsid_2524000/2524269.stm |archive-date=21 March 2009 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Whitehouse had to meet \u00a320,000 costs, most of which was paid by an anonymous donor.<ref name=\"Billington\"/>\n\nWhitehouse's account of the trial is recorded in ''A Most Dangerous Woman'' ({{ISBN|0-85648-540-3}}); she wrote that she was of the opinion that the legal point had been established, and they had no wish to criminalise Bogdanov, the play's director.\n\n===Margaret Thatcher's government===\nBy the 1980s, Whitehouse had found a powerful ally in the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] government, particularly in [[Margaret Thatcher]] herself, whose support base partially consisted of Christians and social conservatives. It has been claimed by the Conservative journalist [[Bruce Anderson (columnist)|Bruce Anderson]] that the market orientation of the Thatcher government prejudiced it against Whitehouse in private.<ref>Bruce Anderson [https://www.independent.co.uk/opinion/commentators/bruce-anderson/bruce-anderson-a-life-spent-trying-in-vain-to-preserve-the-suburban-idyll-618069.html \"A life spent trying in vain to preserve the suburban idyll\"], {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110913124456/http://www.independent.co.uk/opinion/commentators/bruce-anderson/bruce-anderson-a-life-spent-trying-in-vain-to-preserve-the-suburban-idyll-618069.html |date=13 September 2011 }} ''The Independent'', 26 November 2001</ref>\n\nIt has been claimed by commentators not necessarily in agreement with her that Whitehouse's efforts played a part in the passage of the [[Protection of Children Act 1978]], the [[Indecent Displays (Control) Act 1981]], which concerned sex shops, and the [[Video Recordings Act 1984]], which banned '[[video nasty|video nasties]]'. A term reportedly coined by Whitehouse,<ref name=\"Holmes\">Andrew Holmes [https://www.theguardian.com/film/2002/jul/05/filmcensorship.artsfeatures \"Let there be blood\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170419003416/https://www.theguardian.com/film/2002/jul/05/filmcensorship.artsfeatures |date=19 April 2017 }}, ''The Guardian'', 5 July 2002</ref> she screened edited highlights from these films for MPs at the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] in late 1983,<ref name=\"Stanley\">Richard Stanley \"Dying Light: An Obituary for the Great British Horror Movie\" in Steve Chibnall and Julian Petley (eds.) ''British Horror Cinema'', London: Routledge, 2002, p.184</ref> which included extracts from ''[[The Evil Dead]]'' (1981) considered by her \"the number one nasty\".<ref name=\"Holmes\"/> It was \"a highly effective means of lobbying the government to introduce tight state controls on the burgeoning video industry\".<ref name=\"Stanley\"/>\n\nAround 1986, papers released in late December 2014 indicate, Whitehouse met with Thatcher on at least two occasions to discuss the possibility of banning [[sex toy]]s using a potential extension of the \"deprave and corrupt\" provision in the Obscene Publications Act 1959.<ref name=\"Tufft\">Ben Tufft [https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/thatcher-wanted-to-ban-sex-toys-using-antipornography-laws-after-pressure-from-campaigners-9949565.html \"Thatcher wanted to ban sex toys using anti-pornography laws after pressure from campaigners\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150101180456/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/thatcher-wanted-to-ban-sex-toys-using-antipornography-laws-after-pressure-from-campaigners-9949565.html |date=1 January 2015 }}, ''The Independent'', 30 December 2014</ref> The plan was abandoned because home secretary [[Leon Brittan]] thought the concept of public taste would be a problematic concept for legal action.<ref name=\"Tufft\"/><ref>Natasha Hinde [http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2014/12/31/sex-toys-ban-margaret-thatcher_n_6399746.html \"Sex Toys V Margaret Thatcher: The Iron Lady Wanted To Ban Them Under Obscenity Laws\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150103232555/http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2014/12/31/sex-toys-ban-margaret-thatcher_n_6399746.html |date=3 January 2015 }}, ''The Huffington Post'', 31 December 2014</ref>\n\n==Later years and assessments of her influence==\nWhitehouse was appointed a [[Commander of the Order of the British Empire|CBE]] in 1980.<ref name=\"Winter\"/> In 1988, she suffered a spinal injury in a fall, which severely curbed her campaigning activities.<ref name=\"Telegraph\"/> Whitehouse retired as president of the NVALA in 1994. She died, aged 91, in a nursing home in [[Colchester]], [[Essex]], on 23 November 2001.<ref name=\"LA Times\" /> Whitehouse is buried in the churchyard of the parish church of St Mary the Virgin at [[Dedham, Essex|Dedham]] in Essex.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ipswichstar.co.uk/news/mourners-pay-tribute-to-mary-whitehouse-1-94847|title=Mourners pay tribute to Mary Whitehouse|date=6 December 2001|website=Ipswich Star|language=en|access-date=17 February 2019}}</ref>\n[[File:Mary Whitehouse grave.jpg|thumb|The grave of Mary Whitehouse's husband, Ernest Raymond Whitehouse]]\n\nThe journalist [[Mary Kenny]] believes \"Mary Whitehouse was a significant figure. Some of her battles were justified, even prophetic. Today her attacks on 'kiddie porn' would be widely supported.\"<ref>Mary Kenny [http://www.spectator.co.uk/coffeehouse/6064488/in-defence-of-mary-whitehouse.thtml \"In defence of Mary Whitehouse\"], {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100815015701/http://www.spectator.co.uk/coffeehouse/6064488/in-defence-of-mary-whitehouse.thtml |date=15 August 2010 }} ''The Spectator'' (blog), 10 June 2010</ref> The academic [[Richard Hoggart]] observed: \"her main focus was on sex, followed by bad language and violence. Odd: if she had reversed the order, she might have been more effective.\"<ref name=\"RHoggart\"/>\n\nWriting in the ''[[Dictionary of National Biography]]'', the philosopher [[Mary Warnock, Baroness Warnock|Mary Warnock]] opined, \"Even if her campaigning did not succeed in 'cleaning up TV', still less in making it more fit to watch in other ways, she was of serious intent, and was an influence for good at a crucial stage in the development both of the [[BBC]] and of [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]]. She was not, as the BBC seemed officially to proclaim, a mere figure of fun.\"<ref name=\"Warnock\"/>\n\nThe papers of the NVALA for 1970\u20131990 have been deposited at the Library<ref>[http://libwww.essex.ac.uk/Archives/nvala.htm NVALA Archive] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100824214807/http://libwww.essex.ac.uk/Archives/nvala.htm |date=24 August 2010 }}, Albert Sloman Library, University of Essex</ref> of the [[University of Essex]].<ref>[http://archiveshub.ac.uk/features/15000.html \"National Viewers' and Listeners' Association\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110929001259/http://archiveshub.ac.uk/features/15000.html |date=29 September 2011 }}, Archive Hub website</ref>\n\nWhitehouse's early campaign and her disagreements with the BBC under [[Hugh Greene|Greene]] were the basis of a drama first broadcast in 2008 entitled ''[[Filth: The Mary Whitehouse Story]]'', written by [[Amanda Coe]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b00bws1h |title=Filth: The Mary Whitehouse Story BBC2 |access-date=24 May 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100530210017/http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b00bws1h |archive-date=30 May 2010 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> [[Julie Walters]] played Whitehouse, [[Alun Armstrong]] played her husband Ernest, and [[Hugh Bonneville]] played Greene.\n\nHer favourite programmes were ''[[Dixon of Dock Green]]'' (winner of NVALA's Best Family Viewing Award in 1967),<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/archive/article/1967-05-19/3/15.html|title=Best Family Viewing Award for ''Dixon''|work=The Times|location=London|date=19 May 1967|accessdate=1 May 2016|page=3}} {{subscription required}}</ref> ''[[Neighbours]]'', and coverage of [[snooker]].<ref name=\"Telegraph\"/><ref name=\"Dowell\">Ben Dowell [https://www.theguardian.com/media/2006/jul/21/channel4.broadcasting \"Mary Whitehouse drama heads for BBC\"], {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160916132104/https://www.theguardian.com/media/2006/jul/21/channel4.broadcasting |date=16 September 2016 }} ''The Guardian'', 21 July 2008</ref> She had privately expressed gratitude to Dennis Potter and the BBC for his television play ''[[Where Adam Stood]]'' in 1976.<ref>Ben Thompson (ed.) ''[[Ban This Filth!]]'' [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=-r7k88pWzYgC&pg=RA2-PT83 p.83-84] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160701091540/https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=-r7k88pWzYgC&pg=RA2-PT83 |date=1 July 2016 }}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Censorship]]\n*[[Pornography]]\n*\"Mary Long\", a song in [[Deep Purple]]'s 1973 album ''[[Who Do We Think We Are]]''\n*\"[[Pigs (Three Different Ones)]]\", a song in [[Pink Floyd]]'s 1977 album [[Animals (Pink Floyd album)|''Animals'']]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* [[Ramsey Campbell]] (1987) \"Turn Off: The Whitehouse Way\" (an account of a public appearance by Mary Whitehouse) in ''Ramsey Campbell, Probably'', PS Publishing, {{ISBN|1-902880-40-4}}\n* Max Caulfield (1976) ''Mary Whitehouse'', Mowbray, {{ISBN|0-264-66190-7}}\n* Mary Whitehouse (1967) ''Cleaning-up TV: From Protest to Participation'', Blandford, ISBN B0000CNC3I\n* Mary Whitehouse (1971) ''Who Does She Think She is?'', New English Library, {{ISBN|0-450-00993-9}}\n* Mary Whitehouse (1977) ''Whatever Happened to Sex?'', Wayland, {{ISBN|0-85340-460-7}} (pbk: Hodder & Stoughton, {{ISBN|0-340-22906-3}})\n* Mary Whitehouse (1982) ''Most Dangerous Woman?'', Lion Hudson, {{ISBN|0-85648-408-3}}\n* Mary Whitehouse (1985) ''Mightier Than the Sword'', Kingsway Publications, {{ISBN|0-86065-382-X}}\n* Mary Whitehouse (1993) ''Quite Contrary: An Autobiography'', Sidgwick & Jackson, {{ISBN|0-283-06202-9}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb name|0925766|Mary Whitehouse}}\n* {{UK National Archives ID}}\n* {{NPG name}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Whitehouse, Mary}}\n[[Category:1910 births]]\n[[Category:2001 deaths]]\n[[Category:Anti-pornography activists]]\n[[Category:British lobbyists]]\n[[Category:Commanders of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:English Christians]]\n[[Category:People from Nuneaton]]\n[[Category:Schoolteachers from Warwickshire]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|the British comedy show or the television film with Julie Walters|The Mary Whitehouse Experience|Filth: The Mary Whitehouse Story}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2016}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name =Mary Whitehouse\n| honorific_suffix = {{postnom|country=GBR|size=100|CBE}}\n|birth_name = Constance Mary Hutcheson\n|birth_date = {{birth date|1910|6|13|df=y}}\n|birth_place = [[Nuneaton|Nuneaton, Warwickshire]], England\n|death_date = {{death date and age|df=yes|2001|11|23|1910|6|13}}\n|death_place = [[Colchester|Colchester, Essex]], England\n|image = Mary Whitehouse on phone.jpg\n| caption = Whitehouse in 1981\n|signature =\n|parents =\n|spouse = {{marriage|Ernest Raymond Whitehouse|1940|2000|end=his death}}\n|children = 3<ref name=\"Udall\">Elizabeth Udall [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/features/3636761/Mary-WhitehouseSometimes-I-denied-she-was-my-mother.html \"Mary Whitehouse: 'Sometimes I denied she was my mother'\"], {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110629215919/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/features/3636761/Mary-WhitehouseSometimes-I-denied-she-was-my-mother.html |date=29 June 2011 }} ''The Daily Telegraph'', 27 May 2008</ref>\n|movement = [[Social conservatism]]<br />[[Nationwide Festival of Light]]\n|organization = [[Mediawatch-uk|National Viewers' and Listeners' Association]]\n|monuments =\n|alma_mater = [[Queens Park High School|Chester City Grammar School]].<br />[[MMU Cheshire|Cheshire County Teacher Training College]]\n|awards =\n}}\n'''Constance Mary Whitehouse''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|CBE}} (n\u00e9e '''Hutcheson'''; 13 June 1910 \u2013 23 November 2001) was a [[British people|British]] [[educator]] and [[Conservatism in the United Kingdom|conservative]] [[activist]]. She campaigned against [[social liberalism]] and the mainstream British media, both of which she accused of encouraging a more [[permissive society]]. She was the founder and first president of the [[Mediawatch-UK|National Viewers' and Listeners' Association]], through which she led a longstanding campaign against the [[BBC]]. A hard-line [[Social conservatism|social conservative]], she was disparagingly termed a [[reactionary]] by her socially liberal opponents. Her motivation derived from her traditional [[Christianity|Christian]] beliefs, her aversion to the rapid social and political changes in British society of the 1960s and her work as a teacher of sex education.<ref name=\"LA Times\">{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2001/nov/26/local/me-8356|title=Mary Whitehouse, 91; Led British TV Cleanup|work=Los Angeles Times|date=26 November 2001|accessdate=5 January 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160306230659/http://articles.latimes.com/2001/nov/26/local/me-8356|archive-date=6 March 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nBorn in [[Nuneaton]], [[Warwickshire]], Whitehouse became an art teacher, at the same time becoming involved in evangelical Christian groups such as the [[Student Christian Movement of Great Britain|Student Christian Movement]] (which became increasingly more liberal leading up to and after a 1928 split with the [[Universities and Colleges Christian Fellowship]]) and [[Moral Re-Armament]]. She became a public figure via the Clean-Up TV pressure group, established in 1964, in which she was the most prominent figure. The following year she founded the National Viewers' and Listeners' Association, using it as a platform to criticise the BBC for what she perceived as a lack of accountability, and excessive use of bad language and portrayals of sex and violence in its programmes. As a result, she became an object of mockery in the media.\n\nDuring the 1970s she broadened her activities, and was a leading figure in the [[Nationwide Festival of Light]], a Christian campaign that gained mass support for a period. She initiated a successful private prosecution against ''[[Gay News]]'' on the grounds of [[blasphemous libel]], the first such case for more than 50 years. Another private prosecution was against the director of the play ''[[The Romans in Britain]]'', which had been performed at the [[Royal National Theatre|National Theatre]].\n\nWhitehouse's campaigns continue to divide opinion. Her critics have accused her of being a highly censorious figure, and her traditional moral convictions brought her into direct conflict with advocates of the [[sexual revolution]], [[feminism]], [[Children's rights#Opposition|children's rights]] and [[LGBT rights in the United Kingdom|gay rights]]. Others see her more positively and believe she was attempting to halt a decline in what they perceived as Britain's moral standards. According to Ben Thompson, the editor of an anthology of Whitehouse-related letters published in 2012: \"From ... feminist anti-pornography campaigns to the executive naming and shaming strategies of [[UK Uncut]], her ideological and tactical influence has been discernible in all sorts of unexpected places in recent years.\"<ref name=\"Thompson\">Ben Thompson [http://www.ft.com/cms/s/2/093c3726-24e1-11e2-86fb-00144feabdc0.html#axzz2Bv5X3utv \"Ban this filth!\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121112141447/http://www.ft.com/cms/s/2/093c3726-24e1-11e2-86fb-00144feabdc0.html#axzz2Bv5X3utv#axzz2Bv5X3utv |date=12 November 2012 }}, ''Financial Times'', 9 November 2012. This article is a reprint of the introduction to Ben Thompson (ed.) ''[[Ban This Filth!: Letters From the Mary Whitehouse Archive]]'', London: [[Faber & Faber]], 2012 {{ISBN|978-0571281497}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nBorn in [[Nuneaton|Nuneaton, Warwickshire]], Whitehouse was the second of four children of a \"less-than-successful businessman\" and a \"necessarily resourceful mother\".<ref name=\"Times\">Obituary, ''[[The Times (United Kingdom)|The Times]]'', 24 November 2001</ref> She won a scholarship to [[Queens Park High School|Chester City Grammar School]],<ref name=\"Telegraph\">[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/culture-obituaries/tv-radio-obituaries/6605110/Mary-Whitehouse.html Obituary], {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100606052212/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/culture-obituaries/tv-radio-obituaries/6605110/Mary-Whitehouse.html |date=6 June 2010 }} ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'', 24 November 2001</ref> where she was keen on hockey and tennis,<ref name=\"Times\"/> and after leaving she did two years of unpaid apprentice teaching at St John's School in [[Chester]], [[Cheshire]]. At the [[Manchester Metropolitan University|Cheshire County Teacher Training College]] in [[Crewe]], Cheshire, specialising in [[secondary school]] art teaching, she was involved with the [[Student Christian Movement of Great Britain|Student Christian Movement]] before qualifying in 1932. She became an art teacher at Lichfield Road School in [[Lichfield]], [[Staffordshire]], where she stayed for eight years.\n\nShe joined the Wolverhampton branch of the [[Oxford Group]], later known<!-- from 1938. --> as [[Moral Re-Armament]] (MRA), in 1935.<ref name=\"Moorehead1977\">{{cite news|last=Moorehead|first=Caroline|url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/archive/article/1977-10-31/8/1.html|title=Mrs Mary Whitehouse: A Certainty That Everything is Either Black or White|work=The Times|location=London|date=31 October 1977|accessdate=1 May 2016|page=8}} {{subscription required}}</ref> At MRA meetings, she met Ernest Raymond Whitehouse; they married in 1940 and remained married until he died in [[Colchester]], [[Essex]], aged 87, in 2000.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.findmypast.com/BirthsMarriagesDeaths.jsp |title=England and Wales Deaths 1984\u20132006 |publisher=Findmypast.com |accessdate=25 July 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090228000620/http://www.findmypast.com/BirthsMarriagesDeaths.jsp |archive-date=28 February 2009 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The couple had five sons, two of whom (twins) died in infancy.<ref name=\"Warnock\">Mary Warnock \"Whitehouse <nowiki>[</nowiki>n\u00e9e Hutcheson<nowiki>]</nowiki>, (Constance) Marywhitehouse, Mary\", ''Oxford Dictionary of National Biography''</ref>\n\nAfter raising her sons in their earliest years, Whitehouse returned to teaching in 1953. That year she broadcast on ''[[Woman's Hour]]'' on the day before the coronation of [[Elizabeth II]] \"as a loyal housewife and subject\" and wrote an extensive article on [[homosexuality]] for ''[[The Sunday Times]]''.<ref name=\"Thompson\"/> According to Thompson this concerned how a mother might \"best avoid inadvertently pressuring her sons towards that particular orientation\", and gained enough attention to be republished as a pamphlet.<ref name=\"Thompson\"/>\n\nShe taught art at Madeley Modern School in [[Madeley, Shropshire]] from 1960, taking responsibility for sex education. Shocked at the moral beliefs of her pupils, she became concerned about what she and many others perceived as declining moral standards in the British media, especially in the [[BBC]].\n\n==Clean Up TV campaign and the NVALA==\n\n===Beginnings===\nWhitehouse began her activism in 1963 with a letter to the [[BBC]]<ref name=\"Brown\">Jonathan Brown [https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/mary-whitehouse-to-some-a-crank-to-others-a-warrior-617910.html \"Mary Whitehouse: To some a crank, to others a warrior\"], {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101001223421/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/mary-whitehouse-to-some-a-crank-to-others-a-warrior-617910.html |date=1 October 2010 }} ''The Independent'', 24 November 2001</ref> requesting to see [[Hugh Greene]], the BBC's [[Director-General of the BBC|Director-General]]. Greene was out of the country at the time, so she accepted an invitation to meet [[Harman Grisewood]], his deputy,<ref>Tracey and Morrison ''Whitehouse'', London & Basingstoke: Macmillan, 1979, p.41 {{ISBN|0-333-23790-0}}</ref> a Roman Catholic who she felt listened to her with understanding.<ref name=\"Briggs\">Asa Briggs ''The History of Broadcasting in the United Kingdom, Volume 5'', Oxford: Oxford University Press, 1995, p.332, 334</ref> Over the next few months though, she continued to be dissatisfied with what she saw on television.\n\nWith Norah Buckland, the wife of a vicar, she launched the Clean Up TV Campaign in January 1964 with a manifesto appealing to the \"women of Britain\". The campaign's first public meeting, on 5 May 1964, was held in [[Birmingham Town Hall|Birmingham's Town Hall]].<ref name=\"Winter\">David Winter [https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/mary-whitehouse-755388.html Obituary], {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110913163055/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/mary-whitehouse-755388.html |date=13 September 2011 }} ''The Independent'', 24 November 2001</ref> Richard Whitehouse, one of her sons, recalled in 2008: \"Coaches arrived from all over the country. Two thousand people poured in and suddenly there was my mother on a podium inspiring them to rapturous applause. Her hands were shaking. But she didn't stop\".<ref name=\"Udall\"/>\n\nAlthough he regularly clashed with Whitehouse, the academic [[Richard Hoggart]] shared some of her opinions and was present on the platform with her at this meeting.<ref name=\"RHoggart\">Richard Hoggart [https://www.theguardian.com/media/2001/nov/24/comment.comment \"Valid arguments lost in an obsession over sex\"], {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170419003224/https://www.theguardian.com/media/2001/nov/24/comment.comment |date=19 April 2017 }} ''The Guardian'', 24 November 2001. Hoggart is mistaken here in thinking he could have referred to Dennis Potter's plays on 5 May 1964, as Potter's earliest work in this form, ''The Confidence Course'', was not transmitted until 24 February 1965.</ref> ''[[The Times]]'' commented the following day: \"Perhaps never before in the history of the Birmingham Town Hall has such a successful meeting been sponsored by such a flimsy organisation\".<ref>''The Times'', 6 May 1964, cited by Tracey and Morrison, p.44</ref>\n\n===Sir Hugh Greene at the BBC===\nGreene, knighted in January 1964,<ref>Michael Tracey ''The Production of Political Television'', London: Routledge & Kegan Paul, 1978, p.159</ref> became her ''[[wikt:b\u00eate noire|b\u00eate noire]]''. He was, according to Whitehouse, \"the devil incarnate\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lewis|first1=Paul|title=Crusader was dubbed Britain's 'Queen of Clean'|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=soVIAAAAIBAJ&sjid=MXADAAAAIBAJ&pg=6209%2C7091403|accessdate=30 March 2016|work=The New York Times|date=20 December 2001}}</ref> who \"more than anybody else ... [was] responsible for the moral collapse in this country\".<ref name=\"Barker\">Dennis Barker [https://www.theguardian.com/media/2001/nov/24/guardianobituaries.obituaries \"Mary Whitehouse: Self-appointed campaigner against the permissive society on television\"], {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170317215956/https://www.theguardian.com/media/2001/nov/24/guardianobituaries.obituaries |date=17 March 2017 }} ''The Guardian'', 24 November 2001</ref> The CUTV manifesto asserted that the BBC under Greene spread \"the propaganda of disbelief, doubt and dirt ... promiscuity, infidelity and drinking\".<ref name=\"Stubbs\">Mary Whitehouse quoted by David Stubbs [https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2008/may/24/features16.theguide12 \"The moral minority\"], {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170419003438/https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2008/may/24/features16.theguide12 |date=19 April 2017 }} ''The Guardian'', 24 May 2008</ref> In place of this, the authors argued, the Corporation's activities should \"encourage and sustain faith in God and bring Him back to the hearts of our family and national life\".<ref>Quoted in Dominic Sandbrook ''White Heat'', London: Little, Brown, 2006, p.544</ref><ref>The full manifesto is quoted by [[Roy Shaw (arts administrator)|Roy Shaw]] in [http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1111/j.1741-2005.1966.tb01015.x/abstract \"Television: Freedom and Responsibility\"], {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121102112240/http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1111/j.1741-2005.1966.tb01015.x/abstract |date=2 November 2012 }} ''New Blackfriars'', no.553, June 1966, p.453</ref> Interviewed by ''[[The Catholic Herald]]'' for its Christmas 1965 issue, Whitehouse thought the BBC loaded its programmes in favour of the 'new morality'.<ref name=\"James\">Ian James [http://archive.catholicherald.co.uk/article/24th-december-1965/5/mrs-mary-whitehouse-co-founder-of-the-clean-up-tel \"MRS. MARY WHITEHOUSE, co-founder of the Clean-up Television Campaign\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140116212629/http://archive.catholicherald.co.uk/article/24th-december-1965/5/mrs-mary-whitehouse-co-founder-of-the-clean-up-tel |date=16 January 2014 }}, ''Catholic Herald'', 24 December 1965</ref> She commented about one unnamed television programme, believing it to be \"unbalanced\" and biased, in which \"youngsters were asking questions [and] there was not a single member of the panel who was prepared to say outright that pre-marital relations were wrong. In fact, when a girl asked a clergyman, 'Do you think that fornication is sin?' he replied, 'It depends on what you mean by sin and what you mean by fornication.'\" Whitehouse thought it was a \"big hazard\" for \"present-day children\" that \"so many adults do not stand for anything\", and affirmed that it was the responsibility of the BBC to have a \"missionary role\" to compensate for this social deficiency.<ref name=\"James\"/>\n\nThe Clean Up TV petition, using the manifesto, gained 500,000 signatures. Whitehouse complained in 1993 that during Greene's period at the BBC, \"hardly a week went by without a sniping reference to me\".<ref name=\"Telegraph\"/> Whitehouse's critics responded quickly. The playwright [[David Turner (dramatist)|David Turner]] had heckled her<ref name=\"Barker\"/> at Birmingham Town Hall; his work was criticised during the meeting.<ref name=\"Briggs\"/> Within a few months, an episode of ''[[Swizzlewick]]'', a twice-weekly serial he created, featured a parody of her as Mrs Smallgood.<ref>Steve Fielding [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=QS3LAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA136 ''A State of Play: British Politics on Screen, Stage and Page, from Anthony Trollope to \"The Thick of It\"''\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150220204756/https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=QS3LAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA136 |date=20 February 2015 }}, London & New York; Bloomsbury, 2014, p.136</ref>\n\nIn a speech Greene delivered in 1965, he argued, without naming Whitehouse directly, that the critics of his liberalisation of broadcasting policy would \"attack whatever does not underwrite a set of prior assumptions\", and saw the potential for \"a dangerous form of censorship...which works by causing artists and writers not to take risks\". He defended the right of the BBC \"to be ahead of public opinion\".<ref>Reprinted in Sir Hugh Greene ''The Third Floor Front: A View of Broadcasting in the Sixties'', London: The Bodley Head, 1969, p.100-1</ref> Greene ignored Whitehouse, blocked her from participation in BBC broadcasts, and purchased a painting of Whitehouse with five breasts<ref name=\"Barker\"/> by [[James Lawrence Isherwood]].\n\nThe [[Mediawatch-UK|National Viewers' and Listeners' Association]] (now known as Mediawatch-UK) was launched to succeed CUTV in November 1965,<ref name=\"Winter\"/> replacing what they themselves perceived as CUTV's negativity with an active campaign for legislative change.<ref>Michael Tracey and David Morrison ''Whitehouse'', p.47</ref> The former cabinet minister [[Bill Deedes]], later editor of ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'', supported the group in this period and was the leading speaker at NVALA's founding conference in Birmingham on 30 April 1966,<ref name=\"Thompson36\">Thompson ''Ban This Filth'', p.36-37</ref> and acted as a contact between his parliamentary colleagues and Whitehouse.<ref>Stephen Robinson [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=2KqLM3lMA60C&pg=PT112 ''The Remarkable Lives Of Bill Deedes''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160306071839/https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=2KqLM3lMA60C&pg=PT112 |date=6 March 2016 }}, London: Little, Brown (Hatchette Digital) 2008, p.111-12</ref> [[Quintin Hogg, Baron Hailsham of St Marylebone|Quintin Hogg]], better known as Lord Hailsham,<!-- he disavowed his hereditary peerage in 1963, later he was a life peer. --> was another high-profile politician who gave his support to NVALA and Whitehouse at this time.<ref name=\"Thompson36\"/>\n\nThrough the letters she frequently sent to [[Harold Wilson]], the Prime Minister, Whitehouse caused particular difficulties for civil servants at [[10 Downing Street]].<ref name=\"Travis\">Alan Travis ''Bound and Gagged: A Secret History of Censorship in Britain'', Profile Books, 2000, p.231-2</ref> Reportedly, for some time Downing Street intentionally \"lost\" her letters to avoid having to respond to them.<ref name=\"Travis\" /> It has though been suggested that her contact with parliamentarians helped give her some leverage over the BBC which her own direct communication with the Corporation's executives could not achieve.<ref>Thompson [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=-r7k88pWzYgC&pg=RA2-PT33 ''Ban This Filth''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160307070313/https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=-r7k88pWzYgC&pg=RA2-PT33 |date=7 March 2016 }}, p.33</ref> Although accepting the differences between them, Whitehouse wrote to Wilson on 1 January 1968: \"You have always treated our approaches to you seriously and with courtesy.\"<ref>Thompson [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=-r7k88pWzYgC&pg=RA2-PT39 ''Ban This Filth''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160307070938/https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=-r7k88pWzYgC&pg=RA2-PT39 |date=7 March 2016 }}, p.39</ref>\n\n[[Geoffrey Robertson]], QC, suggests that when Greene left the BBC in 1969, contrary to the view that it was because of disagreements over the appointment of the Conservative [[Charles Hill, Baron Hill of Luton|Lord Hill]] as BBC chairman in 1967, whereby she could be given some credit for his departure, it was more to do with a political struggle between the BBC and Wilson.<ref name=\"ROBQC\">{{Cite news | title= The Mary Whitehouse Story: Mary, quite contrary | last1= Robertson | first1= Geoffrey | newspaper= Times | date= 24 May 2008 | url= http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/arts/tv-radio/article2443029.ece | location= London }} (subscription required) Also see Geoffrey Robertson [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=s0dhdH_VzJ4C&pg=PA136 ''The Justice Game''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160306041255/https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=s0dhdH_VzJ4C&pg=PA136 |date=6 March 2016 }}, London: Vintage, 1999 [1998], p.136</ref> However, Hill was prepared to meet Whitehouse at Broadcasting House.<ref>Robert Hewison ''Too Much: Art and Society in the Sixties, 1960\u201375'', New York: Oxford University Press, 1987, p.33 (Published by Methuen, London in 1986)</ref>\n\n===Television and war===\nWar coverage met with her objections. During his brief period as editor of ''[[Panorama (TV programme)|Panorama]]'' (1965\u201366),<ref>Alan Rosenthal ''The New Documentary in Action: a Casebook in Film Making'', Berkeley & Los Angeles: University of California Press, 1972, p.95, 96</ref> [[Jeremy Isaacs]] received a letter from Whitehouse complaining about his decision to repeat [[Richard Dimbleby]]'s coverage of the liberation of the [[Bergen-Belsen concentration camp|Belsen concentration camp]]. She complained about this \"filth\" being allowed on air as \"it was bound to shock and offend\". In a 1994 interview, Whitehouse continued to maintain that it was \"an awful intrusion\" and \"very off-putting\".<ref>Allison Pearson [https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/television--mary-mary-quite-contrary-1439331.html \"Television: Mary, Mary, quite contrary \"], {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121111162343/http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/television--mary-mary-quite-contrary-1439331.html |date=11 November 2012 }} ''The Independent on Sunday'', 29 May 1994. The interviews with Isaacs and Whitehouse were contained within ''The Late Show: The Mary Whitehouse Story'', which was, according to the [http://ftvdb.bfi.org.uk/sift/title/509525?view=transmission BFI Film & TV database] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121023232005/http://ftvdb.bfi.org.uk/sift/title/509525?view=transmission |date=23 October 2012 }}, transmitted on 23 May 1994. See the BFI site also [http://ftvdb.bfi.org.uk/sift/title/509525?view=synopsis for a synopsis] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121023232012/http://ftvdb.bfi.org.uk/sift/title/509525?view=synopsis |date=23 October 2012 }} of this programme.</ref>\n\nLater in 1965, the decision by the BBC not to broadcast [[Peter Watkins]]' ''[[The War Game]]'' on 6 August 1965 led to Whitehouse writing to Sir Hugh Greene and Harold Wilson on 5 September,<ref name=\"Murphy\">Patrick Murphy and John Cook \"The War Game\" in Ian Aitken [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=4r8cRrzOavEC&pg=PA974 ''The Concise Routledge Encyclopedia of the Documentary Film''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160306122344/https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=4r8cRrzOavEC&pg=PA974 |date=6 March 2016 }}, Abingdon & New York: Routledge, 2013 [2006], p,974</ref> and again to the [[Home Secretary]] [[Frank Soskice, Baron Stow Hill|Frank Soskice]] on 6 October<ref name=\"Thompson30\">Thompson [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=-r7k88pWzYgC&pg=RA2-PT30 ''Ban This Filth''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160307035054/https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=-r7k88pWzYgC&pg=RA2-PT30 |date=7 March 2016 }}, p.30</ref> In her view a decision over whether to broadcast Watkins' film should be taken by the [[Home Office]] rather than the BBC. Nuclear war was \"too serious a matter to be treated as entertainment. For a producer to be allowed, as now appears possible, to prejudice the effectiveness of our Civil Defence Services, or the ability of the British people to re-act with courage, initiative and control in a crisis, surely goes far beyond the responsibility\" which should be given to someone in this role.<ref name=\"Thompson30\"/> The letter was leaked at the time and extracts were published.<ref name=\"Murphy\"/>\n\nThe contemporary coverage of the [[Vietnam War]], \"the first 'television war'\",<ref>A much used description, see for example Daniel Hallin [http://www.museum.tv/eotvsection.php?entrycode=vietnamonte \"Vietnam on Television\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110628203924/http://www.museum.tv/eotvsection.php?entrycode=vietnamonte |date=28 June 2011 }}, The Museum of Broadcast Communications website</ref> demonstrated for Whitehouse that television was \"an ally of pacifism\".<ref name=\"RCN1970\">Mary Whitehouse 'Promoting Violence', Royal College of Nursing in the UK Professional Conference, ''The Violent Society'', 5 April 1970, quoted in Tracey and Morrison ''Whitehouse'', London: Macmillan, 1979, p.86-87, 205, n.27</ref> In a 1970 speech to the [[Royal College of Nursing]] she argued: \"However good the cause ... the horrific effects on men and terrain of modern warfare as seen on the television screen could well sap the will of a nation to safeguard its own freedom, let alone resist the forces of evil abroad.\"<ref name=\"RCN1970\"/> Trying to reconcile this \"pacifism\" with her objection to fictional violence, she saw such news coverage as \"desensitisation\"<ref name=\"RCN1970\"/> in which the media use the \"techniques of violence\" to raise \"impact\" in order \"to satisfy an apparently insatiable demand for realism\".<ref name=\"RCN1970\"/>\n\n===Programmes: comedy and drama from the mid-1960s to 1980===\nThe situation comedy ''[[Till Death Us Do Part]]'' attacked many of the things Whitehouse cherished. She objected to its profane language: \"I doubt if many people would use 121 bloodies in half-an-hour\",<ref name=\"Brown\"/> and \"Bad language coarsens the whole quality of our life. It normalises harsh, often indecent language, which despoils our communication.\"<ref name=\"Brown\"/>\n\nWhitehouse and the NVALA won a libel action against the BBC and its writer [[Johnny Speight]] in July 1967 with a full apology and substantial damages, after Speight implied in a BBC radio interview that the organisation's members and its head were fascists.<ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=2507&dat=19670728&id=HmtAAAAAIBAJ&sjid=bKMMAAAAIBAJ&pg=2186,3589259 \"Damages For Mrs Mary Whitehouse\"], ''Glasgow Herald'', 28 July 1967, p.11</ref><ref name=\"Ward\">Mark Ward [http://www.petford.net/kaleidoscope/a-family-at-war.html \"A Family at War: Till Death Do Us Part\"], {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101012071642/http://www.petford.net/kaleidoscope/a-family-at-war.html |date=12 October 2010 }} ''The Main Event'' (''Kaleidoscope'' brochure) 1996</ref> Shortly after Speight's interview, she was mocked in an episode of the series entitled \"Alf's Dilemma\" (27 February 1967). [[Alf Garnett]] is shown reading her book ''Cleaning Up TV'', and agreeing with every word,<ref name=\"Ward\"/> but the episode ends with the book being burned to exclamations of \"Unclean, unclean\".<ref>Thompson [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=-r7k88pWzYgC&pg=PR12 ''Ban This Filth''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160306062434/https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=-r7k88pWzYgC&pg=PR12 |date=6 March 2016 }}, p.12</ref>\n\nWhitehouse was critical of comedians such as [[Benny Hill]] and his use of dancers; she described [[Dave Allen (comedian)|Dave Allen]] as \"offensive, indecent and embarrassing\" after a comic account of a conversation following sexual intercourse.<ref>Patrick Newley [http://www.thestage.co.uk/features/feature.php/6898/dave-allen Obituary: Dave Allen], {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110611161306/http://www.thestage.co.uk/features/feature.php/6898/dave-allen |date=11 June 2011 }} ''The Stage'', 15 March 2005</ref> In return, comedy writers during this era saw her as possessing humorous potential. [[The Goodies]] comedy team created an episode (\"[[Gender Education]]\", 1971) with the principal objective of irritating her.<ref>{{cite news|last=Brooke-Taylor|first=Tim|url=http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/tv_and_radio/article3984004.ece|title=Why The Goodies had to 'get back' at Mary Whitehouse|work=The Times|date=24 May 2008|accessdate=16 September 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110615185532/http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/tv_and_radio/article3984004.ece|archive-date=15 June 2011|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}} (subscription required)</ref>\n\nWhitehouse criticised the work of [[Dennis Potter]] from ''[[Son of Man (play)|Son of Man]]'' (1969) onwards, arguing that the BBC was at the centre \"of a conspiracy to remove the myth of god from the minds of men\",<ref>Quoted by Boris Ford [https://books.google.com/books?id=z3I_wzri-SUC&pg=PA24&lpg=PA24&dq=%22Mary+Whitehouse%22+conspiracy+left&source=bl&ots=wWvKy6zAwE&sig=lGEiby5o0T3YmxSIlTYhE5PyNbk&hl=en&ei=T3y4TN2aIcjKjAerm8GmDg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=10&ved=0CDMQ6AEwCQ#v=onepage&q=%22Mary%20Whitehouse%22%20conspiracy%20left&f=false ''The Cambridge Cultural History of Britain: Modern Britain''], Cambridge University Press, 1992, p.24</ref> and also ''[[A Clockwork Orange (film)|A Clockwork Orange]]'' (1971). In the case of the violence in ''A Clockwork Orange'', she rejected any attempt to show a 'copycat' correlation in academic studies, but urged its acceptance as a fact arrived at by common sense.<ref>Michael Tracey and David Morrison ''Whitehouse'', p.84</ref> In December 1974, she wrote of the \"deliberate propagation\" of the idea that there is no proof of the effects of television on \"standards and behaviour\". To reject its effect, and its ability to \"declaim or pervert truth, is to deny the potency of communication itself, it is crazily to question the ability of education to affect the social conscience and to train the human mind\".<ref>Mary Whitehouse [http://archive.spectator.co.uk/article/28th-december-1974/14/television \"Television: Controlling the explosive influence\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150514200908/http://archive.spectator.co.uk/article/28th-december-1974/14/television |date=14 May 2015 }}, ''The Spectator'', 28 December 1974, p.14. The page on the website of ''The Spectator'' contains some typographical errors, these have been corrected.</ref>\n\n[[Chuck Berry]]'s [[novelty song]] \"[[My Ding-a-Ling#Critical reception|My Ding-a-Ling]]\" was one of several pop songs to receive Whitehouse's disapproval in this period. She was unsuccessful in trying to persuade the BBC to ban it,<ref>{{cite web|last=Coleman|first=Sarah|title=Morals Campaigner Mary Whitehouse|url=http://www.worldpress.org/europe/0202whitehouse.htm|work=World Press Review|accessdate=13 May 2012|date=February 2002|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120413091328/http://worldpress.org/europe/0202whitehouse.htm|archive-date=13 April 2012|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>See also Ben Thompson (ed.) ''Ban This Filth!: Letters from the Mary Whitehouse Archive'', London: Faber, 2012 cited by  [https://www.theguardian.com/books/2012/oct/26/ban-this-filth-ben-thompson-review \"Ban This Filth!: Letters from the Mary Whitehouse Archive by Ben Thompson \u2013 review\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170113163352/https://www.theguardian.com/books/2012/oct/26/ban-this-filth-ben-thompson-review |date=13 January 2017 }}, ''The Guardian'', 26 October 2012</ref> but her campaign to stop [[Alice Cooper]]'s \"[[School's Out (song)|School's Out]]\" being featured on ''[[Top of the Pops]]'' was successful.<ref>[http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b017pn6z ''Mark Lawson Talks to...'': \"Rock \u2018n\u2019 Roll legend Alice Cooper in conversation with Mark Lawson\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111227191836/http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b017pn6z |date=27 December 2011 }}, BBC Four, November 2011</ref> Cooper sent her a bunch of flowers, since he believed the publicity helped the song to reach number one.<ref>Martin Fletcher [https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/books/reviews/ban-this-filth-letters-from-the-mary-whitehouse-archive-edited-by-ben-thompson-8297791.html \"Ban This Filth! Letters from the Mary Whitehouse Archive, Edited by Ben Thompson\"], {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130121211702/http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/books/reviews/ban-this-filth-letters-from-the-mary-whitehouse-archive-edited-by-ben-thompson-8297791.html |date=21 January 2013 }} ''The Independent'', 10 November 2012</ref> In 1977, one of the regular presenters of ''Top of the Pops'' in this era, [[Jimmy Savile]], won an award from NVALA for his \"wholesome family entertainment\" on ''[[Jim'll Fix It]]''.<ref name=\"Thompson\"/>\n\nThe NVALA had around 150,000 members at its peak,<!-- much cited figure, but unclear when it dates from. --><ref>James Silver [https://www.theguardian.com/media/2007/apr/09/mondaymediasection6 \"The post-Mary Whitehouse experience\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303214652/http://www.theguardian.com/media/2007/apr/09/mondaymediasection6 |date=3 March 2016 }},  ''The Guardian'', 9 April 2007</ref> but claimed 30,000 in April 1977.<ref name=\"Salmans\">Sandra Salmans [https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1755&dat=19770407&id=shIfAAAAIBAJ&sjid=TGcEAAAAIBAJ&pg=5392,3886203 \"British Woman Carries On Crusade Against Sex and Violence in the Media\"], ''Sarasota Herald-Tribune'' (NY Times News Service), 7 April 1977</ref>\n\n===''Doctor Who''===\nThe ''[[Doctor Who]]'' series met with her heaviest disapproval between 1975 and 1977 during which time [[Philip Hinchcliffe]] produced the series.\n\nCriticising ''[[The Seeds of Doom]]'' (1976), in which [[Fourth Doctor|the Doctor]] ([[Tom Baker]]) survives an encounter with a giant carnivorous plant monster, she commented: \"Strangulation\u2014by hand, by claw, by obscene vegetable matter<ref name=\"Stubbs\"/><ref name=\"Sandbrook\">Mary Whitehouse quoted by Dominic Sandbrook ''State of Emergency, The Way We Were: Britain 1970\u201374'', London: Allen Lane, 2010, p.461-62</ref>\u2014is the latest gimmick, sufficiently close up so they get the point. And just for a little variety show the children how to make a [[Molotov cocktail]].\"<ref>The full quote is in Tracey and Morrison, p.85</ref>\n\nFollowing her complaint about ''[[The Deadly Assassin]]'' (broadcast later in 1976), Whitehouse received an apology from [[Director-General of the BBC]] [[Charles Curran (broadcaster)|Sir Charles Curran]].<!-- knighted in 1974. --> A [[Freeze-frame shot|freeze-frame]] cliffhanger ending to the third episode, in which the Doctor appeared to drown, was altered for repeat showings.<ref>Graeme Burk and Robert Smith [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=WT0FAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA148 ''Who's 50: The 50 Doctor Who Stories to Watch Before You Die\u2014An Unofficial Companion''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170419003150/https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=WT0FAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA148 |date=19 April 2017 }}, Toronto: ECW Press, 2013, p.148-49</ref>\n\nThe series' next producer, [[Graham Williams (television producer)|Graham Williams]], was told to lighten the tone and reduce the violence following Whitehouse's complaints.<ref>David J. Howe, Mark Stammers, Stephen Walker. ''Doctor Who: The Seventies''. {{ISBN|978-1852274443}}</ref> Senior television executives commented that at this time her views were not disregarded lightly.<ref name=\"BBC_Obit\">{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/tv_and_radio/1673258.stm |title=\"Whitehouse 'kept TV on its toes'\", BBC obituary, 23 November 2001 |publisher=BBC News |date=23 November 2001 |accessdate=25 July 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080530044339/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/tv_and_radio/1673258.stm |archive-date=30 May 2008 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nShe had described the serial ''[[Genesis of the Daleks]]'' (1975) as consisting of \"teatime brutality for tots\".<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/david-maloney-411226.html | title=David Maloney | work=The Independent | location=London | date=10 August 2006 | accessdate=12 May 2010 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121106091547/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/david-maloney-411226.html | archive-date=6 November 2012 | url-status=live | df=dmy-all }}</ref> Philip Hinchcliffe later remarked, \"I always felt that Mary Whitehouse thought of ''Doctor Who'' as a children's programme, for little children, and it wasn't ... so she was really coming at the show from the wrong starting-point.\"<ref name=\"Serial Thrillers\">Documentary on the DVD \"Doctor Who: [[Pyramids of Mars]]\", BBC Worldwide, 2004</ref>\n\n===After 1980===\nWhitehouse criticised the [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] adventure/drama series ''[[Robin of Sherwood]]'' (1984\u20131986). [[Simon Farquhar]], in an obituary for ''[[The Independent]]'' of the series' creator, [[Richard Carpenter (screenwriter)|Richard Carpenter]], wrote that Whitehouse \"objected to the [show's] relentless slaughter and blasphemous religious elements, but was deftly silenced by Carpenter in public when he introduced himself to her and the audience by saying \"I'm Richard Carpenter, and I'm a professional writer. And you're a professional... what?\"<ref>Simon Farquhar [https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/richard-carpenter-actor-and-writer-famed-for-catweazleand-the-ghosts-of-motley-hall-7547338.html \"Obituary: Richard Carpenter: Actor and writer famed for 'Catweazle' and 'The Ghosts of Motley Hall'\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130110041908/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/richard-carpenter-actor-and-writer-famed-for-catweazleand-the-ghosts-of-motley-hall-7547338.html |date=10 January 2013 }}, ''The Independent'', 10 March 2012</ref>\n\nWithin a week of the launch of [[Channel 4]] in November 1982, Whitehouse was objecting to swear words in the soap opera ''[[Brookside]]'' and two feature films the channel screened, ''[[Woodstock (film)|Woodstock]]'' (1970) and ''[[Network (1976 film)|Network]]'' (1976). On 25 November, she called for the resignation of the channel's chief executive Jeremy Isaacs over a scene in ''Brookside'' \"in which a young thug had tried to force a schoolgirl to have sex with him\", according to an item in ''The Times''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/archive/article/1982-11-26/3/3.html|title=Channel 4 Serial Attacked|work=The Times|location=London|date=26 November 1982|accessdate=1 May 2016|page=3}} {{subscription required}}</ref><ref>Dorothy Hobson [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=X6rdu_oU89wC&pg=PA39 ''Channel 4: The Early Years and the Jeremy Isaacs Legacy''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160306220706/https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=X6rdu_oU89wC&pg=PA39 |date=6 March 2016 }}, London: I.B Tauris, 2008, p.39, 41</ref>\n\nIn 1984, Whitehouse won a case in the [[High Court of Justice|High Court]] against John Whitney, director-general of the [[Independent Broadcasting Authority]], who had failed to forward the feature film ''[[Scum (film)|Scum]]'' (1979) for consideration by other IBA board members to decide if Channel 4 should transmit it. Based on a then-banned BBC television play, the channel had screened the theatrical remake in June 1983.<ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=2507&dat=19840414&id=zspAAAAAIBAJ&sjid=4aUMAAAAIBAJ&pg=3545,3023801 \"Whitehouse wins Scum television film court case\"], ''Glasgow Herald'', 14 April 1984, p.5</ref> The High Court decision was overturned on appeal when it reached the [[House of Lords]].<ref>Lord Thomson of Monifieth \"A Defence of the Independent Broadcasting Authority\" in Peter Catteral [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=5dIqAAAAQBAJ&pg=PT75 ''The Making of Channel 4''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160306014025/https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=5dIqAAAAQBAJ&pg=PT75 |date=6 March 2016 }}, Abingdon: Routledge, 1999 [2013], p.75</ref><ref>[http://www.scotsman.com/news/obituaries/lord-thomson-born-16-january-1921-in-stirling-died-3-october-2008-in-london-aged-87-1-1135792 \"Lord Thomson: Born: 16 January, 1921, in Stirling. Died: 3 October 2008 in London, aged 87\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141017231840/http://www.scotsman.com/news/obituaries/lord-thomson-born-16-january-1921-in-stirling-died-3-october-2008-in-london-aged-87-1-1135792 |date=17 October 2014 }}, ''The Scotsman'', 6 October 2008</ref>\n\nWhitehouse's supporters have asserted that her campaigns helped end [[Channel 4]]'s \"[[Red triangle (Channel 4)|red triangle]]\" series of films in 1986; claimed by Channel 4 to be intended to warn viewers of material liable to cause offence, the broadcasting of these films with the triangle had received criticism from opponents of Whitehouse. She was said to have had a role in the establishment of the Broadcasting Standards Council in 1988,<ref name=\"BBCobit\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/763998.stm|title=Mary Whitehouse: Moral crusader or spoilsport?|publisher=BBC News|date=23 November 2001|accessdate=16 September 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090126140538/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/763998.stm|archive-date=26 January 2009|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> which later became the Broadcasting Standards Commission and was subsumed into the [[Ofcom|Office of Communications]] in 2004.<ref>{{cite news|last=Rees-Mogg|first=William|url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/opinion/columnists/williamreesmogg/article2543538.ece|title=Was Mary Whitehouse right all along?|work=The Times|date=7 June 2010|accessdate=16 September 2015}} (subscription required)</ref>\n\nIn August 1989,<ref name=\"Thompson86\">Thompson ''[[Ban This Filth!]]'', p.86. See also Stuart Jeffries [https://www.theguardian.com/books/2012/oct/26/ban-this-filth-ben-thompson-review \"Ban This Filth!: Letters from the Mary Whitehouse Archive by Ben Thompson \u2013 review\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170113163352/https://www.theguardian.com/books/2012/oct/26/ban-this-filth-ben-thompson-review |date=13 January 2017 }}, ''[[The Guardian]]'', 26 October 2012</ref> in a broadcast of ''In the Psychiatrist's Chair'' on BBC Radio, Whitehouse confused the playwright with his hero in ''[[The Singing Detective]]''. She claimed that [[Dennis Potter]]'s mother had \"committed adultery with a strange man and that the shock of witnessing this had caused her son to be afflicted\"<ref name=\"Thompson86\"/> with [[Psoriatic arthritis|psoriatic arthropathy]]. Potter's mother won substantial damages from the BBC<ref>Mark Lawson [https://www.theguardian.com/film/2003/oct/31/1 \"Watching the detective\"], {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160927180717/https://www.theguardian.com/film/2003/oct/31/1 |date=27 September 2016 }} ''The Guardian'', 31 October 2003.</ref> and ''[[The Listener (magazine)|The Listener]]''.<ref>John R. Cook ''Dennis Potter: A Life on Screen'', Manchester University Press, 1998, p.350, n.82</ref> Whitehouse said she had a blackout at the interview's halfway point and her comments were not intentional.<ref>George W. Brandt (ed.) [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=MOQbnlogBK8C&pg=PA10 ''British Television Drama in the 1980s''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160307030651/https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=MOQbnlogBK8C&pg=PA10 |date=7 March 2016 }}, Cambridge: Cambridge University Press, 1993, p.10</ref>\n\nSome years earlier, Potter had publicly defended Whitehouse on several occasions without agreeing with her arguments.<ref>See for example ''The Guardian'', 16 February 1973, quoted in W. Stephen Gilbert ''The Life and Work of Dennis Potter'', Woodstock, NY: The Overlook Press, 1998, p.145 (originally published as ''Fight and Kick and Bite: Life and Work of Dennis Potter'', London: Hodder and Stoughton, 1995) and Ben Thompson (ed) [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=-r7k88pWzYgC&pg=RA2-PT85 ''Ban This Filth!: Letters From the Mary Whitehouse Archive''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160307063233/https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=-r7k88pWzYgC&pg=RA2-PT85 |date=7 March 2016 }}, p.85</ref>\n\nWhitehouse stepped down as President of the National Viewers and Listeners Association in May 1994. [[Michael Grade]], at the time the Chief Executive of Channel 4, reflected on her career:\n\n{{quote|I don't think she has had any effect at all. She never sees things in context. She will see something in an exploitation video and condemn it in the same breath as she will condemn a Dennis Potter classic. I respect her fortitude in fighting the battles over the years, trying to get her point of view across, but it is a point of view which would have totally destroyed British television if it had become the set of values by which we had commissioned programmes.<ref name=\"Midgley\">Simon Midgley [https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/so-has-the-mary-whitehouse-experience-been-worth-it-simon-midgley-explores-the-legacy-of-the-campaigner-who-is-retiring-at-the-age-of-83-1437749.html \"So has the Mary Whitehouse experience been worth it?\"], ''The Independent'', 22 May 1994</ref>}} At the same time [[William Rees-Mogg]], Chairman of the [[Ofcom|Broadcasting Standards Commission]],<!-- The source says 'Council', as it was originally, but the later name is better remembered. --> commented that she was \"on the whole a force for the good, an important woman\".<ref name=\"BBCobit\"/><ref name=\"Midgley\"/>\n\n==Other campaigns and private prosecutions==\n\n===Permissiveness===\nWhitehouse had taken up other campaigns against the [[permissive society]] by the early 1970s. She objected to the UK edition of ''[[The Little Red Schoolbook]]'', \"a manual of children's rights\"<ref>Jonathon Green ''All Dressed Up: The Sixties and the Counterculture'', London: Pimlico, 1999, p.349 (Originally published by Jonathan Cape in 1998)</ref> on sex, drugs and attitudes to adults, which was successfully prosecuted for obscenity in July 1971. It was originally published in Denmark where, according to Whitehouse, it had done \"incalculable damage\"<ref>''Daily Telegraph'', 29 March 1971, quote as reproduced in Tracey and Morrison, p.134</ref> and was \"a revolutionary primer\",<ref>Whitehouse (1977) p.181, quoted in Tony McEnery ''Swearing in English: Bad Language, Purity and Power From 1586 to the Present Day'', London: Routledge, 2006, p.143</ref> in which \"open rebellion against the 'system', be it school, parents or authority generally, was openly advocated, while children were constantly exhorted to collect evidence against teachers of alleged injustices or anything which was likely to enhance revolution.\"<ref>Whitehouse (1977) p.180, cited in McEnery, p.143</ref> She was \"greatly relieved\u2014for the sake of the children\" at the \u00a350 fine and \u00a3115.50 costs imposed on Richard Handyside and Geoffrey Collins, its publishers,<ref>John Sutherland ''Offensive Literature'', Junction Books, 1982, p.111, 113</ref> who also had works by [[Che Guevara]] and [[Fidel Castro]] on their small list of publications. For Whitehouse it was a \"fundamental right of a child to be a child\" and \"the duty of mature people to ensure that childhood is protected against the inroads of those who would exploit its immaturity for political, social or personal gain.\"<ref>[http://archive.spectator.co.uk/article/7th-august-1971/23/little-red-school-book Letter from Mary Whitehouse] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140402053147/http://archive.spectator.co.uk/article/7th-august-1971/23/little-red-school-book |date=2 April 2014 }}, ''The Spectator'', 6 August 1971, p.23; quoted in Tracey and Morrison, p.138</ref> A modified second edition was allowed to be published in the UK,<ref name=\"Moorhead\">Joanna Moorhead [https://www.theguardian.com/education/2014/jul/08/the-little-red-schoolbook-republished-soren-hansen \"The Little Red Schoolbook \u2013 honest about sex and the need to challenge authority\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170319200323/https://www.theguardian.com/education/2014/jul/08/the-little-red-schoolbook-republished-soren-hansen |date=19 March 2017 }}, ''The Guardian'', 8 July 2014</ref> but the original verdict in the prosecution was sustained in the [[Court of Appeal (England and Wales)|Appeal Court]] and the [[European Court of Human Rights]] (see ''[[Handyside v United Kingdom]]''). An unexpurgated edition of the book, bar one minor cut, was published in the UK during July 2014.<ref name=\"Moorhead\"/>\n\nAlong with the ([[Catholic Church|Catholic]]) Labour peer [[Frank Pakenham, 7th Earl of Longford|Lord Longford]], [[Malcolm Muggeridge]] and [[Cliff Richard]],<ref>Mark Duguid [http://www.screenonline.org.uk/people/id/463770/ \"Whitehouse, Mary (1910\u20132001)\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110628194939/http://www.screenonline.org.uk/people/id/463770/ |date=28 June 2011 }}, BFI screenonline</ref> Whitehouse was a leading figure in the [[Nationwide Festival of Light]], which protested against the commercial exploitation of sex and violence. The Festival's mass \"rally against permissiveness\" in [[Trafalgar Square]] was attended by 50,000 people in September 1971.<ref name=\"Winter\"/> On 25 August that year she had an audience with [[Pope Paul VI]] regarding 'moral pollution',<ref name=\"Brown\"/> in which she attempted to present the pontiff with ''Oz28'' and the ''Little Red School Book'', but these items found their way to an official of the Papal See instead.<ref>Sutherland ''Offensive Literature'', p.116</ref> In his Foreword to Whitehouse's book, ''Who Does She Think She Is?'' (1971), Malcolm Muggeridge wrote: \"It is literally true that but for her the total demolition of all Christian decencies and values in this country would have taken place virtually without a word of public protest.\"<ref name=\"Salmans\"/>\n\nFollowing the release on appeal of the defendants in the [[Oz (magazine)#UK obscenity trials|''Oz'' trial]], \"an unmitigated disaster for the children of our country\",<ref>''Evening Standard'', 6 November 1971, quote as reproduced in Tracey and Morrison, p.135, 207 n.6:14</ref> Whitehouse launched the Nationwide Petition for Public Decency in January 1972, which gained 1.35 million signatures by the time it was presented to [[Edward Heath]] in April 1973.<ref>Dominic Sandbrook ''State of Emergency, The Way We Were: Britain 1970\u201374'', London: Allen Lane, 2010, p.462</ref> She had around 300 speaking engagements during the period of her highest profile.<ref name=\"Barker\"/> The pornographic magazine ''Whitehouse'' was launched in 1975 by publisher [[David Sullivan (businessman)|David Sullivan]].<ref>Roy Greenslade ''Press Gang: How Newspapers Make Profits From Propaganda'', London: Macmillan, 2004 [2003], p.490</ref><ref>Jamie Doward [https://www.theguardian.com/business/2001/may/13/pressandpublishing.media \"Top shelf gathers dust\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160816082645/https://www.theguardian.com/business/2001/may/13/pressandpublishing.media |date=16 August 2016 }}, ''The Observer'', 13 May 2001</ref>\n\n=== Opposition to paedophilia and child pornography ===\nThe [[Paedophile Information Exchange]] had been asked to help the [[Albany Trust]], which received public money, to produce a booklet on paedophilia, which was to have been published by the Trust. Whitehouse mentioned the connection in a speech, asserting that public funds were being used to subsidise paedophile groups, and the Trust withdrew its support for the production of the pamphlet in 1977.<ref>{{cite news|last=Kennedy|first=Dominic|url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/news/uk/article4141527.ece|title=Groups linked to paedophile network given state grants|work=The Times|location=London|date=8 July 2014|accessdate=11 October 2015}} {{subscription required}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title = Lost Freedom: The Landscape of the Child and the British Post-War Settlement|publisher = Oxford University Press|date =28 November 2013|isbn = 9780191665097|language = en|first = Mathew|last = Thomson}}{{page needed|date=October 2015}}</ref> However, PIE itself did not receive public funding.<ref name=\"Mason\">{{cite news|last=Mason|first=Rowena|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2014/jul/07/no-evidence-home-office-funded-paedophile-group|title=No evidence that Home Office funded paedophile group, review finds|work=The Guardian|date=7 July 2014|accessdate=11 October 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303125717/http://www.theguardian.com/society/2014/jul/07/no-evidence-home-office-funded-paedophile-group|archive-date=3 March 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nHer subsequent petition against paedophilia and [[child pornography]] was signed by 1\u00bd million people.<ref name=\"Ost\">{{cite book|last=Ost|first=Suzanne|title=Child Pornography and Sexual Grooming: Legal and Societal Responses|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=MruKQz2ZdKMC&pg=PA84|publisher=Cambridge University Press|location=Cambridge|year=2009|page=84|isbn=978-0521885829|access-date=11 October 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160306204705/https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=MruKQz2ZdKMC&pg=PA84|archive-date=6 March 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Whitehouse urged the Conservative opposition to push for a bill on the subject, in the absence of interest from the Labour government. The [[private member's bill]] proposed by Conservative MP [[Cyril Townsend]] became the [[Protection of Children Act 1978]].<ref name=\"Ost\"/>\n\n===''Gay News'' and other cases of alleged blasphemy===\nWhitehouse took private prosecutions in a number of cases where official action was not forthcoming. The action against ''[[Gay News]]'' in 1977 concerned \"[[The Love That Dares to Speak Its Name]]\", a poem by [[James Kirkup]], a fellow of the [[Royal Society of Literature]],<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/culture-obituaries/books-obituaries/5314221/James-Kirkup.html Obituary: James Kirkup], {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101009172516/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/culture-obituaries/books-obituaries/5314221/James-Kirkup.html |date=9 October 2010 }} ''The Daily Telegraph'', 12 May 2009</ref> the theme of which was the sexual fantasies of a Roman centurion about the body of Jesus Christ. She was the plaintiff in a charge of [[blasphemous libel]] against ''Gay News'' (''[[Whitehouse v Lemon]]''), a trial at the [[Old Bailey]] between 4 and 7 July 1977. It was the first prosecution for the offence since 1922. \"I simply had to protect Our Lord,\" said Whitehouse at the time,<ref name=\"Adam\">Corinna Adam [http://www.newstatesman.com/node/152583 \"Protecting Our Lord\"], {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131207222059/http://www.newstatesman.com/node/152583 |date=7 December 2013 }} ''New Statesman'', 15 July 1977, in a version republished 3 February 2006</ref> Kirkup's poem being in her opinion \"the recrucifixion of Christ by 20th-century weapons\".<ref name=\"KirkupTimes\">{{cite news|url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/opinion/obituaries/article2085242.ece|title= James Kirkup: poet and translator|work=The Times|date=13 May 2009|accessdate=16 September 2015}} (subscription required)</ref> The prosecution counsel [[John Smyth (barrister)|John Smyth]], representing Whitehouse, told the jury: \"It may be said that this is a love poem\u2014it is not, it is a poem about buggery\", while the defence case was that the poem suggested all of mankind could love Jesus Christ.<ref name=\"OTD110777\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/july/11/newsid_2499000/2499721.stm|title=1977: Gay paper guilty of blasphemy, July 11|website=BBC On This Day|accessdate=2 February 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080307121819/http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/july/11/newsid_2499000/2499721.stm|archive-date=7 March 2008|url-status=live|df=dmy-all|date=1977-07-11}}</ref> The Archbishop of Canterbury [[Donald Coggan]] and Cardinal [[Basil Hume]] both declined Whitehouse's invitation for them to give evidence at the trial.<ref>Tracey & Morrison, p.12</ref>\n\nDenis Lemon, the editor and owner of ''Gay News'', published the poem in the 3\u201316 June 1976 issue<ref name=\"Tracey3\">Tracey & Morrison ''Whitehouse'', p.3</ref> on the basis that the \"message and intention of the poem was to celebrate the absolute universality of God's love\".<ref>Peter Burton [https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/obituary-denis-lemon-1415565.html Obituary: Denis Lemon], {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120613180522/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/obituary-denis-lemon-1415565.html |date=13 June 2012 }} ''The Independent'', 23 July 1994</ref> Whitehouse told Michael Tracey and David Morrison, the authors of a book about her: \"I think it shook me more than anything I had seen or come into contact with all the time I had been campaigning. ... I don't think Jesus Christ has ever been more real to me as a person than he was at that particular moment.\"<ref name=\"Tracey3\"/>\n\n''Gay News'' lost the case; the jury decided the case on a 10\u20132 majority.<ref name=\"OTD110777\"/> Lemon and his paper were fined, and Lemon received a nine-month suspended prison sentence.<ref name=\"KirkupTimes\"/> A ''[[The Guardian|Guardian]]'' editorial after the verdict said of the trial: \"No evidence was called, or allowed to be called, about the merits of the poem in literature or theology\", despite the case concerning blasphemy, or to suggest that Kirkup's intention had been to \"scandalise\" which, given the poet's \"list of serious works\", the newspaper thought should have been proven.<ref>Editorial [https://www.theguardian.com/theguardian/2012/jul/13/archive-1977-gay-blasphemy-church-law-religion \"From the archive, 13 July 1977: Editorial: Is the law on blasphemy still relevant?\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170203091315/https://www.theguardian.com/theguardian/2012/jul/13/archive-1977-gay-blasphemy-church-law-religion |date=3 February 2017 }}, ''The Guardian'', 13 July 2012 (reprint)</ref> The judge in at the prosecution, [[Alan King-Hamilton]], QC, had only allowed novelist [[Margaret Drabble]] and journalist [[Bernard Levin]] to appear as \"character\" witnesses for the newspaper.<ref name=\"KirkupTimes\"/> ''[[The Spectator]]'' editorial on 15 July commented: \"The prosecution was perverse, the verdict misguided. As for the punishments, given that this was in effect a test case, they are excessive\" and \"left the law on obscenity even more muddled and confused than it was before, and have served no useful purpose whatsoever, except to delight Mrs Whitehouse\".<ref>[http://archive.spectator.co.uk/article/16th-july-1977/3/bad-news \"Bad news\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131214095856/http://archive.spectator.co.uk/article/16th-july-1977/3/bad-news |date=14 December 2013 }}, ''The Spectator'', 15 July 1977, p.3</ref> The [[Court of Appeal of England and Wales|Court of Appeal]] and the [[Judicial functions of the House of Lords|House of Lords]] dismissed appeals, although Lemon's sentence was overturned.<ref name=\"KirkupTimes\"/>\n\n[[Geoffrey Robertson]], QC, the barrister for ''Gay News'' in the case, described Whitehouse as [[Homophobia|homophobic]] in ''The Times'' in 2008, saying: \"Her fear of homosexuals was visceral\".<ref name=\"ROBQC\"/> He describes the beliefs she reveals in her book, ''Whatever Happened to Sex?'', as \"nonsense\", such as her assertion that \"homosexuality was caused by abnormal parental sex 'during pregnancy or just after'\", saying that for her, \"being gay was like having acne: 'Psychiatric literature proves that 60 per cent of homosexuals who go for treatment get completely cured'\".<ref name=\"ROBQC\"/>\n\nWhitehouse had hoped to use the blasphemy laws against material other than Kirkup's poem, and was interested in pursuing a possible action against allegedly blasphemous content for some time.<ref name=\"Tracey4\">Tracey & Morrison ''Whitehouse'', p.4-5</ref> She had hoped that it could be used as a basis for prosecution if a planned pornographic film on the life of Jesus Christ had been made in Britain. The intended work, containing both homosexual and heterosexual content, was a project by the Danish filmmaker [[Jens J\u00f8rgen Thorsen]]. This time Whitehouse, whose organisation had commissioned a translation of the script, gained more widespread support.<ref>Tracey & Morrison ''Whitehouse'', p.11</ref> NVALA organised a publicity campaign,<ref>Sutherland ''Offensive Litearure'', p.149-50</ref> which resulted in Thorsen's intentions gaining significant public condemnation in September 1976 from leading public figures, including [[Elizabeth II|the Queen]].<ref>John Horton and Susan Mendus (eds.) [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=Zdu5_V_F1TgC&pg=RA2-PA24&lpg=RA2-PA24 ''Aspects of Toleration: Philosophical Studies''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160306120831/https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=Zdu5_V_F1TgC&pg=RA2-PA24&lpg=RA2-PA24 |date=6 March 2016 }}, Abingdon: Routledge, 1985 [2010], p.24</ref> Jensen was forced to abandon his plans.<ref name=\"Tracey4\"/>\n\nWhitehouse and a letter writing campaign from the Festival of Light, after unsuccessfully lobbying the [[British Board of Film Classification|British Board of Film Classification] to refuse the film a certificate, were successful in persuading some councils in Britain to ban screenings of ''[[Monty Python's Life of Brian]]'' (1979) in their areas on unproven grounds that the film is blasphemous.<ref>{{cite news|last=Sellers|first=Richard|url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2003/mar/28/artsfeatures1|title=Welease Bwian<!-- sic. -->|work=The Guardian|date=28 March 2003|accessdate=7 March 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161220140824/https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2003/mar/28/artsfeatures1|archive-date=20 December 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Bhaskar|first=Sanjeev|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/6679546/What-did-Life-of-Brian-ever-do-for-us.html|title=What did 'Life of Brian' ever do for us?|work=The Sunday Telegraph|date=29 November 2009|accessdate=7 March 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170301233425/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/6679546/What-did-Life-of-Brian-ever-do-for-us.html|archive-date=1 March 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Jones|first=Nelson|url=http://www.newstatesman.com/blogs/nelson-jones/2011/08/blasphemy-law-brian-religion|title=The afterlife of Brian|work=New Statesman|date=16 August 2011|accessdate=7 March 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170307205824/http://www.newstatesman.com/blogs/nelson-jones/2011/08/blasphemy-law-brian-religion|archive-date=7 March 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Nearly a decade later, a threatened campaign by Whitehouse against [[Martin Scorsese]]'s ''[[The Last Temptation of Christ (film)|The Last Temptation of Christ]]'' (1988), with the law against blasphemy still in force at the time, failed to materialise.<ref>{{cite news|last=Travis|first=Alan|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2004/oct/18/religion.world|title=Medieval law has had its day|work=The Guardian|date=18 October 2004|accessdate=7 March 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170308050704/https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2004/oct/18/religion.world|archive-date=8 March 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Brooke|first=Michael|url=http://www.screenonline.org.uk/film/id/592689/|title=The Last Temptation of Christ: How the BBFC Dealt With the Threat of a Prosecution for Blasphemy|work=BFI Screenonline|date=2003\u201314|accessdate=7 March 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170308044911/http://www.screenonline.org.uk/film/id/592689/|archive-date=8 March 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===''The Romans in Britain''===\nIn 1982 she pursued a private prosecution against [[Michael Bogdanov]], the director of a [[Royal National Theatre|National Theatre]] production of [[Howard Brenton]]'s ''[[The Romans in Britain]]'', a play that \"drew a direct parallel between the [[Roman conquest of Britain|Roman invasion]] of Celtic Britain in 54 BC and the contemporary British presence in [[Northern Ireland]]\".<ref name=\"Billington\">Michael Billington ''State of the Nation: British Theatre Since 1945'', London: Faber, 2007, p.305-6</ref> The first act contains \"a brief scene\"<ref name=\"Billington\"/> of (simulated) [[Anal sex|anal]] [[rape]]\u2014the Police had visited the production three times and found no basis for legal action.<ref name=\"Brenton\">Howard Brenton [https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2006/jan/28/theatre.stage \"Look back in anger\"], {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170319200503/https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2006/jan/28/theatre.stage |date=19 March 2017 }} ''The Guardian'', 28 January 2006</ref> In the prosecution Whitehouse's counsel claimed Section 13 of the [[Sexual Offences Act 1956]], which described the offence of \"procuring an act of gross indecency\",<ref name=\"LawsonRB\">Mark Lawson [https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2005/oct/28/theatre \"Passion play\"], {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170319200435/https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2005/oct/28/theatre |date=19 March 2017 }} ''The Guardian'', 28 October 2005</ref> was applicable. Because this was a general Act, there was no possibility of defence on the basis of artistic merit, unlike that permitted under the [[Obscene Publications Act 1959]].\n\nSince Whitehouse had not seen the play, the prosecution evidence rested on the testimony of her solicitor, Graham Ross-Cornes, who claimed he saw the actor's penis. However, cross-examination revealed that he had seen a performance of the play from the back row of the stalls, 90 feet from the stage.<ref name=\"LawsonRB\"/><ref name=\"The Justice Game\">Robertson [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=s0dhdH_VzJ4C&pg=PA177 ''The Justice Game''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160306104214/https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=s0dhdH_VzJ4C&pg=PA177 |date=6 March 2016 }}, p.177</ref> [[Jeremy Hutchinson, Baron Hutchinson of Lullington|Lord Hutchinson]], counsel for Bogdanov, was able to demonstrate the nature of the illusion performed on stage.<ref name=\"LawsonRB\"/> This was achieved by suggesting that it might have been the actor's thumb protruding from his fist, rather than his erect penis. The defence had argued that the Act did not apply to the theatre; the judge [[Christopher Staughton|Mr Justice Staughton]] then ruled that it did. After three days,<ref name=\"Billington\"/> the action was withdrawn after the prosecution counsel told Whitehouse that he was unable to continue with the case;<ref name=\"LawsonRB\"/> the litigation was ended by the Attorney General putting forward a plea of ''[[nolle prosequi]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/opinion/obituaries/article4269412.ece|title=Sir Christopher Staughton|work=The Times|date=17 November 2014|accessdate=16 September 2015}} (subscription required)</ref> Both sides claimed a victory; Whitehouse's side asserted that the important legal point had been made with the ruling on the applicability of the Sexual Offences Act, while Bogdanov said it was because she knew that he would not be convicted.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/march/18/newsid_2524000/2524269.stm |title=BBC 'On This Day', 18 March |publisher=BBC News |date=18 March 1967 |accessdate=25 July 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090321130757/http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/march/18/newsid_2524000/2524269.stm |archive-date=21 March 2009 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Whitehouse had to meet \u00a320,000 costs, most of which was paid by an anonymous donor.<ref name=\"Billington\"/>\n\nWhitehouse's account of the trial is recorded in ''A Most Dangerous Woman'' ({{ISBN|0-85648-540-3}}); she wrote that she was of the opinion that the legal point had been established, and they had no wish to criminalise Bogdanov, the play's director.\n\n===Margaret Thatcher's government===\nBy the 1980s, Whitehouse had found a powerful ally in the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] government, particularly in [[Margaret Thatcher]] herself, whose support base partially consisted of Christians and social conservatives. It has been claimed by the Conservative journalist [[Bruce Anderson (columnist)|Bruce Anderson]] that the market orientation of the Thatcher government prejudiced it against Whitehouse in private.<ref>Bruce Anderson [https://www.independent.co.uk/opinion/commentators/bruce-anderson/bruce-anderson-a-life-spent-trying-in-vain-to-preserve-the-suburban-idyll-618069.html \"A life spent trying in vain to preserve the suburban idyll\"], {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110913124456/http://www.independent.co.uk/opinion/commentators/bruce-anderson/bruce-anderson-a-life-spent-trying-in-vain-to-preserve-the-suburban-idyll-618069.html |date=13 September 2011 }} ''The Independent'', 26 November 2001</ref>\n\nIt has been claimed by commentators not necessarily in agreement with her that Whitehouse's efforts played a part in the passage of the [[Protection of Children Act 1978]], the [[Indecent Displays (Control) Act 1981]], which concerned sex shops, and the [[Video Recordings Act 1984]], which banned '[[video nasty|video nasties]]'. A term reportedly coined by Whitehouse,<ref name=\"Holmes\">Andrew Holmes [https://www.theguardian.com/film/2002/jul/05/filmcensorship.artsfeatures \"Let there be blood\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170419003416/https://www.theguardian.com/film/2002/jul/05/filmcensorship.artsfeatures |date=19 April 2017 }}, ''The Guardian'', 5 July 2002</ref> she screened edited highlights from these films for MPs at the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] in late 1983,<ref name=\"Stanley\">Richard Stanley \"Dying Light: An Obituary for the Great British Horror Movie\" in Steve Chibnall and Julian Petley (eds.) ''British Horror Cinema'', London: Routledge, 2002, p.184</ref> which included extracts from ''[[The Evil Dead]]'' (1981) considered by her \"the number one nasty\".<ref name=\"Holmes\"/> It was \"a highly effective means of lobbying the government to introduce tight state controls on the burgeoning video industry\".<ref name=\"Stanley\"/>\n\nAround 1986, papers released in late December 2014 indicate, Whitehouse met with Thatcher on at least two occasions to discuss the possibility of banning [[sex toy]]s using a potential extension of the \"deprave and corrupt\" provision in the Obscene Publications Act 1959.<ref name=\"Tufft\">Ben Tufft [https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/thatcher-wanted-to-ban-sex-toys-using-antipornography-laws-after-pressure-from-campaigners-9949565.html \"Thatcher wanted to ban sex toys using anti-pornography laws after pressure from campaigners\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150101180456/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/thatcher-wanted-to-ban-sex-toys-using-antipornography-laws-after-pressure-from-campaigners-9949565.html |date=1 January 2015 }}, ''The Independent'', 30 December 2014</ref> The plan was abandoned because home secretary [[Leon Brittan]] thought the concept of public taste would be a problematic concept for legal action.<ref name=\"Tufft\"/><ref>Natasha Hinde [http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2014/12/31/sex-toys-ban-margaret-thatcher_n_6399746.html \"Sex Toys V Margaret Thatcher: The Iron Lady Wanted To Ban Them Under Obscenity Laws\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150103232555/http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2014/12/31/sex-toys-ban-margaret-thatcher_n_6399746.html |date=3 January 2015 }}, ''The Huffington Post'', 31 December 2014</ref>\n\n==Later years and assessments of her influence==\nWhitehouse was appointed a [[Commander of the Order of the British Empire|CBE]] in 1980.<ref name=\"Winter\"/> In 1988, she suffered a spinal injury in a fall, which severely curbed her campaigning activities.<ref name=\"Telegraph\"/> Whitehouse retired as president of the NVALA in 1994. She died, aged 91, in a nursing home in [[Colchester]], [[Essex]], on 23 November 2001.<ref name=\"LA Times\" /> Whitehouse is buried in the churchyard of the parish church of St Mary the Virgin at [[Dedham, Essex|Dedham]] in Essex.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ipswichstar.co.uk/news/mourners-pay-tribute-to-mary-whitehouse-1-94847|title=Mourners pay tribute to Mary Whitehouse|date=6 December 2001|website=Ipswich Star|language=en|access-date=17 February 2019}}</ref>\n[[File:Mary Whitehouse grave.jpg|thumb|The grave of Mary Whitehouse's husband, Ernest Raymond Whitehouse]]\n\nThe journalist [[Mary Kenny]] believes \"Mary Whitehouse was a significant figure. Some of her battles were justified, even prophetic. Today her attacks on 'kiddie porn' would be widely supported.\"<ref>Mary Kenny [http://www.spectator.co.uk/coffeehouse/6064488/in-defence-of-mary-whitehouse.thtml \"In defence of Mary Whitehouse\"], {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100815015701/http://www.spectator.co.uk/coffeehouse/6064488/in-defence-of-mary-whitehouse.thtml |date=15 August 2010 }} ''The Spectator'' (blog), 10 June 2010</ref> The academic [[Richard Hoggart]] observed: \"her main focus was on sex, followed by bad language and violence. Odd: if she had reversed the order, she might have been more effective.\"<ref name=\"RHoggart\"/>\n\nWriting in the ''[[Dictionary of National Biography]]'', the philosopher [[Mary Warnock, Baroness Warnock|Mary Warnock]] opined, \"Even if her campaigning did not succeed in 'cleaning up TV', still less in making it more fit to watch in other ways, she was of serious intent, and was an influence for good at a crucial stage in the development both of the [[BBC]] and of [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]]. She was not, as the BBC seemed officially to proclaim, a mere figure of fun.\"<ref name=\"Warnock\"/>\n\nThe papers of the NVALA for 1970\u20131990 have been deposited at the Library<ref>[http://libwww.essex.ac.uk/Archives/nvala.htm NVALA Archive] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100824214807/http://libwww.essex.ac.uk/Archives/nvala.htm |date=24 August 2010 }}, Albert Sloman Library, University of Essex</ref> of the [[University of Essex]].<ref>[http://archiveshub.ac.uk/features/15000.html \"National Viewers' and Listeners' Association\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110929001259/http://archiveshub.ac.uk/features/15000.html |date=29 September 2011 }}, Archive Hub website</ref>\n\nWhitehouse's early campaign and her disagreements with the BBC under [[Hugh Greene|Greene]] were the basis of a drama first broadcast in 2008 entitled ''[[Filth: The Mary Whitehouse Story]]'', written by [[Amanda Coe]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b00bws1h |title=Filth: The Mary Whitehouse Story BBC2 |access-date=24 May 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100530210017/http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b00bws1h |archive-date=30 May 2010 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> [[Julie Walters]] played Whitehouse, [[Alun Armstrong]] played her husband Ernest, and [[Hugh Bonneville]] played Greene.\n\nHer favourite programmes were ''[[Dixon of Dock Green]]'' (winner of NVALA's Best Family Viewing Award in 1967),<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/archive/article/1967-05-19/3/15.html|title=Best Family Viewing Award for ''Dixon''|work=The Times|location=London|date=19 May 1967|accessdate=1 May 2016|page=3}} {{subscription required}}</ref> ''[[Neighbours]]'', and coverage of [[snooker]].<ref name=\"Telegraph\"/><ref name=\"Dowell\">Ben Dowell [https://www.theguardian.com/media/2006/jul/21/channel4.broadcasting \"Mary Whitehouse drama heads for BBC\"], {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160916132104/https://www.theguardian.com/media/2006/jul/21/channel4.broadcasting |date=16 September 2016 }} ''The Guardian'', 21 July 2008</ref> She had privately expressed gratitude to Dennis Potter and the BBC for his television play ''[[Where Adam Stood]]'' in 1976.<ref>Ben Thompson (ed.) ''[[Ban This Filth!]]'' [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=-r7k88pWzYgC&pg=RA2-PT83 p.83-84] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160701091540/https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=-r7k88pWzYgC&pg=RA2-PT83 |date=1 July 2016 }}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Censorship]]\n*[[Pornography]]\n*\"Mary Long\", a song in [[Deep Purple]]'s 1973 album ''[[Who Do We Think We Are]]''\n*\"[[Pigs (Three Different Ones)]]\", a song in [[Pink Floyd]]'s 1977 album [[Animals (Pink Floyd album)|''Animals'']]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* [[Ramsey Campbell]] (1987) \"Turn Off: The Whitehouse Way\" (an account of a public appearance by Mary Whitehouse) in ''Ramsey Campbell, Probably'', PS Publishing, {{ISBN|1-902880-40-4}}\n* Max Caulfield (1976) ''Mary Whitehouse'', Mowbray, {{ISBN|0-264-66190-7}}\n* Mary Whitehouse (1967) ''Cleaning-up TV: From Protest to Participation'', Blandford, ISBN B0000CNC3I\n* Mary Whitehouse (1971) ''Who Does She Think She is?'', New English Library, {{ISBN|0-450-00993-9}}\n* Mary Whitehouse (1977) ''Whatever Happened to Sex?'', Wayland, {{ISBN|0-85340-460-7}} (pbk: Hodder & Stoughton, {{ISBN|0-340-22906-3}})\n* Mary Whitehouse (1982) ''Most Dangerous Woman?'', Lion Hudson, {{ISBN|0-85648-408-3}}\n* Mary Whitehouse (1985) ''Mightier Than the Sword'', Kingsway Publications, {{ISBN|0-86065-382-X}}\n* Mary Whitehouse (1993) ''Quite Contrary: An Autobiography'', Sidgwick & Jackson, {{ISBN|0-283-06202-9}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb name|0925766|Mary Whitehouse}}\n* {{UK National Archives ID}}\n* {{NPG name}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Whitehouse, Mary}}\n[[Category:1910 births]]\n[[Category:2001 deaths]]\n[[Category:Anti-pornography activists]]\n[[Category:British lobbyists]]\n[[Category:Commanders of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:English Christians]]\n[[Category:People from Nuneaton]]\n[[Category:Schoolteachers from Warwickshire]]\n", "name_user": "77.248.70.40", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mary_Whitehouse"}
{"title_page": "Inholland University of Applied Sciences", "text_new": "{{short description|Dutch university with eight campuses}}\n{{Infobox university\n| name = Inholland University of Applied Sciences\n| native_name = Hogeschool Inholland\n| image = Short logo.png\n| caption = \n| motto = Leren = durven\n| mottoeng = Learning = being courageous\n| established = 1 September 2002 - mergers of higher vocational education institutions in the provinces of North and South Holland\n| type = University of Applied Sciences\n| chairperson = Jet de Ranitz\n| students = 37,000; 6000 international students\n| city = [[The Hague]], [[Amsterdam]], [[Haarlem]], [[Alkmaar]], [[Delft]], [[Diemen]], [[Dordrecht]], [[Rotterdam]]\n| province = [[South Holland]]\n| country = [[Netherlands]]\n| campus = Multiple campuses\n| colours = {{color box|#E10075}} [[Magenta]]\n| website = {{URL|https://www.inholland.nl/}}\n| logo = [[File:Inholland University black.png|thumb|Inholland University black]]\n}}\n[[File:Hogeschool-inholland-delft.jpg|thumb|Inholland Delft Campus]]\n'''Inholland University of Applied Sciences''' ({{Lang-nl|Hogeschool Inholland}}; {{Lang-fr|Universit\u00e9 des sciences appliqu\u00e9es d'Inholland}}; {{Lang-de|Hochschule Inholland}}) is a [[university]] of applied sciences with its campuses located in 8 different cities<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.inholland.nl/locaties/|title=Locaties - Hogeschool Inholland - Hbo-opleidingen|website=www.inholland.nl|language=nl|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> placed throughout the western [[Netherlands]] with an education campus in every main city of the [[Randstad]] \u2013 the country's economic, political and cultural hub. With over 37,000 students from more than 100 countries, the university follows the applied sciences mode of education.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.inholland.nl/over-inholland/|title=Over Inholland - Hogeschool Inholland|website=www.inholland.nl|language=nl|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\nThere are two sorts of universities in Dutch higher education: research universities and universities of applied sciences. Research universities are essentially accountable for offering research-oriented programs, while universities of applied sciences offer courses that focus on the practical application of arts and sciences with the main focus on real-life practice and career preparation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.studyinholland.nl/dutch-education/dutch-higher-education|title=Dutch education|last=Nuffic|date=2012-04-12|website=Study in Holland|language=en|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref> \n\nBetween 2007 and 2010, the chairman of the Executive Board was Geert Dales. In the period 2010 to December 2014, the position was filled by Doekle Terpstra. He was succeeded on 1 December 2014 by Jet de Ranitz.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.chiefstoryteller.nl/jet-de-ranitz/|title=Jet de Ranitz|last=Rombouts|first=Reinier|date=2017-05-15|website=Chief Storyteller|language=nl|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>\n\n== Campuses ==\nInholland University has campuses in the following cities:\n\n* [[Alkmaar]]\n* [[Amsterdam]]\n* [[Delft]]\n* [[The Hague]]\n* [[Diemen]]\n* [[Dordrecht]]\n* [[Haarlem]]\n* [[Rotterdam]]\n\n[[File:500 inhollanddenhaag.jpg|thumb|Inholland The Hague Campus]]\n'''2022 Amsterdam campus'''\n\nThe new building of Inholland in Amsterdam on the Zeeburgereiland is set to be presented in September 2022. The new construction of Inholland on Zeeburgereiland is the result of the fact that the location in Diemen has reached the end of its lifespan. But also because the municipality of Amsterdam has indicated that it would like to see Hogeschool Inholland operate in and from the city. The relocation gives the university of applied sciences a recognizable position in the city of Amsterdam and a good profile in the city and region. The study programs from Amsterdam and Diemen will soon come together at one location.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.inholland.nl/nieuws/nieuwbouw-amsterdam-bestemmingsplan-sluisbuurt-vastgesteld/|title=Nieuwbouw Amsterdam: bestemmingsplan Sluisbuurt vastgesteld|website=Nieuwbouw Amsterdam: bestemmingsplan Sluisbuurt vastgesteld|language=nl|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>\n\n== Organization and activities ==\nWorking in the pattern of applied sciences, Inholland University of Applied Sciences has several in-house learning companies where students conduct projects within a particular industry, often on behalf of a company, institution or governmental agency. For example, NEWb and Rookie Entertainment are student-run companies for our music and media students. Here they learn how to produce a radio or TV show, do market research, create a promotional campaign or organise an event. In Delft, Inholland Composites offers Aeronautical Engineering students an opportunity to gain practical and theoretical knowledge on advanced composite materials.\n\n[[Bachelor's degree]]s at Inholland University of Applied Sciences demand three or four years of full-time study and require 240 European Credit Transfer and Accumulation System (ECTS) credits. One [[ECTS grading scale|ECTS]] credit represents 28 hours of full-time study and the study/workload for one academic year accounts for 60 credits.The Accreditation Organisation of the Netherlands and Flanders ([[Accreditation Organisation of the Netherlands and Flanders|NVAO]]) approves study programs offered by [[Dutch universities]]. All international bachelor's programs offered by Inholland University of Applied Sciences are recognised by [[Accreditation Organisation of the Netherlands and Flanders|NVAO]].\n\n'''Internships'''\n\nDuring their studies, all Inholland students are required to do at least one internship (one semester in the third academic year). Internships, or\u00a0 work placements, can be done in the Netherlands or abroad, and the choice upon the company is generally done by students themselves, but supervised and approved by the university. Specific requirements may vary according to the study programme.\n\nDuring the internship students are supervised by one university lecturer or coach, and one company employee.\n\nThese internships are useful for building a professional network and gaining work experience directly on the field. Inholland is committed to protect its students during the work placements experience by monitoring its development and quality in rapport to the study career.\n\n== Faculties ==\nThe [[degree programs]] of Inholland University of Applied Sciences are divided into faculties. There are 75 Bachelor's programs provided by Inholland. The international bachelor's programs come under the faculties of Creative Business and Engineering, Design and Computing.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.inholland.nl/opleidingen-v2/#/|title=- Hbo-opleidingen Hogeschool Inholland|website=www.inholland.nl|language=nl|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> Inholland also offers Associate Degree (AD) programs, managed by Inholland Academy,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.inholland.nl/academy/opleidingen/|title=Praktijkgerichte post-hbo opleidingen - Inholland Academy|website=www.inholland.nl|language=nl|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref> and master\u2019s programs only in dutch language.\n\n\n'''Agri, Food & Life Sciences'''\n\nLocations: [[Amsterdam]] and [[Delft]]\n\n- \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 Animal and Livestock Farming ''\u00a0- Full-time Bachelor'' - Delft\n\n- \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 Food Commerce and Technology ''\u00a0- Full-time Bachelor'' - Amsterdam, Delft\n\n- \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 Horticulture & Agribusiness ''\u00a0- Full-time Bachelor'' - Delft\n\n- \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 Horticulture & Agribusiness \u00a0- ''Part-time Bachelor'' - Delft\n\n- \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 Landscape and Environment Management ''\u00a0- Full-time Bachelor'' - Delft\n\n- \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 Biology and Medical Laboratory Research ''\u00a0- Full-time Bachelo''r - Amsterdam\n\n- \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 Biotechnology ''\u00a0- Full-time Bachelor'' - Amsterdam\n\n- \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 Chemistry ''\u00a0- Full-time Bachelor''- Amsterdam\n\n'''Business, Finance & Law'''\n\n[[File:Rotterdam hogeschool inholland.jpg|alt=|thumb|250x250px|Inholland Campus Rotterdam]]\n\nLocations: [[Alkmaar]], [[Diemen]], [[The Hague]], [[Haarlem]] and [[Rotterdam]] \u00a0\n\n- \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 Accountancy ''\u00a0- Full-time Bachelor'' \u00a0-. Alkmaar, Diemen, Rotterdam\n\n- \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 Business Studies ''\u00a0- Full-time Bachelor'' \u00a0- Alkmaar, The Hague, Diemen, Haarlem, Rotterdam\n\n- \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 Finance & Control: Business Economics ''\u00a0- Full-time Bachelor'' \u00a0- Alkmaar, Diemen, Haarlem, Rotterdam\n\n- \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 Integral Safety Science ''\u00a0- Full-time Bachelor'' \u00a0- Rotterdam\n\n- \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 Integral Safety Science - ''Part-time Bachelor'' - Rotterdam\n\n- \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 Law studies ''- Full-time Bachelor'' r - Rotterdam\n\n- \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 Law studies \u00a0- ''Part-time Bachelo''r - Rotterdam\n\n- \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 Social Legal Services ''\u00a0- Full-time Bachelor'' \u00a0- The Hague, Rotterdam\n\n- \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 Social Legal Services \u00a0- ''Part-time Bachelor'' - The Hague, Rotterdam\n\n'''Creative Business'''\n\nLocations: [[Alkmaar]], [[Diemen]], [[The Hague]], [[Haarlem]] and [[Rotterdam]] \u00a0\n\n- \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 Business Innovation (EN) ''\u00a0- Full-time Bachelor'' - Amsterdam/Diemen\n\n- \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 Communication ''\u00a0- Full-time Bachelor'' \u00a0-. The Hague, Diemen, Rotterdam\n\n-       Creative Business ''\u00a0- Full-time Bachelor'' \u00a0-The Hague, Haarlem, Rotterdam\n\n- \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 Facility management ''\u00a0- Full-time Bachelor'' \u00a0- Diemen\n\n- \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 International Creative Business (EN) ''\u00a0- Full-time Bachelor'' \u00a0- The Hague, Haarlem\n\n- \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 Leisure & Events Management ''\u00a0- Full-time Bachelor'' - Diemen\n\n- \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 Music ''\u00a0- Full-time Bachelor'' \