 as '''5-methyluracil,''' a [[pyrimidine]] nucleobase. In [[RNA]], thymine is replaced by the nucleobase [[uracil]].  Thymine was first isolated in 1893 by [[Albrecht Kossel]] and Albert Neumann from calves' thymus glands, hence its name.<ref>Albrecht Kossel and Albert Neumann (1893) [http://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k90730p/f455.image \"Ueber das Thymin, ein Spaltungsproduct der Nucle\u00efns\u00e4ure\"] (On thymine, a cleavage product of nucleic acid), ''Berichte der Deutschen Chemischen Gesellschaft zu Berlin'', '''26''' :  2753-2756.  From p. 2754:  ''\"Wir bezeichnen diese Substanz als Thymin.\"'' (We designate this substance as \"thymine\" [because it was initially obtained from the thymus glands of calves].)</ref>\n\nPinis\n\nPinis\n\n==See also==\n{{Div col|colwidth=20em}}\n* [[Deoxyribose]]\n* [[Deoxythymidine]]\n* [[Nucleobase]]  \n* [[Pyrimidine]]\t\n* [[Thymineless death]]\n* [[Uracil]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://gmd.mpimp-golm.mpg.de/Spectrums/51a54b80-5865-40c0-8275-cf90f70d6331.aspx Thymine MS Spectrum]\n*[http://www.infoplease.com/ce6/sci/A0848663.html Infoplease Encyclopedia]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20100823233329/http://scienceaid.co.uk/biology/genetics/dna.html Science Aid: DNA Structure and Replication]\n\n{{Nucleobases, nucleosides, and nucleotides}}\n\n[[Category:Nucleobases]]\n[[Category:Pyrimidinediones]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|Chemical compound of DNA}}\n{{for|the similarly spelled B vitamin |Thiamine}}\n{{chembox\n| Verifiedfields = changed\n| Watchedfields = changed\n| verifiedrevid = 458956008\n| ImageFile1 = Thymine_skeletal.svg\n| ImageSize1 = 120px\n| ImageFileL2 = Thymine-3D-balls.png\n| ImageFileR2 = Thymine-3D-vdW.png\n| IUPACName = 5-Methylpyrimidine-2,4(1''H'',3''H'')-dione\n| OtherNames = 5-methyluracil\n| Section1 = {{Chembox Identifiers\n| IUPHAR_ligand = 4581\n|   CASNo = 65-71-4\n|    CASNo_Ref = {{cascite|correct|CAS}}\n| ChEBI_Ref = {{ebicite|changed|EBI}}\n| ChEBI = 17821\n| ChEMBL_Ref = {{ebicite|changed|EBI}}\n| ChEMBL = 993\n|   UNII_Ref = {{fdacite|correct|FDA}}\n| UNII = QR26YLT7LT\n|  PubChem = 1135\n|  ChemSpiderID_Ref = {{chemspidercite|changed|chemspider}}\n| ChemSpiderID = 1103\n|  SMILES = Cc1c[nH]c(=O)[nH]c1=O\n|  InChI = 1/C5H6N2O2/c1-3-2-6-5(9)7-4(3)8/h2H,1H3,(H2,6,7,8,9)\n|  InChIKey = RWQNBRDOKXIBIV-UHFFFAOYAL\n|  StdInChI_Ref = {{stdinchicite|changed|chemspider}}\n| StdInChI = 1S/C5H6N2O2/c1-3-2-6-5(9)7-4(3)8/h2H,1H3,(H2,6,7,8,9)\n|  StdInChIKey_Ref = {{stdinchicite|changed|chemspider}}\n| StdInChIKey = RWQNBRDOKXIBIV-UHFFFAOYSA-N\n|   MeSHName = Thymine\n  }}\n| Section2 = {{Chembox Properties\n|   C = 5\n|   H = 6\n|   N = 2\n|   O = 2\n|   Appearance = \n|   Density = 1.223 g cm<sup>\u22123</sup> (calculated)\n|   MeltingPtC = 316 to 317\n|   BoilingPtC = 335\n|   BoilingPt_notes = (decomposes)\n|   pKa=9.7\n  }}\n<!---\n| Section3 = {{Chembox Hazards\n|   Solubility = \n|   MainHazards = \n|   FlashPt = \n|   AutoignitionPt = \n| MagSus = -57.1\u00b710<sup>\u22126</sup> cm<sup>3</sup>/mol\n  }}\n--->\n}}\n'''Thymine''' {{IPAc-en|\u02c8|\u03b8|a\u026a|m|\u1d7b|n}} ('''T''', '''Thy''') is one of the four [[nucleobase]]s in the [[nucleic acid]] of [[DNA]] that are represented by the letters G\u2013C\u2013A\u2013T. The others are [[adenine]], [[guanine]], and [[cytosine]].  Thymine is also known as '''5-methyluracil,''' a [[pyrimidine]] nucleobase. In [[RNA]], thymine is replaced by the nucleobase [[uracil]].  Thymine was first isolated in 1893 by [[Albrecht Kossel]] and Albert Neumann from calves' thymus glands, hence its name.<ref>Albrecht Kossel and Albert Neumann (1893) [http://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k90730p/f455.image \"Ueber das Thymin, ein Spaltungsproduct der Nucle\u00efns\u00e4ure\"] (On thymine, a cleavage product of nucleic acid), ''Berichte der Deutschen Chemischen Gesellschaft zu Berlin'', '''26''' :  2753-2756.  From p. 2754:  ''\"Wir bezeichnen diese Substanz als Thymin.\"'' (We designate this substance as \"thymine\" [because it was initially obtained from the thymus glands of calves].)</ref>\n\n==Derivation==\nAs its alternate name (5-methyluracil) suggests, thymine may be derived by methylation of uracil at the 5th carbon. In [[RNA]], thymine is replaced with [[uracil]] in most cases.  In DNA, thymine (T) binds to [[adenine]] (A) via two hydrogen bonds, thereby stabilizing the nucleic acid structures.\n\nThymine combined with [[deoxyribose]] creates the [[nucleoside]] [[deoxythymidine]], which is synonymous with the term [[thymidine]]. Thymidine can be phosphorylated with up to three phosphoric acid groups, producing [[dTMP]] ('''d'''eoxy'''t'''hymidine '''m'''ono'''p'''hosphate), [[dTDP]], or [[dTTP]] (for the '''d'''i- and '''t'''ri- phosphates, respectively).\n\nOne of the common mutations of DNA involves two adjacent thymines or cytosine, which, in presence of [[Ultraviolet|ultraviolet light]], may form [[thymine dimers]], causing \"kinks\" in the DNA molecule that inhibit normal function.\n\nThymine could also be a target for actions of 5-[[fluorouracil]] (5-FU) in [[cancer]] treatment. 5-FU can be a metabolic analog of thymine (in DNA synthesis) or uracil (in RNA synthesis).  Substitution of this analog inhibits [[DNA replication|DNA synthesis]] in actively dividing cells.\n\nThymine bases are frequently oxidized to [[hydantoin]]s over time after the death of an organism.<ref>Hofreiter M., Serre D., Poinar H.N., Kuch M., and Paabo S. ''Nature Reviews Genetics'' (2001) '''2''':353.</ref>\n\n==Theoretical aspects==\nIn March 2015, NASA scientists reported that, for the first time, complex [[DNA]] and [[RNA]] [[organic compound]]s of [[life]], including [[uracil]], [[cytosine]] and thymine, have been formed in the laboratory under [[outer space]] conditions, using starting chemicals, such as [[pyrimidine]], found in [[meteorite]]s. Pyrimidine, like [[polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbon]]s (PAHs), the most carbon-rich chemical found in the [[Universe]], may have been formed in [[red giant]]s or in [[Cosmic dust|interstellar dust]] and gas clouds, according to the scientists.<ref name=\"NASA-20150303\">{{cite web |last=Marlaire |first=Ruth |title=NASA Ames Reproduces the Building Blocks of Life in Laboratory |url=http://www.nasa.gov/content/nasa-ames-reproduces-the-building-blocks-of-life-in-laboratory |date=3 March 2015 |work=[[NASA]] |accessdate=5 March 2015 }}</ref> Thymine has not been found in meteorites, which suggests the first strands of DNA had to look elsewhere to obtain this building block. Thymine likely formed within some meteorite parent bodies, however may not have persisted within these bodies due to an [[Redox|oxidation]] reaction with [[hydrogen peroxide]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://blogs.scientificamerican.com/guest-blog/did-the-seeds-of-life-come-from-space/|title=Did the Seeds of Life Come from Space?|last=Tasker|first=Elizabeth|newspaper=Scientific American Blog Network|access-date=2016-11-24}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Div col|colwidth=20em}}\n* [[Deoxyribose]]\n* [[Deoxythymidine]]\n* [[Nucleobase]]  \n* [[Pyrimidine]]\t\n* [[Thymineless death]]\n* [[Uracil]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://gmd.mpimp-golm.mpg.de/Spectrums/51a54b80-5865-40c0-8275-cf90f70d6331.aspx Thymine MS Spectrum]\n*[http://www.infoplease.com/ce6/sci/A0848663.html Infoplease Encyclopedia]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20100823233329/http://scienceaid.co.uk/biology/genetics/dna.html Science Aid: DNA Structure and Replication]\n\n{{Nucleobases, nucleosides, and nucleotides}}\n\n[[Category:Nucleobases]]\n[[Category:Pyrimidinediones]]\n", "name_user": "172.88.23.179", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Fixd a typo)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thymine"}
{"title_page": "Ken Armstrong (politician)", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Ken Armstrong\n| image              = File:Ken Armstrong POTUS46 Headshot.jpg\n| alt                = \n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = Kenneth Reed Armstrong\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1957|04|25}}\n| birth_place        = [[Pasadena, California|Pesadena]], [[California]], U.S.\n| residence          = [[Selma, Oregon|Selma]], [[Oregon]], U.S.\n| nationality        = \n| citizenship        = \n| other_names        = \n| known_for          = Candidate for the Libertarian nomination for President in 2020\n| education          = Weinberg Fellow, [[Hawaii Pacific University]]\n| occupation         = \n| years_active       = \n| home_town          = \n| title              = \n| term               = \n| predecessor        = \n| successor          = \n| party              = [[Libertarian Party (United States)|Libertarian Party]]\n| opponents          = \n| boards             = \n| spouse             = Dawn Midori Kaneshiro Armstrong\n| children           = \n| parents            = \n| relations          = \n| callsign           = \n| website            = https://www.armstrong2020.com\n| awards             = \n| signature          = \n| footnotes          = \n| box_width          = \n| module             = {{Infobox military person|embed=yes\n|allegiance = United States\n|branch=United States Coast Guard\n|serviceyears= 1977\u20131994\n|rank = [[File:US-O3_insignia.svg|18px]] [[Lieutenant]]\n}}\n}}\n'''Kenneth Reed Armstrong''' (born April 25, 1957) is an American military officer, author, speaker, and politican. He served as a [[commissioned officer]] in the [[United States Coast Guard]],<ref>Allen, David\u00a0 (February 5, 1993). \"CG looks for hijacked freighter\" ''[[Pacific Stars and Stripes]]''. Retrieved November 14, 2019.</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.upi.com/Archives/1993/01/30/Coast-Guard-reports-possible-vessel-hijacking-in-Pacific/4824728370000/ |title=Coast Guard reports possible vessel hijacking in Pacific |publisher=[[UPI]]|date=January 30, 1993 |access-date=November 14, 2019}}</ref> spending most of his commissioned service in Joint Service assignments.<ref>http://www.fruitdalecc.org</ref>  He was the commander of the [[NATO]] base at [[Lampedusa Island]], Italy, from 1988 to 1989. During his tour of command, the U.S. Navy [[Gulf of Sidra incident (1989)|shot down two Libyan fighters]] in the area, causing Libyan dictator [[Muammar Gaddafi]] to threaten Armstrong's life, and bringing a media spotlight on the NATO base.<ref>{{Citation|title=Commanding Officer's Log, Loran Station Lampedusa (January 4\u20148, 1989)|publisher=United States Coast Guard}}</ref>\n\nOn May 10, 2019, Armstrong launched his campaign to seek the [[Libertarian Party (United States)|Libertarian Party]] [[2020 Libertarian Party presidential primaries|nomination]] in the [[2020 United States presidential election]].<ref name=\"Iowa\">{{Cite news|title=Libertarian candidate for President brings his campaign to North Iowa |url=https://www.kimt.com/content/news/Libertarian-candidate-for-President--512898891.html|website=[[KIMT]]|last1=Bunge|first1=Mike|date=July 18, 2019|access-date=November 14, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"vie\">{{Cite web|title=Candidates Vie to Represent the Libertarian Wing of the Libertarian Party |url=https://reason.com/2019/11/07/candidates-vie-to-represent-the-libertarian-wing-of-the-libertarian-party/ |website=[[Reason (magazine)|Reason]]|last1=Welch|first1=Matt|date=November 7, 2019|access-date=November 14, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and career==\nArmstrong was born on April 25, 1957 in [[Pasadena, California]]. He is a Weinberg Fellow of [[Hawaii Pacific University]].\n\nAs a federal healthcare executive, he worked with the [[Surgeon General of the United States]]. As a contingency planner, he was nominated as Federal Executive of the Year. He has dealt with issues in housing, poverty and mental health.\n\n==Military career==\nArmstrong enlisted in the [[United States Coast Guard]] in 1977.\n\nArmstrong's Coast Guard career included serving as\u00a0a [[NATO]] base commander and as a NATO/[[United Nations]] advisor in the [[Bosnian War]].<ref name=vie/> He was also a\u00a0representative to the [[Pelagie Islands]] for the U.S. [[Consul (representative)|Consul General]] at [[Palermo]].<ref name=Iowa/><ref name=\"center\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.heraldandnews.com/new-counseling-center-opens-in-klamath/article_1bb02372-f8c8-5c70-bb3e-54a76c883298.html |title=New counseling center opens in Klamath |work=[[Herald and News]] |date=November 3, 2002}} Retrieved November 14, 2019.</ref> \u00a0\n\nIn 1992, Armstrong commanded the humanitarian response detachment on the [[Kauai|Island of Kauai]] following [[Hurricane Iniki]].  Armstrong received the [[Coast Guard Commendation Medal]] and the [[Humanitarian Service Medal]] for the action.\n\nIn 1993, Armstrong was officer in charge of a NATO/[[United Nations]] [[Rules of Engagement]] (ROE) detachment aboard foreign naval vessels engaged in enforcing the blockade of [[Serbia and Montenegro]] in the [[Bosnian War]]. He received the [[NATO Medal|NATO Medal for Yugoslavia]] and later, retroactively received the [[Armed Forces Service Medal]].\n\nAlso in 1993, Armstrong led the U.S. Coast Guard's media response to the case of the MV ''East Wood'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9F0CEFD8133DF934A35751C0A965958260|title=Ship Distress Call Reveals 500 Being Smuggled In|newspaper=The New York Times|date=February 7, 1993|via=Reuters}}</ref> a vessel adrift in the Pacific Ocean with more than 500 Chinese refugees aboard. The incident started just days after [[Bill Clinton]] took office, and gained significant international attention. Armstrong made daily reports to the [[White House Situation Room]] during the incident. Armstrong again received a [[Coast Guard Commendation Medal]].\n\nHe retired from the Coast Guard in 1994.\n\n==Post-military career==\nArmstrong has been a [[nonprofit]] executive,<ref name=mars>{{Cite web|url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/2000/04/25/features/story3.html|title=Mars likes to fix everything... including Venus|work=[[Honolulu Star-Bulletin]]|last1=Oi|first1=Cynthia|date=April 25, 2000|accessdate=November 14, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bizjournals.com/pacific/stories/1999/03/29/smallb2.html|title=Out-of-office business easy here|website=[[Pacific Business News]]|accessdate=November 14, 2019|last1=Mangieri|first1=Gina|date=March 28, 1999}}</ref>\u00a0serving as Executive Director of [[Habitat for Humanity]]\u2019s Hawaii Statewide Organization.\n\nArmstrong has served as a columnist for ''[[Pacific Business News]]'' and was elected to the Honolulu County Neighborhood Board twice.<ref name=mars/><ref name=vie/>\u00a0\u00a0\n\n==2020 presidential campaign==\n{{see also|2020 Libertarian Party presidential primaries}}\n\nArmstrong announced in March 2019 that he had formed a [[exploratory committee]] to consider a run for the 2020 Libertarian nomination for [[President of the United States]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8EseFjZCiJc|title=Announcing Exploratory Committee for possible 2020 run for POTUS|website=YouTube|last1=Armstrong|first1=Ken|date=March 8, 2019}}</ref>\u00a0On May 10, 2019, he officially announced his candidacy.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qecqVmcVBrs|title=Ken Armstrong for President Kickoff Speech|date=May 19, 2019|last1=Armstrong|first1=Ken}}</ref><ref name=Iowa/><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.kxnet.com/news/web-extra-homeless-presidential-candidate-campaigns-in-bismarck-2/ |title=WEB EXTRA: \u201cHomeless\u201d presidential candidate campaigns in Bismarck |website=[[KXNet]]|date=June 5, 2019|access-date=November 15, 2019}}</ref>\u00a0\n\nHis campaign originally relied heavily on travel by car,<ref name=Iowa/> but on March 17, 2020 he announced a transition over to virtual campaigning in light of the [[COVID-19 crisis]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/photo.php?fbid=10159547288084745|title=Ken Armstrong|website=[[Facebook]]|accessdate=March 18, 2020}}</ref> His campaign performed poorly in early Libertarian primaries and caucuses. However, his stronger performances in later primaries, particularly in California, have netted him 4th place in the overall votes in the [[2020 Libertarian Party presidential primaries]]. To support his efforts, he has launched a campaign podcast called The Commander's Table.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/armstrongPOTUS2020/posts/236752891015571|title=Ken Armstrong|website=[[Facebook]]|accessdate=April 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n{{Endorsements box\n| title = Endorsements\n| list =\n;Party officials\n* Adam Reinhardt, Chair of the Monroe County Libertarian Party (Pennsylvania)<ref name=\"Endorsements\"/>\n* Duane Whitmer, Erie County Libertarian Party Chair, Candidates for U.S. House, New York's 27th District<ref name=\"Endorsements\"/>\n\n;Individuals\n* Tonya Millis, Candidate for U.S. House, Indiana's 9th District<ref name=\"Endorsements\">{{cite web|title=Endorsements|accessdate=April 23, 2020|url=https://armstrong2020.com/endorsements/|website=Ken Armstrong for President}}</ref>\n* Oscar Herrera, Candidate for Ohio State House, 96th District<ref name=\"Endorsements\"/>\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.armstrong2020.com Armstrong2020.com], official presidential campaign website\n*[https://www.iheart.com/podcast/139-brian-thomas-55krc-25690995/episode/ken-armstrong-2020-49729120/ Brian Thomas Morning Show at 55KRC, Cincinnati (iHeart Radio)]\n*[http://voicesofreason.bonneville.libsynpro.com/ Voices of Reason Podcast at KSL (NBC), Salt Lake City]\n*[https://www.kxnet.com/news/bismarck-news/web-extra-homeless-presidential-candidate-campaigns-in-bismarck/2054847049 KX Net (CBS), Bismarck, North Dakota]\n*[https://www.kimt.com/content/news/Libertarian-candidate-for-President--512898891.html?a KIMT (CBS), Mason City, Iowa]\n\n{{2020 United States presidential election}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Armstrong, Ken}}\n[[Category:1957 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American columnists]]\n[[Category:American libertarians]]\n[[Category:American nonprofit executives]]\n[[Category:Candidates in the 2020 United States presidential election]]\n[[Category:Hawaii local politicians]]\n[[Category:Libertarian Party (United States) politicians]]\n[[Category:United States Coast Guard officers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Ken Armstrong\n| image              = File:Ken Armstrong POTUS46 Headshot.jpg\n| alt                = \n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = Kenneth Reed Armstrong\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1957|04|25}}\n| birth_place        = [[Pasadena, California|Pesadena]], [[California]], U.S.\n| residence          = [[Selma, Oregon|Selma]], [[Oregon]], U.S.\n| nationality        = \n| citizenship        = \n| other_names        = \n| known_for          = Candidate for the Libertarian nomination for President in 2020\n| education          = Weinberg Fellow, [[Hawaii Pacific University]]\n| occupation         = \n| years_active       = \n| home_town          = \n| title              = \n| term               = \n| predecessor        = \n| successor          = \n| party              = [[Libertarian Party (United States)|Libertarian Party]]\n| opponents          = \n| boards             = \n| spouse             = Dawn Midori Kaneshiro Armstrong\n| children           = \n| parents            = \n| relations          = \n| callsign           = \n| website            = https://www.armstrong2020.com\n| awards             = \n| signature          = \n| footnotes          = \n| box_width          = \n| module             = {{Infobox military person|embed=yes\n|allegiance = United States\n|branch=United States Coast Guard\n|serviceyears= 1977\u20131994\n|rank = [[File:US-O3_insignia.svg|18px]] [[Lieutenant]]\n}}\n}}\n'''Kenneth Reed Armstrong''' (born April 25, 1957) is an American military officer, author, speaker, and politican. He served as a [[commissioned officer]] in the [[United States Coast Guard]],<ref>Allen, David\u00a0 (February 5, 1993). \"CG looks for hijacked freighter\" ''[[Pacific Stars and Stripes]]''. Retrieved November 14, 2019.</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.upi.com/Archives/1993/01/30/Coast-Guard-reports-possible-vessel-hijacking-in-Pacific/4824728370000/ |title=Coast Guard reports possible vessel hijacking in Pacific |publisher=[[UPI]]|date=January 30, 1993 |access-date=November 14, 2019}}</ref> spending most of his commissioned service in Joint Service assignments.<ref>http://www.fruitdalecc.org</ref>  He was the commander of the [[NATO]] base at [[Lampedusa Island]], Italy, from 1988 to 1989. During his tour of command, the U.S. Navy [[Gulf of Sidra incident (1989)|shot down two Libyan fighters]] in the area, causing Libyan dictator [[Muammar Gaddafi]] to threaten Armstrong's life, and bringing a media spotlight on the NATO base.<ref>{{Citation|title=Commanding Officer's Log, Loran Station Lampedusa (January 4\u20148, 1989)|publisher=United States Coast Guard}}</ref>\n\nOn May 10, 2019, Armstrong launched his campaign to seek the [[Libertarian Party (United States)|Libertarian Party]] [[2020 Libertarian Party presidential primaries|nomination]] in the [[2020 United States presidential election]].<ref name=\"Iowa\">{{Cite news|title=Libertarian candidate for President brings his campaign to North Iowa |url=https://www.kimt.com/content/news/Libertarian-candidate-for-President--512898891.html|website=[[KIMT]]|last1=Bunge|first1=Mike|date=July 18, 2019|access-date=November 14, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"vie\">{{Cite web|title=Candidates Vie to Represent the Libertarian Wing of the Libertarian Party |url=https://reason.com/2019/11/07/candidates-vie-to-represent-the-libertarian-wing-of-the-libertarian-party/ |website=[[Reason (magazine)|Reason]]|last1=Welch|first1=Matt|date=November 7, 2019|access-date=November 14, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and career==\nArmstrong was born on April 25, 1957 in [[Pasadena, California]]. He is a Weinberg Fellow of [[Hawaii Pacific University]].\n\nAs a federal healthcare executive, he worked with the [[Surgeon General of the United States]]. As a [[contingency planner]], he was nominated as Federal Executive of the Year. He has dealt with issues in housing, poverty and mental health.\n\n==Military career==\nArmstrong enlisted in the [[United States Coast Guard]] in 1977.\n\nArmstrong's Coast Guard career included serving as\u00a0a [[NATO]] base commander and as a NATO/[[United Nations]] advisor in the [[Bosnian War]].<ref name=vie/> He was also a\u00a0representative to the [[Pelagie Islands]] for the U.S. [[Consul (representative)|Consul General]] at [[Palermo]].<ref name=Iowa/><ref name=\"center\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.heraldandnews.com/new-counseling-center-opens-in-klamath/article_1bb02372-f8c8-5c70-bb3e-54a76c883298.html |title=New counseling center opens in Klamath |work=[[Herald and News]] |date=November 3, 2002}} Retrieved November 14, 2019.</ref> \u00a0\n\nIn 1992, Armstrong commanded the humanitarian response detachment on the [[Kauai|Island of Kauai]] following [[Hurricane Iniki]].  Armstrong received the [[Coast Guard Commendation Medal]] and the [[Humanitarian Service Medal]] for the action.\n\nIn 1993, Armstrong was officer in charge of a NATO/[[United Nations]] [[Rules of Engagement]] (ROE) detachment aboard foreign naval vessels engaged in enforcing the blockade of [[Serbia and Montenegro]] in the [[Bosnian War]]. He received the [[NATO Medal|NATO Medal for Yugoslavia]] and later, retroactively received the [[Armed Forces Service Medal]].\n\nAlso in 1993, Armstrong led the U.S. Coast Guard's media response to the case of the MV ''East Wood'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9F0CEFD8133DF934A35751C0A965958260|title=Ship Distress Call Reveals 500 Being Smuggled In|newspaper=The New York Times|date=February 7, 1993|via=Reuters}}</ref> a vessel adrift in the Pacific Ocean with more than 500 Chinese refugees aboard. The incident started just days after [[Bill Clinton]] took office, and gained significant international attention. Armstrong made daily reports to the [[White House Situation Room]] during the incident. Armstrong again received a [[Coast Guard Commendation Medal]].\n\nHe retired from the Coast Guard in 1994.\n\n==Post-military career==\nArmstrong has been a [[nonprofit]] executive,<ref name=mars>{{Cite web|url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/2000/04/25/features/story3.html|title=Mars likes to fix everything... including Venus|work=[[Honolulu Star-Bulletin]]|last1=Oi|first1=Cynthia|date=April 25, 2000|accessdate=November 14, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bizjournals.com/pacific/stories/1999/03/29/smallb2.html|title=Out-of-office business easy here|website=[[Pacific Business News]]|accessdate=November 14, 2019|last1=Mangieri|first1=Gina|date=March 28, 1999}}</ref>\u00a0serving as Executive Director of [[Habitat for Humanity]]\u2019s Hawaii Statewide Organization.\n\nArmstrong has served as a columnist for ''[[Pacific Business News]]'' and was elected to the Honolulu County Neighborhood Board twice.<ref name=mars/><ref name=vie/>\u00a0\u00a0\n\n==2020 presidential campaign==\n{{see also|2020 Libertarian Party presidential primaries}}\n\nArmstrong announced in March 2019 that he had formed a [[exploratory committee]] to consider a run for the 2020 Libertarian nomination for [[President of the United States]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8EseFjZCiJc|title=Announcing Exploratory Committee for possible 2020 run for POTUS|website=YouTube|last1=Armstrong|first1=Ken|date=March 8, 2019}}</ref>\u00a0On May 10, 2019, he officially announced his candidacy.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qecqVmcVBrs|title=Ken Armstrong for President Kickoff Speech|date=May 19, 2019|last1=Armstrong|first1=Ken}}</ref><ref name=Iowa/><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.kxnet.com/news/web-extra-homeless-presidential-candidate-campaigns-in-bismarck-2/ |title=WEB EXTRA: \u201cHomeless\u201d presidential candidate campaigns in Bismarck |website=[[KXNet]]|date=June 5, 2019|access-date=November 15, 2019}}</ref>\u00a0\n\nHis campaign originally relied heavily on travel by car,<ref name=Iowa/> but on March 17, 2020 he announced a transition over to virtual campaigning in light of the [[COVID-19 crisis]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/photo.php?fbid=10159547288084745|title=Ken Armstrong|website=[[Facebook]]|accessdate=March 18, 2020}}</ref> His campaign performed poorly in early Libertarian primaries and caucuses. However, his stronger performances in later primaries, particularly in California, have netted him 4th place in the overall votes in the [[2020 Libertarian Party presidential primaries]]. To support his efforts, he has launched a campaign podcast called The Commander's Table.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/armstrongPOTUS2020/posts/236752891015571|title=Ken Armstrong|website=[[Facebook]]|accessdate=April 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n{{Endorsements box\n| title = Endorsements\n| list =\n;Party officials\n* Adam Reinhardt, Chair of the Monroe County Libertarian Party (Pennsylvania)<ref name=\"Endorsements\"/>\n* Duane Whitmer, Erie County Libertarian Party Chair, Candidates for U.S. House, New York's 27th District<ref name=\"Endorsements\"/>\n\n;Individuals\n* Tonya Millis, Candidate for U.S. House, Indiana's 9th District<ref name=\"Endorsements\">{{cite web|title=Endorsements|accessdate=April 23, 2020|url=https://armstrong2020.com/endorsements/|website=Ken Armstrong for President}}</ref>\n* Oscar Herrera, Candidate for Ohio State House, 96th District<ref name=\"Endorsements\"/>\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.armstrong2020.com Armstrong2020.com], official presidential campaign website\n*[https://www.iheart.com/podcast/139-brian-thomas-55krc-25690995/episode/ken-armstrong-2020-49729120/ Brian Thomas Morning Show at 55KRC, Cincinnati (iHeart Radio)]\n*[http://voicesofreason.bonneville.libsynpro.com/ Voices of Reason Podcast at KSL (NBC), Salt Lake City]\n*[https://www.kxnet.com/news/bismarck-news/web-extra-homeless-presidential-candidate-campaigns-in-bismarck/2054847049 KX Net (CBS), Bismarck, North Dakota]\n*[https://www.kimt.com/content/news/Libertarian-candidate-for-President--512898891.html?a KIMT (CBS), Mason City, Iowa]\n\n{{2020 United States presidential election}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Armstrong, Ken}}\n[[Category:1957 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American columnists]]\n[[Category:American libertarians]]\n[[Category:American nonprofit executives]]\n[[Category:Candidates in the 2020 United States presidential election]]\n[[Category:Hawaii local politicians]]\n[[Category:Libertarian Party (United States) politicians]]\n[[Category:United States Coast Guard officers]]\n", "name_user": "Sal2100", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEarly life and career:no article for that, so unlinked", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ken_Armstrong_(politician)"}
{"title_page": "The Idiot (album)", "text_new": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = The Idiot\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Iggy Pop]]\n| cover      = Iggy Pop - The Idiot.png\n| alt        =\n| released   = {{Start date|1977|03|18}}\n| recorded   = July \u2013 August 1976\n| venue      =\n| studio     = {{Unbulleted list|[[Ch\u00e2teau d'H\u00e9rouville]], [[H\u00e9rouville-en-Vexin|H\u00e9rouville]]|[[Musicland Studios]], [[Munich]]|[[Hansa Tonstudio|Hansa Studio 1]], [[Berlin]]}}\n| genre      = {{hlist|[[Art rock]]<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/blah-blah-blah-mw0000191320 | title=Iggy Pop \u2013 Blah-Blah-Blah review | work=[[AllMusic]] | accessdate=July 15, 2015 | author=Deming, Mark}}</ref><ref name=\"Vinyl\">{{cite web|last1=Little|first1=Michael H.|title=Iggy Pop, The Idiot|url=http://www.thevinyldistrict.com/storefront/2016/03/graded-on-a-curve-iggy-pop-the-idiot/|website=The Vinyl District|access-date=4 June 2016}}</ref>|[[gothic rock]]<ref>{{Cite book |last1=Thompson |first1=Dave |title=The Dark Reign of Gothic Rock: In the Reptile House with the Sisters of Mercy, Bauhaus and the Cure|date=2002 |publisher=Helter Skelter |url=https://books.google.com/books/about/The_Dark_Reign_of_Gothic_Rock.html?id=vWkq4X_VBAIC}}</ref>|[[industrial rock]]<ref name=\"stockholm\">{{Cite web|title=GIG HIGHLIGHT: IGGY POP|url=http://totallystockholm.se/music/gig-highlight-iggy-pop/|website=Totally Stockholm|access-date=14 February 2017}}</ref>}}\n| length     = 38:49\n| label      = [[RCA Records|RCA]]\n| producer   = [[David Bowie]]\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title = [[Lust for Life (Iggy Pop album)|Lust for Life]]\n| next_year  = 1977\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = The Idiot\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = Sister Midnight\" / \"Baby\n | single1date = February 1977\n | single2     = [[China Girl (song)|China Girl]]\" / \"Baby\n | single2date = May 1977\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''The Idiot''''' is the debut solo album by American musician [[Iggy Pop]], released on March 18, 1977 by [[RCA Records]]. It was the first of two albums that Pop wrote and recorded in collaboration with [[David Bowie]], who is credited as producer. The sessions for the album began before the recording of Bowie's 1977 album ''[[Low (David Bowie album)|Low]]''; as a result, ''The Idiot'' has been called the unofficial beginning of Bowie's [[Berlin Trilogy|Berlin period]].<ref name=\"Wilcken\">{{cite book |last=Wilcken |first=Hugo |year=2005 |title=Low |pages=37\u201358}}</ref>\n\nDescribed by Pop as \"a cross between [[James Brown]] and [[Kraftwerk]],\"<ref name=\"auto\"/> ''The Idiot'' marked a departure from the [[guitar]]-based [[proto-punk]] of his former band [[the Stooges]], and has been compared with Bowie's \"[[Berlin Trilogy]]\" of albums in its [[electronic music|electronic]] sounds and introspective atmosphere.<ref name=\"Carr\">{{cite book |last1=Carr |first1=Roy |author1link=Roy Carr |last2=Murray |first2=Charles Shaar |authorlink2=Charles Shaar Murray |year=1981 |title=Bowie: An Illustrated Record |page=118}}</ref><ref name=\"Deming\">{{cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/the-idiot-mw0000204192 |title=''The Idiot'' \u2013 Iggy Pop <nowiki>| Songs, Reviews, Credits, Awards |</nowiki> AllMusic |last=Deming |first=Mark |website=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=8 December 2014}}</ref> Its title was taken from [[Fyodor Dostoevsky]]'s [[The Idiot|novel of the same title]], three of the participants in the recording&nbsp;\u2014 Bowie, Pop, and [[Tony Visconti]]&nbsp;\u2014 being familiar with the book.<ref name=\"Trynka\">{{cite book |last=[[Paul Trynka]] |year=2007 |title=Iggy Pop: Open Up and Bleed |url=https://archive.org/details/iggypopopenupble00tryn |url-access=registration |pages=[https://archive.org/details/iggypopopenupble00tryn/page/242 242\u2013250]}}</ref>\n\n''The Idiot'' received critical acclaim upon its release, and is regarded by many as one of Pop's best works; however, it is not generally considered representative of his output. The album has been characterized as a major influence on subsequent [[post-punk]], [[industrial music|industrial]], and [[Gothic rock|gothic]] artists.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web |url=http://www.clashmusic.com/feature/classic-albums-iggy-pop-the-idiot |title=Classic Albums: Iggy Pop \u2013 ''The Idiot'' <nowiki>| Features |</nowiki> Clash Music |last=Arber |first=Amanda |date=16 March 2012 |website=Clash |accessdate=8 December 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Stereo\">{{cite web|last1=Freeman|first1=Phil|title=Iggy Pop Albums From Worst To Best|url=https://www.stereogum.com/1865856/iggy-pop-albums-from-worst-to-best/franchises/counting-down%3Famp%3D1|website=[[Stereogum]]|accessdate=5 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Production ==\nThe album's opening track, \"Sister Midnight\", was written by Bowie, Pop and guitarist [[Carlos Alomar]], and performed live on the ''[[Station to Station]]'' tour in early 1976. In July that year, following the end of the tour, Bowie and Pop holed up in [[Ch\u00e2teau d'H\u00e9rouville]], the same locale where Bowie recorded ''[[Pin Ups]]'' (1973) and would soon record much of ''Low'', and began putting together the rest of the songs that later became ''The Idiot''. At the Ch\u00e2teau they were augmented by Laurent Thibault on bass and Michel Santangeli on drums, who were required, with minimal guidance, to add to rough music tracks already taped by Bowie, their first takes often becoming part of the final mix.<ref name=\"Trynka\"/>\n\nRecording continued in August at [[Musicland Studios|Musicland]] in [[Munich]], Germany with guitarist [[Phil Palmer]], who found the creative collaboration with Pop and Bowie stimulating but disquieting, never seeing them around during the day (\"[[Vampire|Vampiric]] would be the perfect word\", he said later).<ref name=\"Trynka\"/> Overdubs by Bowie's regular rhythm section of Carlos Alomar, [[Dennis Davis]] and [[George Murray (musician)|George Murray]], plus a final mix by Tony Visconti, took place in [[Berlin]] at [[Hansa Records|Hansa Studio 1]] (not, as is often incorrectly reported, the bigger Studio 2 by the [[Berlin Wall]]).<ref name=\"Trynka\"/> Given the almost demo quality of the tapes, the post-production work was, in Visconti's words, \"more of a salvage job than a creative mixing\".<ref name=\"Strange Fascination\">{{cite book |last=Buckley |first=David |year=1999 |title=Strange Fascination \u2013 David Bowie: The Definitive Story |pages=298, 315\u2013318}}</ref>\n\nBecause of its ambiguous and in some cases non-existent credits, misconceptions have arisen over the years as to who contributed what to the album. Although the common belief that Pop wrote the lyrics while Bowie composed the music is generally accurate, their approach occasionally saw the positions change, with some music (such as \"Dum Dum Boys\") being Pop's and some lyrics (including the first verse to \"Sister Midnight\") being Bowie's.<ref name=\"Wilcken\"/> The album's cover photo, inspired by [[Erich Heckel]]'s Roquairol, is often assumed to be by Bowie but was in fact taken by Andy Kent.<ref name=\"Strange Fascination\"/>{{sfn|Pegg|2000|pp=382\u2013383}} No instrumental credits were included on the sleeve, causing some speculation as to the musicians involved;<ref name=\"Carr\"/> however, recent works by Hugo Wilcken, [[Paul Trynka]] and [[Nicholas Pegg]] have provided a generally agreed list of the personnel involved.<ref name=\"Wilcken\"/><ref name=\"Trynka\"/>{{sfn|Pegg|2000|pp=382\u2013383}}\n\n== Style and themes ==\nAt the time of its release, Pop described ''The Idiot'' as a cross between [[James Brown]] and [[Kraftwerk]].<ref name=\"auto\"/> Bowie biographer David Buckley has called it \"a funky, [[robot]]ic Hellhole of an album\".<ref name=\"Strange Fascination\"/> The funk influence was most pronounced on \"Sister Midnight\", based on a riff by Carlos Alomar and laced with Pop's [[Oedipus complex|oedipal]] dream imagery. Its lack of overtly electronic instrumentation belied what critic Dave Thompson has described as a \"defiantly futuristic ambience\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/song/sister-midnight-mt0010705960 |title=''Sister Midnight'' \u2013 Iggy Pop <nowiki>| Listen, Appearances, Song Review |</nowiki> AllMusic |last=Thompson |first=Dave |website=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=8 December 2014}}</ref>\n\nPop, speaking of Bowie, described the [[Krautrock]]-influenced \"[[Nightclubbing (song)|Nightclubbing]]\" as \"my comment on what it was like hanging out with him every night\". The track was recorded one night after the other musicians had left, Bowie playing the melody on piano with an old [[drum machine|rhythm machine]] for backing. When Pop pronounced himself happy with the result, Bowie protested that they needed real drums to finish it off. Pop insisted on keeping the rhythm machine, saying \"it kicks ass, it's better than a drummer\". Pop largely wrote the lyrics on the spot \"in ten minutes\", Bowie suggesting that he write about \"walking through the night like ghosts\".{{sfn|Pegg|2000|pp=152\u2013153}} The riff has been described as a mischievous quote of [[Gary Glitter]]'s \"[[Rock and Roll (Gary Glitter song)|Rock and Roll]]\".<ref name=\"Trynka\"/>\n\n\"[[China Girl (song)|China Girl]]\", originally called \"Borderline\", was a tale of unrequited love inspired by Kuelan Nguyen, partner of French actor-singer [[Jacques Higelin]], who was also recording at Ch\u00e2teau d'H\u00e9rouville at the time. The protagonist's \"Shhh...\" was a direct quote from Nguyen after Pop confessed his feelings for her one night.<ref name=\"Trynka\"/> Production-wise it was raw and unpolished compared to Bowie's hit remake in 1983.{{sfn|Pegg|2000|pp=382\u2013383}} Other songs included \"[[Funtime (Iggy Pop song)|Funtime]]\", a proto-[[gothic rock|gothic]] number that Bowie advised Pop to sing \"like [[Mae West]]\";<ref name=\"Wilcken\"/> \"Dum Dum Boys\", a tribute/lament for Pop's former Stooges bandmates (the spoken intro references [[Zeke Zettner]], [[Dave Alexander (musician)|Dave Alexander]], [[Scott Asheton]] and [[James Williamson (musician)|James Williamson]]) and \"Mass Production\", a harsh, grinding piece of early [[industrial music|industrial]] [[electronica]].<ref name=\"Wilcken\"/>\n\n== Release ==\n=== Original edition ===\nAlthough the bulk of ''The Idiot'' was recorded before ''Low'', the initial installment of the \"Berlin Trilogy\", Bowie's album was released first in January 1977, while Pop's was held over until March. Laurent Thibault opined that \"David didn't want people to think he'd been inspired by Iggy's album, when in fact it was all the same thing\".<ref name=\"Wilcken\"/> In 1981, ''[[NME]]'' editors [[Roy Carr]] and [[Charles Shaar Murray]] suggested that ''The Idiot''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s electronic sound had been \"pioneered\" on ''Low'',<ref name=\"Carr\"/> whereas by 2000, Nicholas Pegg would describe it as \"a stepping stone between ''Station to Station'' and ''Low''.{{sfn|Pegg|2000|pp=382\u2013383}}\n\n\"Sister Midnight\" and \"China Girl\" were released as singles in February and May 1977, respectively, both with the same B-side \"Baby\".<ref>{{cite book |last=Strong |first=Martin C. |year=2002 |title=The Great Rock Discography |edition=6th |pages=815\u2013816}}</ref>\n\n===2020 Deluxe edition===\nOn April 10, 2020, Pop released an alternate mix of his hit song \"[[China Girl (song)|China Girl]]\" as part of the forthcoming release on May 29 of ''The Bowie Years'', a new seven-disc Deluxe box set due to feature expanded remastered versions of his David Bowie-produced albums ''The Idiot'' and ''[[Lust for Life (Iggy Pop album)|Lust for Life]]'', both originally released in 1977. The box set is due to include remastered versions of both 1977 studio projects along with outtakes, alternate mixes and a 40-page book. As well, the two original albums are due to be paired with an additional album of live material to create separate stand-alone two-disc Deluxe editions.<ref>[https://ultimateclassicrock.com/iggy-pop-the-bowie-years/?utm_source=tsmclip&utm_medium=referral Ultimate Classic Rock > Iggy Pop Box Set to Focus on First Two David Bowie-Produced LPs (by Nick Deriso, April 10, 2020)]</ref>\n\n== Reception ==\n=== Critical reception ===\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1score = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref name=\"Deming\"/>\n| rev2 = ''[[Blender (magazine)|Blender]]''\n| rev2score = {{rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://blender.com/guide/reviews.aspx?id=2623 |title=Iggy Pop: The Idiot |work=[[Blender (magazine)|Blender]] |date=September 2004 |accessdate=August 11, 2016 |last=Smith |first=RJ |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060630184015/http://blender.com/guide/reviews.aspx?id=2623 |archivedate=June 30, 2006}}</ref>\n| rev3 = ''[[Chicago Tribune]]''\n| rev3score = {{rating|3|4}}<ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1990-07-22/entertainment/9003010792_1_star-stooges-atmospheric-art-rock |title=Pop On Pop: Iggy Rates His Own Music (and So Do We) |work=[[Chicago Tribune]] |date=July 22, 1990 |accessdate=August 11, 2016 |last=Kot |first=Greg |authorlink=Greg Kot}}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''[[Christgau's Record Guide: Rock Albums of the Seventies|Christgau's Record Guide]]''\n| rev4score = A\u2212<ref>{{cite book |chapter-url=http://www.robertchristgau.com/get_album.php?id=1599 |chapter=Iggy Pop: The Idiot |accessdate=December 8, 2014 |title=Christgau's Record Guide: Rock Albums of the '70s |last=Christgau |first=Robert |authorlink=Robert Christgau |publisher=[[Ticknor and Fields]] |year=1981 |isbn=0-89919-026-X |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/christgausrecord00robe_1 }}</ref>\n| rev5 = ''[[Encyclopedia of Popular Music]]''\n| rev5Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite book |title=[[Encyclopedia of Popular Music|The Encyclopedia of Popular Music]] |last=Larkin |first=Colin | authorlink=Colin Larkin |publisher=[[Omnibus Press]] |edition=5th concise |year=2011 |isbn=0-85712-595-8}}</ref>\n| rev6 = ''[[Q (magazine)|Q]]''\n| rev6score = {{rating|5|5}}<ref>{{cite journal |title=Iggy Pop: The Idiot |work=[[Q (magazine)|Q]] |issue=402 |date=September 2019 |page=106}}</ref>\n| rev7 = ''[[The Rolling Stone Album Guide]]''\n| rev7Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite book |chapter=Iggy Pop |last1=Coleman |first1=Mark |last2=Kemp |first2=Rob |title=[[The Rolling Stone Album Guide|The New Rolling Stone Album Guide]] |edition=4th |year=2004 |editor1-last=Brackett |editor1-first=Nathan |editor2-last=Hoard |editor2-first=Christian |publisher=[[Simon & Schuster]] |isbn=0-7432-0169-8 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/newrollingstonea00brac/page/645 645\u201346] }}</ref>\n| rev8 = ''[[Spin Alternative Record Guide]]''\n| rev8score = 7/10<ref name=\"Spin\">{{cite book |last1=Weisbard |first1=Eric |last2=Marks |first2=Craig |title=[[Spin Alternative Record Guide]] |year=1995 |publisher=[[Vintage Books]] |isbn=0-679-75574-8 |page=378}}</ref>\n}}\n\nBiographer Paul Trynka wrote that ''The Idiot'' \"would remain an album that was more respected than loved, the reviews mostly neutral\", but that it \"prefigured the soul of [[post-punk]]\".<ref name=\"Trynka\"/> In a contemporary review of the album, ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' termed it \"the most savage indictment of rock posturing ever recorded\" and \"a necrophiliac's delight\".<ref name=\"Rolling Stone\">{{cite journal |last=Swenson |first=John |date=5 May 1977 |title=<nowiki>[</nowiki>''The Idiot'' review<nowiki>]</nowiki> |magazine=[[Rolling Stone]] |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/the-idiot-19770505 |accessdate=8 December 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== Charts ===\n''The Idiot'' peaked at number 72 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' Top 200 Albums Chart]], and also reached number 30 on the [[UK Albums Chart]], marking the first time an Iggy Pop album had cracked the top 40.\n\n== Legacy ==\nWhile the album has become highly praised in its own right over the years, fans of Iggy Pop have criticized the work as unrepresentative of his repertoire and as evidence of his being \"co-opted\" by Bowie for the latter's own ends.<ref name=\"Strange Fascination\"/><ref name=\"Gimme Danger\">{{cite book |last=Ambrose |first=Joe |year=2004 |title=Gimme Danger: The Story of Iggy Pop |pages=175\u2013178}}</ref> Bowie himself later admitted:\n\n{{Quote | style=font-size:100% | Poor Jim, in a way, became a guinea pig for what I wanted to do with sound. I didn't have the material at the time, and I didn't feel like writing at all. I felt much more like laying back and getting behind someone else's work, so that album was opportune, creatively.<ref>[[Kurt Loder]] & [[David Bowie]] (1989). ''[[Sound + Vision (box set)|Sound + Vision]]'': CD liner notes</ref>}}\n\nBowie later re-worked \"Sister Midnight\" with new lyrics as \"Red Money\" on his 1979 album ''[[Lodger (album)|Lodger]]'', while his version of \"China Girl\" on 1983's ''[[Let's Dance (David Bowie album)|Let's Dance]]'' became a major hit.\n\nPop has called ''The Idiot'' his \"album of freedom\".<ref name=\"Gimme Danger\"/> [[Siouxsie Sioux]] described it as \"re-affirmation that our suspicions were true \u2013 the man was a genius and what a voice!\"<ref name=\"Gimme Danger\"/> and she performed \"Nightclubbing\" with her second band [[the Creatures]] at the [[Glastonbury Festival|Glastonbury festival]] in 1999.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tsngzxmUF3M&t=213s \"Siouxsie / The Creatures Glastonbury\"]. Youtube. Retrieved 2 November 2019.</ref> The album has been cited as a major influence on a number of acts, including [[Depeche Mode]], [[Nine Inch Nails]], and [[Joy Division]] - the lead singer of Joy Division, [[Ian Curtis]], committed suicide in 1980 with the record still playing on his turntable.{{sfn|Pegg|2000|pp=382\u2013383}} [[Killing Joke]]'s [[Youth (musician)|Youth]] also described ''The Idiot'' as one of his favorite albums.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://thequietus.com/articles/05965-killing-joke-youth-favourite-records |title=The Quietus <nowiki>| Features | Baker's Dozen |</nowiki> Killing Joke's Youth on His 13 Favourite Records |date=29 March 2011 |website=[[The Quietus]] |accessdate=8 December 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 1981, [[Grace Jones]] covered the song \"Nightclubbing\" as the title track to her album [[Nightclubbing (Grace Jones album)|of the same name]]. Pop's version of \"Nightclubbing\" provided the [[Bass drum|kick drum]] sound for Nine Inch Nails' 1994 song \"[[Closer (Nine Inch Nails song)|Closer]]\". The drum loop of \"Nightclubbing\" was also duplicated by [[Oasis (band)|Oasis]] for the song \"Force of Nature\" on their 2002 album ''[[Heathen Chemistry]]''. \"Nightclubbing\" was also sampled in the song \"Small Town Witch\" by the British band [[Sneaker Pimps]] on their 2002 album ''[[Bloodsport (album)|Bloodsport]]''.\n\n== Live performances ==\n\"Nightclubbing\" and \"Funtime\" appeared on the 1978 live set ''[[TV Eye Live 1977|TV Eye]]'', recorded during Pop's 1977 tour, the UK and portions of the US leg of which featured Bowie on keyboards and backing vocals.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\nMost of the album was performed alongside ''Lust for Life'' material during the 2016 spring tour by Pop and his new band featuring [[Josh Homme]], [[Dean Fertita]] and [[Troy Van Leeuwen]] from [[Queens of the Stone Age]] and [[Matt Helders]] from [[Arctic Monkeys]], as part of the promotion for ''[[Post Pop Depression]]'', an album self-referential to Pop's Berlin period. Tracks such as \"Mass Production\" and \"Baby\" were performed live in some cases for the first time since they were released.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\n== Track listing ==\nAll tracks are written by [[Iggy Pop]] and [[David Bowie]], except \"Sister Midnight\", co-written by [[Carlos Alomar]].\n\n;Side one\n# \"Sister Midnight\" \u2013 4:19\n# \"[[Nightclubbing (song)|Nightclubbing]]\" \u2013 4:14\n# \"[[Funtime (Iggy Pop song)|Funtime]]\" \u2013 2:54\n# \"Baby\" \u2013 3:24\n# \"[[China Girl (song)|China Girl]]\" \u2013 5:08\n\n;Side one\n# \"Dum Dum Boys\" \u2013 7:12\n# \"Tiny Girls\" \u2013 2:59\n# \"Mass Production\" \u2013 8:24\n\n== Personnel ==\n* [[Iggy Pop]]&nbsp;\u2014 vocals\n* [[David Bowie]]&nbsp;\u2014 keyboards, synthesizer, guitar, piano, saxophone, xylophone, backing vocals, [[record producer|production]]\n* [[Carlos Alomar]]&nbsp;\u2014 guitar\n* [[Dennis Davis]]&nbsp;\u2014 drums\n* [[George Murray (musician)|George Murray]]&nbsp;\u2014 bass guitar\n* [[Phil Palmer]]&nbsp;\u2014 guitar\n* Michel Santangeli&nbsp;\u2014 drums\n* Laurent Thibault&nbsp;\u2014 bass\n* [[Tony Visconti]]&nbsp;\u2014 additional mixing\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n'''Sources'''\n* {{Cite book |last=Pegg |first=Nicholas |authorlink=Nicholas Pegg |year=2000 |title=The Complete David Bowie |ref=harv}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Discogs master|38306|The Idiot}}\n* [http://idiotlust.blogspot.com/ Iggy Pop's \"The Idiot\"]\n\n{{Iggy Pop}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Idiot, The (album)}}\n[[Category:Iggy Pop albums]]\n[[Category:1977 debut albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by David Bowie]]\n[[Category:RCA Records albums]]\n[[Category:Art rock albums by American artists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = The Idiot\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Iggy Pop]]\n| cover      = Iggy Pop - The Idiot.png\n| alt        =\n| released   = {{Start date|1977|03|18}}\n| recorded   = July \u2013 August 1976\n| venue      =\n| studio     = {{Unbulleted list|[[Ch\u00e2teau d'H\u00e9rouville]], [[H\u00e9rouville-en-Vexin|H\u00e9rouville]]|[[Musicland Studios]], [[Munich]]|[[Hansa Tonstudio|Hansa Studio 1]], [[Berlin]]}}\n| genre      = {{hlist|[[Art rock]]<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/blah-blah-blah-mw0000191320 | title=Iggy Pop \u2013 Blah-Blah-Blah review | work=[[AllMusic]] | accessdate=July 15, 2015 | author=Deming, Mark}}</ref><ref name=\"Vinyl\">{{cite web|last1=Little|first1=Michael H.|title=Iggy Pop, The Idiot|url=http://www.thevinyldistrict.com/storefront/2016/03/graded-on-a-curve-iggy-pop-the-idiot/|website=The Vinyl District|access-date=4 June 2016}}</ref>|[[gothic rock]]<ref>{{Cite book |last1=Thompson |first1=Dave |title=The Dark Reign of Gothic Rock: In the Reptile House with the Sisters of Mercy, Bauhaus and the Cure|date=2002 |publisher=Helter Skelter |url=https://books.google.com/books/about/The_Dark_Reign_of_Gothic_Rock.html?id=vWkq4X_VBAIC}}</ref>|[[industrial rock]]<ref name=\"stockholm\">{{Cite web|title=GIG HIGHLIGHT: IGGY POP|url=http://totallystockholm.se/music/gig-highlight-iggy-pop/|website=Totally Stockholm|access-date=14 February 2017}}</ref>}}\n| length     = 38:49\n| label      = [[RCA Records|RCA]]\n| producer   = [[David Bowie]]\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title = [[Lust for Life (Iggy Pop album)|Lust for Life]]\n| next_year  = 1977\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = The Idiot\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = Sister Midnight\" / \"Baby\n | single1date = February 1977\n | single2     = [[China Girl (song)|China Girl]]\" / \"Baby\n | single2date = May 1977\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''The Idiot''''' is the debut solo album by American musician [[Iggy Pop]], released on March 18, 1977 by [[RCA Records]]. It was the first of two albums that Pop wrote and recorded in collaboration with [[David Bowie]], who is credited as producer. The sessions for the album began before the recording of Bowie's 1977 album ''[[Low (David Bowie album)|Low]]''; as a result, ''The Idiot'' has been called the unofficial beginning of Bowie's [[Berlin Trilogy|Berlin period]].<ref name=\"Wilcken\">{{cite book |last=Wilcken |first=Hugo |year=2005 |title=Low |pages=37\u201358}}</ref>\n\nDescribed by Pop as \"a cross between [[James Brown]] and [[Kraftwerk]],\"<ref name=\"auto\"/> ''The Idiot'' marked a departure from the [[guitar]]-based [[proto-punk]] of his former band [[the Stooges]], and has been compared with Bowie's \"[[Berlin Trilogy]]\" of albums in its [[electronic music|electronic]] sounds and introspective atmosphere.<ref name=\"Carr\">{{cite book |last1=Carr |first1=Roy |author1link=Roy Carr |last2=Murray |first2=Charles Shaar |authorlink2=Charles Shaar Murray |year=1981 |title=Bowie: An Illustrated Record |page=118}}</ref><ref name=\"Deming\">{{cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/the-idiot-mw0000204192 |title=''The Idiot'' \u2013 Iggy Pop <nowiki>| Songs, Reviews, Credits, Awards |</nowiki> AllMusic |last=Deming |first=Mark |website=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=8 December 2014}}</ref> Its title was taken from [[Fyodor Dostoevsky]]'s [[The Idiot|novel of the same title]], three of the participants in the recording&nbsp;\u2014 Bowie, Pop, and [[Tony Visconti]]&nbsp;\u2014 being familiar with the book.<ref name=\"Trynka\">{{cite book |last=[[Paul Trynka]] |year=2007 |title=Iggy Pop: Open Up and Bleed |url=https://archive.org/details/iggypopopenupble00tryn |url-access=registration |pages=[https://archive.org/details/iggypopopenupble00tryn/page/242 242\u2013250]}}</ref>\n\n''The Idiot'' received critical acclaim upon its release, and is regarded by many as one of Pop's best works; however, it is not generally considered representative of his output. The album has been characterized as a major influence on subsequent [[post-punk]], [[industrial music|industrial]], and [[Gothic rock|gothic]] artists.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web |url=http://www.clashmusic.com/feature/classic-albums-iggy-pop-the-idiot |title=Classic Albums: Iggy Pop \u2013 ''The Idiot'' <nowiki>| Features |</nowiki> Clash Music |last=Arber |first=Amanda |date=16 March 2012 |website=Clash |accessdate=8 December 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Stereo\">{{cite web|last1=Freeman|first1=Phil|title=Iggy Pop Albums From Worst To Best|url=https://www.stereogum.com/1865856/iggy-pop-albums-from-worst-to-best/franchises/counting-down%3Famp%3D1|website=[[Stereogum]]|accessdate=5 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Production ==\nThe album's opening track, \"Sister Midnight\", was written by Bowie, Pop and guitarist [[Carlos Alomar]], and performed live on the ''[[Station to Station]]'' tour in early 1976. In July that year, following the end of the tour, Bowie and Pop holed up in [[Ch\u00e2teau d'H\u00e9rouville]], the same locale where Bowie recorded ''[[Pin Ups]]'' (1973) and would soon record much of ''Low'', and began putting together the rest of the songs that later became ''The Idiot''. At the Ch\u00e2teau they were augmented by Laurent Thibault on bass and Michel Santangeli on drums, who were required, with minimal guidance, to add to rough music tracks already taped by Bowie, their first takes often becoming part of the final mix.<ref name=\"Trynka\"/>\n\nRecording continued in August at [[Musicland Studios|Musicland]] in [[Munich]], Germany with guitarist [[Phil Palmer]], who found the creative collaboration with Pop and Bowie stimulating but disquieting, never seeing them around during the day (\"[[Vampire|Vampiric]] would be the perfect word\", he said later).<ref name=\"Trynka\"/> Overdubs by Bowie's regular rhythm section of Carlos Alomar, [[Dennis Davis]] and [[George Murray (musician)|George Murray]], plus a final mix by Tony Visconti, took place in [[Berlin]] at [[Hansa Records|Hansa Studio 1]] (not, as is often incorrectly reported, the bigger Studio 2 by the [[Berlin Wall]]).<ref name=\"Trynka\"/> Given the almost demo quality of the tapes, the post-production work was, in Visconti's words, \"more of a salvage job than a creative mixing\".<ref name=\"Strange Fascination\">{{cite book |last=Buckley |first=David |year=1999 |title=Strange Fascination \u2013 David Bowie: The Definitive Story |pages=298, 315\u2013318}}</ref>\n\nBecause of its ambiguous and in some cases non-existent credits, misconceptions have arisen over the years as to who contributed what to the album. Although the common belief that Pop wrote the lyrics while Bowie composed the music is generally accurate, their approach occasionally saw the positions change, with some music (such as \"Dum Dum Boys\") being Pop's and some lyrics (including the first verse to \"Sister Midnight\") being Bowie's.<ref name=\"Wilcken\"/> The album's cover photo, inspired by [[Erich Heckel]]'s Roquairol, is often assumed to be by Bowie but was in fact taken by Andy Kent.<ref name=\"Strange Fascination\"/>{{sfn|Pegg|2000|pp=382\u2013383}} No instrumental credits were included on the sleeve, causing some speculation as to the musicians involved;<ref name=\"Carr\"/> however, recent works by Hugo Wilcken, [[Paul Trynka]] and [[Nicholas Pegg]] have provided a generally agreed list of the personnel involved.<ref name=\"Wilcken\"/><ref name=\"Trynka\"/>{{sfn|Pegg|2000|pp=382\u2013383}}\n\n== Style and themes ==\nAt the time of its release, Pop described ''The Idiot'' as a cross between [[James Brown]] and [[Kraftwerk]].<ref name=\"auto\"/> Bowie biographer David Buckley has called it \"a funky, [[robot]]ic Hellhole of an album\".<ref name=\"Strange Fascination\"/> The funk influence was most pronounced on \"Sister Midnight\", based on a riff by Carlos Alomar and laced with Pop's [[Oedipus complex|oedipal]] dream imagery. Its lack of overtly electronic instrumentation belied what critic Dave Thompson has described as a \"defiantly futuristic ambience\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/song/sister-midnight-mt0010705960 |title=''Sister Midnight'' \u2013 Iggy Pop <nowiki>| Listen, Appearances, Song Review |</nowiki> AllMusic |last=Thompson |first=Dave |website=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=8 December 2014}}</ref>\n\nPop, speaking of Bowie, described the [[Krautrock]]-influenced \"[[Nightclubbing (song)|Nightclubbing]]\" as \"my comment on what it was like hanging out with him every night\". The track was recorded one night after the other musicians had left, Bowie playing the melody on piano with an old [[drum machine|rhythm machine]] for backing. When Pop pronounced himself happy with the result, Bowie protested that they needed real drums to finish it off. Pop insisted on keeping the rhythm machine, saying \"it kicks ass, it's better than a drummer\". Pop largely wrote the lyrics on the spot \"in ten minutes\", Bowie suggesting that he write about \"walking through the night like ghosts\".{{sfn|Pegg|2000|pp=152\u2013153}} The riff has been described as a mischievous quote of [[Gary Glitter]]'s \"[[Rock and Roll (Gary Glitter song)|Rock and Roll]]\".<ref name=\"Trynka\"/>\n\n\"[[China Girl (song)|China Girl]]\", originally called \"Borderline\", was a tale of unrequited love inspired by Kuelan Nguyen, partner of French actor-singer [[Jacques Higelin]], who was also recording at Ch\u00e2teau d'H\u00e9rouville at the time. The protagonist's \"Shhh...\" was a direct quote from Nguyen after Pop confessed his feelings for her one night.<ref name=\"Trynka\"/> Production-wise it was raw and unpolished compared to Bowie's hit remake in 1983.{{sfn|Pegg|2000|pp=382\u2013383}} Other songs included \"[[Funtime (Iggy Pop song)|Funtime]]\", a proto-[[gothic rock|gothic]] number that Bowie advised Pop to sing \"like [[Mae West]]\";<ref name=\"Wilcken\"/> \"Dum Dum Boys\", a tribute/lament for Pop's former Stooges bandmates (the spoken intro references [[Zeke Zettner]], [[Dave Alexander (musician)|Dave Alexander]], [[Scott Asheton]] and [[James Williamson (musician)|James Williamson]]) and \"Mass Production\", a harsh, grinding piece of early [[industrial music|industrial]] [[electronica]].<ref name=\"Wilcken\"/>\n\n== Release ==\n=== Original edition ===\nAlthough the bulk of ''The Idiot'' was recorded before ''Low'', the initial installment of the \"Berlin Trilogy\", Bowie's album was released first in January 1977, while Pop's was held over until March. Laurent Thibault opined that \"David didn't want people to think he'd been inspired by Iggy's album, when in fact it was all the same thing\".<ref name=\"Wilcken\"/> In 1981, ''[[NME]]'' editors [[Roy Carr]] and [[Charles Shaar Murray]] suggested that ''The Idiot''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s electronic sound had been \"pioneered\" on ''Low'',<ref name=\"Carr\"/> whereas by 2000, Nicholas Pegg would describe it as \"a stepping stone between ''Station to Station'' and ''Low''.{{sfn|Pegg|2000|pp=382\u2013383}}\n\n\"Sister Midnight\" and \"China Girl\" were released as singles in February and May 1977, respectively, both with the same B-side \"Baby\".<ref>{{cite book |last=Strong |first=Martin C. |year=2002 |title=The Great Rock Discography |edition=6th |pages=815\u2013816}}</ref>\n\n===2020 Deluxe edition===\nOn April 10, 2020, Pop released an alternate mix of his hit song \"[[China Girl (song)|China Girl]]\" as part of the forthcoming release on May 29 of ''The Bowie Years'', a new seven-disc Deluxe box set due to feature expanded remastered versions of his David Bowie-produced albums ''The Idiot'' and ''[[Lust for Life (Iggy Pop album)|Lust for Life]]'', both originally released in 1977. The box set is due to include remastered versions of both 1977 studio projects along with outtakes, alternate mixes and a 40-page book. As well, the two original albums are due to be paired with an additional album of live material to create separate stand-alone two-disc Deluxe editions.<ref>[https://ultimateclassicrock.com/iggy-pop-the-bowie-years/?utm_source=tsmclip&utm_medium=referral Ultimate Classic Rock > Iggy Pop Box Set to Focus on First Two David Bowie-Produced LPs (by Nick Deriso, April 10, 2020)]</ref>\n\n== Reception ==\n=== Critical reception ===\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1score = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref name=\"Deming\"/>\n| rev2 = ''[[Blender (magazine)|Blender]]''\n| rev2score = {{rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://blender.com/guide/reviews.aspx?id=2623 |title=Iggy Pop: The Idiot |work=[[Blender (magazine)|Blender]] |date=September 2004 |accessdate=August 11, 2016 |last=Smith |first=RJ |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060630184015/http://blender.com/guide/reviews.aspx?id=2623 |archivedate=June 30, 2006}}</ref>\n| rev3 = ''[[Chicago Tribune]]''\n| rev3score = {{rating|3|4}}<ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1990-07-22/entertainment/9003010792_1_star-stooges-atmospheric-art-rock |title=Pop On Pop: Iggy Rates His Own Music (and So Do We) |work=[[Chicago Tribune]] |date=July 22, 1990 |accessdate=August 11, 2016 |last=Kot |first=Greg |authorlink=Greg Kot}}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''[[Christgau's Record Guide: Rock Albums of the Seventies|Christgau's Record Guide]]''\n| rev4score = A\u2212<ref>{{cite book |chapter-url=http://www.robertchristgau.com/get_album.php?id=1599 |chapter=Iggy Pop: The Idiot |accessdate=December 8, 2014 |title=Christgau's Record Guide: Rock Albums of the '70s |last=Christgau |first=Robert |authorlink=Robert Christgau |publisher=[[Ticknor and Fields]] |year=1981 |isbn=0-89919-026-X |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/christgausrecord00robe_1 }}</ref>\n| rev5 = ''[[Encyclopedia of Popular Music]]''\n| rev5Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite book |title=[[Encyclopedia of Popular Music|The Encyclopedia of Popular Music]] |last=Larkin |first=Colin | authorlink=Colin Larkin |publisher=[[Omnibus Press]] |edition=5th concise |year=2011 |isbn=0-85712-595-8}}</ref>\n| rev6 = ''[[Q (magazine)|Q]]''\n| rev6score = {{rating|5|5}}<ref>{{cite journal |title=Iggy Pop: The Idiot |work=[[Q (magazine)|Q]] |issue=402 |date=September 2019 |page=106}}</ref>\n| rev7 = ''[[The Rolling Stone Album Guide]]''\n| rev7Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite book |chapter=Iggy Pop |last1=Coleman |first1=Mark |last2=Kemp |first2=Rob |title=[[The Rolling Stone Album Guide|The New Rolling Stone Album Guide]] |edition=4th |year=2004 |editor1-last=Brackett |editor1-first=Nathan |editor2-last=Hoard |editor2-first=Christian |publisher=[[Simon & Schuster]] |isbn=0-7432-0169-8 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/newrollingstonea00brac/page/645 645\u201346] }}</ref>\n| rev8 = ''[[Spin Alternative Record Guide]]''\n| rev8score = 7/10<ref name=\"Spin\">{{cite book |last1=Weisbard |first1=Eric |last2=Marks |first2=Craig |title=[[Spin Alternative Record Guide]] |year=1995 |publisher=[[Vintage Books]] |isbn=0-679-75574-8 |page=378}}</ref>\n}}\n\nBiographer Paul Trynka wrote that ''The Idiot'' \"would remain an album that was more respected than loved, the reviews mostly neutral\", but that it \"prefigured the soul of [[post-punk]]\".<ref name=\"Trynka\"/> In a contemporary review of the album, ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' termed it \"the most savage indictment of rock posturing ever recorded\" and \"a necrophiliac's delight\".<ref name=\"Rolling Stone\">{{cite journal |last=Swenson |first=John |date=5 May 1977 |title=<nowiki>[</nowiki>''The Idiot'' review<nowiki>]</nowiki> |magazine=[[Rolling Stone]] |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/the-idiot-19770505 |accessdate=8 December 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== Charts ===\n''The Idiot'' peaked at number 72 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' Top 200 Albums Chart]], and also reached number 30 on the [[UK Albums Chart]], marking the first time an Iggy Pop album had cracked the top 40.\n\n== Legacy ==\nWhile the album has become highly praised in its own right over the years, fans of Iggy Pop have criticized the work as unrepresentative of his repertoire and as evidence of his being \"co-opted\" by Bowie for the latter's own ends.<ref name=\"Strange Fascination\"/><ref name=\"Gimme Danger\">{{cite book |last=Ambrose |first=Joe |year=2004 |title=Gimme Danger: The Story of Iggy Pop |pages=175\u2013178}}</ref> Bowie himself later admitted:\n\n{{Quote | style=font-size:100% | Poor Jim, in a way, became a guinea pig for what I wanted to do with sound. I didn't have the material at the time, and I didn't feel like writing at all. I felt much more like laying back and getting behind someone else's work, so that album was opportune, creatively.<ref>[[Kurt Loder]] & [[David Bowie]] (1989). ''[[Sound + Vision (box set)|Sound + Vision]]'': CD liner notes</ref>}}\n\nBowie later re-worked \"Sister Midnight\" with new lyrics as \"Red Money\" on his 1979 album ''[[Lodger (album)|Lodger]]'', while his version of \"China Girl\" on 1983's ''[[Let's Dance (David Bowie album)|Let's Dance]]'' became a major hit.\n\nPop has called ''The Idiot'' his \"album of freedom\".<ref name=\"Gimme Danger\"/> [[Siouxsie Sioux]] described it as \"re-affirmation that our suspicions were true \u2013 the man was a genius and what a voice!\"<ref name=\"Gimme Danger\"/> and she performed \"Nightclubbing\" with her second band [[the Creatures]] at the [[Glastonbury Festival|Glastonbury festival]] in 1999.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tsngzxmUF3M&t=213s \"Siouxsie / The Creatures Glastonbury\"]. Youtube. Retrieved 2 November 2019.</ref> The album has been cited as a major influence on a number of acts, including [[Depeche Mode]], [[Nine Inch Nails]], and [[Joy Division]] - the lead singer of Joy Division, [[Ian Curtis]], committed suicide in 1980 with the record still playing on his turntable.{{sfn|Pegg|2000|pp=382\u2013383}} [[Killing Joke]]'s [[Youth (musician)|Youth]] also described ''The Idiot'' as one of his favorite albums.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://thequietus.com/articles/05965-killing-joke-youth-favourite-records |title=The Quietus <nowiki>| Features | Baker's Dozen |</nowiki> Killing Joke's Youth on His 13 Favourite Records |date=29 March 2011 |website=[[The Quietus]] |accessdate=8 December 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 1981, [[Grace Jones]] covered the song \"Nightclubbing\" as the title track to her album [[Nightclubbing (Grace Jones album)|of the same name]]. Pop's version of \"Nightclubbing\" provided the [[Bass drum|kick drum]] sound for Nine Inch Nails' 1994 song \"[[Closer (Nine Inch Nails song)|Closer]]\". The drum loop of \"Nightclubbing\" was also duplicated by [[Oasis (band)|Oasis]] for the song \"Force of Nature\" on their 2002 album ''[[Heathen Chemistry]]''. \"Nightclubbing\" was also sampled in the song \"Small Town Witch\" by the British band [[Sneaker Pimps]] on their 2002 album ''[[Bloodsport (album)|Bloodsport]]''.\n\n== Live performances ==\n\"Nightclubbing\" and \"Funtime\" appeared on the 1978 live set ''[[TV Eye Live 1977|TV Eye]]'', recorded during Pop's 1977 tour, the UK and portions of the US leg of which featured Bowie on keyboards and backing vocals.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\nMost of the album was performed alongside ''Lust for Life'' material during the 2016 spring tour by Pop and his new band featuring [[Josh Homme]], [[Dean Fertita]] and [[Troy Van Leeuwen]] from [[Queens of the Stone Age]] and [[Matt Helders]] from [[Arctic Monkeys]], as part of the promotion for ''[[Post Pop Depression]]'', an album self-referential to Pop's Berlin period. Tracks such as \"Mass Production\" and \"Baby\" were performed live in some cases for the first time since they were released.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\n== Track listing ==\nAll tracks written by [Iggy Pop]] and [[David Bowie]], except \"Sister Midnight\", co-written by [[Carlos Alomar]].\n\n;Side one\n# \"Sister Midnight\" \u2013 4:19\n# \"[[Nightclubbing (song)|Nightclubbing]]\" \u2013 4:14\n# \"[[Funtime (Iggy Pop song)|Funtime]]\" \u2013 2:54\n# \"Baby\" \u2013 3:24\n# \"[[China Girl (song)|China Girl]]\" \u2013 5:08\n\n;Side one\n# \"Dum Dum Boys\" \u2013 7:12\n# \"Tiny Girls\" \u2013 2:59\n# \"Mass Production\" \u2013 8:24\n\n== Personnel ==\n* [[Iggy Pop]]&nbsp;\u2014 vocals\n* [[David Bowie]]&nbsp;\u2014 keyboards, synthesizer, guitar, piano, saxophone, xylophone, backing vocals, [[record producer|production]]\n* [[Carlos Alomar]]&nbsp;\u2014 guitar\n* [[Dennis Davis]]&nbsp;\u2014 drums\n* [[George Murray (musician)|George Murray]]&nbsp;\u2014 bass guitar\n* [[Phil Palmer]]&nbsp;\u2014 guitar\n* Michel Santangeli&nbsp;\u2014 drums\n* Laurent Thibault&nbsp;\u2014 bass\n* [[Tony Visconti]]&nbsp;\u2014 additional mixing\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n'''Sources'''\n* {{Cite book |last=Pegg |first=Nicholas |authorlink=Nicholas Pegg |year=2000 |title=The Complete David Bowie |ref=harv}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Discogs master|38306|The Idiot}}\n* [http://idiotlust.blogspot.com/ Iggy Pop's \"The Idiot\"]\n\n{{Iggy Pop}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Idiot, The (album)}}\n[[Category:Iggy Pop albums]]\n[[Category:1977 debut albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by David Bowie]]\n[[Category:RCA Records albums]]\n[[Category:Art rock albums by American artists]]\n", "name_user": "Zmbro", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTrack listing:ce", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Idiot_(album)"}
