e.org/web/20190606020020/https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1111/hic3.12496 online]\n\n== External links ==\n{{Sister project links\n|wikt = Shanghai\n|commons = \u4e0a\u6d77\n|species = no\n|n = Category:Shanghai\n|q = Shanghai\n|voy = Shanghai\n|d = Q8686\n}}\n* {{Commons category-inline|Shanghai}}\n* [http://www.shanghai.gov.cn Official website]\n* [http://www.ICShanghai.com ShanghaiEye], an English News website of SMG\n* {{Curlie|Regional/Asia/China/Shanghai}}\n* [http://wikimapia.org/#lang=en&lat=31.224252&lon=121.472397&z=11&m=b WikiSatellite view of Shanghai at WikiMapia]\n* {{OSM relation|913067|Shanghai}}\n\n{{-}}\n{{Navboxes\n|title = Articles related to Shanghai\n|list =\n{{Shanghai |state = expanded}}\n{{Geographic location\n|Center = Shanghai\n|North = [[Nantong]], Jiangsu\n|Northeast = ''East China Sea''\n|East = ''[[East China Sea]]''\n|Southeast = ''East China Sea''\n|South = ''[[Hangzhou Bay]]''\n|Southwest = [[Jiaxing]], Zhejiang\n|West = [[Suzhou]], Jiangsu\n|Northwest = Suzhou or Nantong\n}}\n{{Yangtze River Delta}}\n{{Regions and cities of China}}\n{{Province-level divisions of the People's Republic of China}}\n{{Metropolitan cities of the People's Republic of China}}\n{{Most populous cities in the People's Republic of China}}\n{{Major cities along the Yangtze River}}\n{{World's most populated urban areas}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Shanghai|01]]\n[[Category:10th-century establishments in China]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n[[Category:Cities in China]]\n[[Category:East China]]\n[[Category:Jiangnan]]\n[[Category:Metropolitan areas of China]]\n[[Category:Municipalities of China]]\n[[Category:Populated coastal places in China]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in the 10th century]]\n[[Category:Port cities and towns in China]]\n[[Category:Province-level divisions of China]]\n[[Category:Treaty of Nanking]]\n[[Category:Wu (region)]]\n[[Category:Yangtze River Delta]]\n", "name_user": "Cyc89145302", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eInternational relations", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shanghai"}
{"title_page": "National Action (UK)", "text_new": "{{distinguish|National Action  (Australia)}}\n{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}} \n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}  \n{{Infobox militant organization\n| name = National Action\n|logo         = File:United Kingdom with National Action Flag.svg\n|logo_size    = 125px\n|leader = Chris Lythgoe\n|foundation    = 2013\n|dissolved    = \n|founders = Benjamin Raymond, Alex Davies<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.itv.com/news/2018-06-13/mp-murder-plotters-group-wanted-to-wipe-out-non-whites-by-any-means-court-told/ |title=MP murder plotter\u2019s group wanted to wipe out non-whites by any means, court told |publisher=[[ITV (TV network)]] |date=13 June 2018 |accessdate=14 June 2018}}</ref>\n|ideology     = {{unbulleted list|[[Neo-fascism]]|[[British fascism]]|[[Ultranationalism]]|[[Neo-Nazism]]||[[Anti-Semitism]]||[[Homophobia]]}}\n|position     = [[Far-right politics|Far-right]] \n|headquarters = Warrington, United Kingdom \n|size   = 60\u2013100<ref name=\"GadherTimes\">{{cite news |last1=Gadher |first1=Dipesh |title=Neo-Nazis face ban after Cox murder |url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/neo-nazis-face-ban-after-cox-murder-0hgm3r93q |newspaper=[[The Sunday Times]] |url-access=subscription |date=27 November 2016}}</ref> {{small|(2016 estimate)}}\n|status = Banned organisation\n|leader_title = \n|leader_name  = \n|key_people   =  \n|num_staff    = \n|budget       =\n|flag         = [[File:National_Action_flag.png|150px]]\n}}\n{{Neo-fascism |expanded=Movements and parties}}\n\n'''National Action''' is a [[far-right]] [[neo-Nazi]]<ref name=huff/><ref name=mirror>{{cite news |last1=Wright |first1=Simon |last2=Glaze |first2=Ben |last3=Cortbus |first3=Colin |title=Exposed: Rise of Hitler-loving National Action group who want to 'ethnically cleanse' the UK |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/uk-news/exposed-rise-hitler-loving-national-action-3659759#.U-YgoeNdVrI |accessdate=9 August 2014 |work=[[Daily Mirror]] |date=7 June 2014}}</ref> [[terrorism|terrorist]] organisation based in the United Kingdom. Founded in 2013, the group is secretive, and has rules to prevent members from talking openly about the organisation.<ref name=huff>{{cite news |last1=Sheriff |first1=Lucy |title=Meet New Neo-Nazi Group National Action Which Just Wants To 'Piss People Off' |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2014/03/06/new-neo-nazi-group-national-action_n_4910260.html |accessdate=9 August 2014 |work=[[Huffington Post]] |date=6 March 2014}}</ref> It has been a proscribed organisation in the United Kingdom under the [[Terrorism Act 2000]] since 16 December 2016,<ref>{{cite act |title=[[Terrorism Act 2000]] |number=11 |year=2000 |article=2 |articletype=Schedule |url=http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/2000/11/schedule/2}}</ref> the first far-right group to be proscribed since the [[Second World War]]. In March 2017, an undercover investigation by [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] found that its members were still meeting in secret.<ref>[http://www.itv.com/news/2017-03-20/exclusive-former-members-of-banned-terror-group-meet-at-far-right-training-camp/ \"Former members of banned terror group meet at far-right training camp\"], ''ITV News'', 20 March 2017</ref> It is believed that since its proscription, National Action has organised itself in a similar way to the also-banned [[Salafi jihadism|Salafi jihadist]] [[Al-Muhajiroun]] network.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-41768017 |title=Man charged over MP murder threat |date=26 October 2017 |work=[[BBC News]] |accessdate=21 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Members==\nA member known as \"Tom\", who was 18 years old at the time, was interviewed by ''[[The Huffington Post]]'' in March 2014. He named [[Jos\u00e9 Antonio Primo de Rivera]] of the Spanish [[Falange]], [[Alexander Raven Thomson]] and [[Oswald Mosley]] of the [[British Union of Fascists]], and writer [[Wyndham Lewis]] as inspiration for National Action.<ref name=huff/> The group's strategy document twice quoted [[Adolf Hitler]], which \"Tom\" called \"a bit dodgy\". He explained it by saying \"What has been a successful nationalist movement? Oh it was [the Nazis]...That's why we're using [the Nazis]. They used it and they were able to gain power...[[Gottfried Feder]], who was an economist and a member of the [[NSDAP]], he had some good ideas\".<ref name=huff/>\n\nDue to the secretive nature of National Action, it is not clear who the leadership of the organisation are. Former [[National Front (UK)|National Front]] member Ashley Bell ([[pseudonym]] Tommy Johnson) has been referred to as the organisation's leader, and is thought to be one of a number of activists behind National Action's founding document.<ref name=\"HnH Hate Files\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hopenothate.org.uk/hate-groups/na/|title=Hate Files: National Action|publisher=Hope not Hate|accessdate=12 December 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn an investigation by the ''[[Daily Mirror]]'', Benjamin Raymond, age 25 in June 2014, was found to be the leader of National Action. He is a former double-glazing salesman who graduated with a degree in Politics from the [[University of Essex]] in 2013.<ref name=\"Rosthorn\">{{cite news|last=Rosthorn|first=Andrew|url=http://www.tribunemagazine.org/2014/11/twitter-neo-nazis-brag-on-facebook-about-campaign-against-twitter-friendly-mp/|title=Twitter neo-Nazis brag on Facebook about campaign against Twitter-friendly MP|work=Tribune|date=9 November 2014|accessdate=12 December 2016}}</ref> By 2014, he had written on his blog: \"There are non-whites and Jews in my country who all need to be exterminated. As a teenager, ''[[Mein Kampf]]'' changed my life. I am not ashamed to say I love Hitler.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Porter|first=Tom|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/new-uk-far-right-group-national-action-led-by-student-former-double-glazing-salesman-1451795|title=New UK Far-Right Group National Action Led By Student and Former Double-Glazing Salesman|work=International Business Times|date=8 June 2014|accessdate=12 December 2016}}</ref> He has expressed admiration for [[Anders Behring Breivik|Anders Breivik]], the far-right terrorist, who is \"the hero Norway deserves\".<ref>{{cite news|last=James|first=Ben|url=http://www.theargus.co.uk/news/11264390.25_year_old_race_hate_group_leader_uncovered_in_Sussex/|title=23-year old race hate group leader uncovered in Sussex|work=The Argus|location=Southampton|date=4 June 2014|accessdate=12 December 2016}}</ref> Raymond told [[BBC News]] in 2015: \"The source of all of the conflict in society is all the different racial groups that have been brought here. They have been brought here to create a people who are [[wikt:deracinate|deracinated]] and easier to control\".<ref name=\"BBCNye\">{{cite news |last=Nye |first=Catrin |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-34119417 |title=Radicals: 'I'm a proud racist' |work=BBC News |date=3 September 2014 |accessdate=12 December 2016}}</ref>\n\nAnother member was found to be 19-year-old {{interlanguage link|Alex Davies (National Action)|lt=Alex Davies|cy|Alex Davies}} of [[Swansea]], who withdrew from a first-year course in philosophy at [[Warwick University]] in June 2014 after his involvement in National Action was revealed.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://theboar.org/2014/06/18/fascist-leader-leaves-warwick/|title=Fascist leader leaves Warwick|work=The Boar|date=18 June 2014}}</ref> A university spokesman said, \"Any such allegations are taken seriously.\"<ref name=mirror/> Davies had joined the [[Young BNP]] at 16, but found the group to be in \"disarray\". He describes the difference between the two groups as: \"We're targeting universities regularly. That's something the BNP never had. We've built something in a few months the BNP didn't have in 20 years.\"<ref name=mirror/>\n\n[[Jack Renshaw (far-right activist)|Jack Renshaw]], a former Youth BNP activist and a senior spokesperson for the organisation, faced criminal charges over [[incitement to racial hatred]],<ref name=\"Hamilton28Nov\">{{cite news |last1=Hamilton |first1=Fiona |title=Hitler's only fault showing mercy to Jews, youth leader told secret meeting |url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/edition/news/hitlers-only-fault-was-to-show-mercy-to-jews-far-right-youth-leader-told-meeting-3mm6fl35p |work=[[The Times]] |url-access=subscription |date=28 November 2016}}</ref> with his trial scheduled for 2 January 2018.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.southportvisiter.co.uk/news/southport-west-lancs/skelmersdale-man-face-trial-over-13448311 |title=Skelmersdale man to face trial over 'race hate' speeches |newspaper=Southport Visiter<!--sic--> |date=8 August 2017 |author=Press Association |accessdate=5 September 2017}}</ref> Renshaw had called for Jews to be \"eradicated\" as \"nature's financial parasite and nature's social vermin\", and had said that the UK had backed the wrong side in the Second World War, since the Nazis \"were there to remove Jewry from Europe once and for all.\" A person who had committed those same offences, whose name cannot be legally published in the UK, was found guilty at Preston Crown Court of inciting racial hatred on 8 January 2018.<ref>[https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/neo-nazi-called-for-eradication-of-jews-at-far-right-rally-mbt9n8nlx \"Neo-Nazi called for eradication of Jews at far-right rally\"], ''The Times'', 9 January 2018 {{subscription}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2017, six people \u2013 31-year-old Christopher Lythgoe, from [[Warrington]], Garron Helm, 24, of [[Seaforth, Merseyside]]; Matthew Hankinson, 23, of [[Newton-le-Willows]], Merseyside; and Andrew Clarke, 33, and Michael Trubini, 35, both of Warrington, along with Jack Renshaw, were charged with being members of National Action, which is banned in the UK. Two of the men, Lythgoe and Renshaw, were also charged with being involved in a plot to murder the [[West Lancashire (UK Parliament constituency)|West Lancashire]] [[Member of parliament|MP]] [[Rosie Cooper]] with a [[machete]], and of threatening to kill a police officer. In July 2017, a former National Action member, Robbie Mullen, reported the plot to the anti-racism organisation [[Hope not Hate|Hope Not Hate]], who reported the matter to the police.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-44873178 |title=Men jailed for neo-Nazi group membership |date=18 July 2018 |work=BBC News |accessdate=18 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe six faced trial on 11 June 2018 at the [[Old Bailey]] in London.<ref>Hirst, Lauren, [http://www.warringtonguardian.co.uk/news/16148218.Alleged_leader_of_National_Action_appears_in_crown_court/ \"Alleged leader of National Action appears in crown court\"] ''[[Warrington Guardian]]'', 10 April 2017.</ref> The next day, Renshaw pleaded guilty to plotting to murder Rosie Cooper, and to threatening to kill a police officer.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-44452529 |title=MP's murder was to be 'white jihad' |date=12 June 2018 |publisher= |accessdate=12 June 2018 |work=BBC News}}</ref> The following month, Hankinson and Lythgoe were found guilty of being members of National Action and jailed for six years and eight years, respectively. The presiding judge, Mr Justice Jay, told Hankinson: \"You are a neo-Nazi who glorifies and revels in a perverted ideology, has a deep hatred of ethnic minorities and Jews and has advocated violence to achieve your objectives.\" Helm was found not guilty of being a member of the group and Lythgoe was found not guilty of encouragement to murder for allegedly giving Renshaw permission to kill Ms Cooper on behalf of the group.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nAccording to the [[BBC]] and ''[[The Independent]]'', six people \u2013 five men and a woman \u2013 were arrested in co-ordinated raids by the West Midlands Counter Terrorism Unit, and were charged with being members of National Action. The six &ndash; Nathan Pryke, 26, from [[Cambridge]]; Adam Thomas, 21, and Claudia Patatas, 38, both of [[Banbury, Oxfordshire]]; Darren Fletcher, 28, of [[Wednesfield]], [[Wolverhampton]]; Daniel Bogunovic, 26, of [[Leicester]]; and Joel Wilmore, 24, of [[Hazel Grove]], [[Stockport]] &ndash; appeared in court in January 2018 and entered pleas of not guilty. All except Patatas gave their nationality as British; Patatas is Portuguese. Several of the group also faced additional charges.<ref>[https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-42625287 \"National Action: Six in court on terror group charges\"], BBC News, 9 January 2018<br />- Dearden, Lizzie, [https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/crime/national-action-trial-latest-updates-neo-nazis-terorrist-group-westminster-banned-white-supremacist-a8149931.html \"National Action: Six alleged neo-Nazis appear in court charged with joining banned terrorist group\"], ''[[The Independent]]'', 9 January 2018</ref> Thomas, Patatas and Bogunovic were convicted in November 2018. (''[[National Action (UK)#TripleK Mafia|see below]]'') In December 2018, the six received prison sentences varying between five and six-and-a-half years.<ref>Holliday, John (18 December 2018) [https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2018/dec/18/uk-couple-who-named-baby-after-hitler-jailed-for-terror-group-membership \"UK couple who named baby after Hitler jailed for terror group membership\"] ''[[The Guardian]]''</ref>\n\nTwo National Action members were imprisoned for eight years each at the Crown Court in Birmingham. In March 2018, Corporal Mikko Vehvilainen, 34, was described as a recruiter for National Action, a key part of whose strategy was to expand its membership within the armed forces. A self-confessed racist who believes in a coming \"race war\", Vehvilainen wanted to establish an all-white stronghold in the Welsh village of [[Llansilin]]. When arrested at his house there, police found a photograph of him giving a [[Nazi salute]] at a 1917 memorial to his native Finland's independence and an arsenal of weapons and swastika bunting. Another soldier, Private Mark Barrett, like Vehvilainen a member of the 2nd Battalion [[Royal Anglian Regiment]], was acquitted but is believed to have been dismissed by the Army. Alexander Deakin, 24, unemployed, was the Midlands regional organiser. He was seen on CCTV putting up racist stickers at [[Aston University]]. Deakin spread racist propaganda from his bedroom at his parents\u2019 house, telling fellow National Action members via encrypted chat that in a future \"race war\" they would have a \"KKK-themed death squad\". He bragged that counter-terrorism officers were incompetent and would never catch him, but he was found hiding in a cupboard when he was arrested. He was sentenced in April 2018.<ref>Haroon Siddique, [https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2018/nov/12/british-army-solider-recruited-far-right-group-national-action \"\"], ''The Guardian'', 12 November 2018. Retrieved 17 November 2018.</ref>\n\nIn May 2018, Wayne Bell, described as a \"poster boy\" for the organisation, pleaded guilty to two counts of stirring up racial hatred and three counts of possessing multiple items in order to destroy or damage property. The court heard that he had written neo-Nazi graffiti on pillars and lamp posts in his home town of [[Castleford]], and that he had made hundreds of racist and antisemitic posts on [[Twitter]] and the Russian social media site [[VKontakte]]. He was sentenced to four years and three months in prison.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-leeds-44226859 |work=BBC News |title=Wayne Bell jailed for neo-Nazi group social media posts |date=23 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Policy and actions==\n[[File:Mandela statue defaced.jpg|thumb|National Action held a protest at the [[Statue of Nelson Mandela, Parliament Square|statue of Nelson Mandela]] in London, defacing it with a banana.<ref name=\"Collins0315\"/>]] Davies described the group as \"like the BNP but more radical\".<ref name=mirror/> National Action self-styles itself as a \"revolutionary nationalist\" organisation which grew out of a failed offshoot within [[Resistance (YBNP)|the youth wing]] of the [[British National Party]] and has made effective, large-scale use of social media and blogging platforms.<ref name=\"HnH Hate Files\" />\n\nNational Action wanted to reintroduce [[Section 28]], which prohibited the \"[[promotion of homosexuality]]\" in schools.<ref name=huff/><ref name=mirror/> On immigration, \"Tom\" said \"With coloured people we'd say big no to them coming over. But with [white people] we'd be a bit more lenient\".<ref name=huff/>\n\nThe group has distributed its material on at least 12 university campuses.<ref name=huff/><ref name=mirror/> In an interview with ''[[The National Student]]'' in 2014, an anonymous organiser for National Action explained why they target universities: \"very soon they are going to find out just how hard the system has screwed them \u2013 if they knew what we know now we would have an army. The last Labour government aspired to send 50% of 18- to 21-year-olds to university and the total student population has grown exponentially over the past decade. That is 50% of youth who are going to be very angry burger flippers\".<ref name=student>{{cite news|last1=Filfilan|first1=Karam|title=\"This year will be a reign of terror\": Meet the white British Nationalists coming to your campus|url=http://www.thenationalstudent.com/Features/2014-04-25/This_year_will_be_a_reign_of_terror_Meet_the_white_British_Nationalists_coming_to_your_campus.html|accessdate=9 August 2014|work=[[The National Student]]|date=25 April 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140810112134/http://www.thenationalstudent.com/Features/2014-04-25/This_year_will_be_a_reign_of_terror_Meet_the_white_British_Nationalists_coming_to_your_campus.html|archivedate=10 August 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> He also promised \"This year will be a reign of terror\",<ref name=student/> and described people who are in [[interracial relationships]] as \"pathetic internet [[nerd]]s who can't get laid and [[Sexually transmitted disease|STD]]-infested [[sluts]]\".<ref name=\"student\"/>\n\nIn October 2014, Garron Helm, a National Action member from [[Merseyside]], was sentenced to four weeks in prison for sending a message via Twitter to MP [[Luciana Berger]] relating to her Jewish background, which was found to be \"an offensive, indecent or obscene message\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Perraudin |first1=Frances |title=Man jailed for antisemitic tweet to Labour MP |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2014/oct/20/man-jailed-antisemitic-tweet-labour-mp|accessdate=21 October 2014|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=21 October 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Collins0315\">{{cite news |last=Collins |first=Matthew |url=http://www.hopenothate.org.uk/get-hope/issue18/young-nazi-and-dangerous/ |title=National Action: Young, Nazi and Dangerous |work=Hope Not Hate |issue=18 |date=March\u2013April 2015 |accessdate=31 October 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161023195417/http://www.hopenothate.org.uk/get-hope/issue18/young-nazi-and-dangerous/|archivedate=23 October 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> \"I'm not a lunatic for embracing martyrdom, I've just accepted that I could be more use in death than life\", he wrote in early 2015.<ref name=\"Collins0315\"/> Helm served two weeks of his sentence before being released.<ref>{{cite news |last=Rouse |first=Alisha |url=http://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/news/liverpool-news/neo-nazi-not-sorry-slightest-vile-8558360 |title=Neo-Nazi \"not sorry in the slightest\" for vile abuse sent to Luciana Berger |work=[[Liverpool Echo]] |date=2 February 2015 |accessdate=12 December 2016}}</ref> In November 2014, 10 National Action activists were arrested in [[dawn raid]]s on suspicion of conspiring to cause [[criminal damage]] to Berger's office; they were all bailed.<ref name=\"Rosthorn\"/><ref>{{cite news|last=Dysch|first=Marcus|url=https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/ten-arrested-near-luciana-berger-s-liverpool-office-1.60959|title=Ten arrested near Luciana Berger\u2019s Liverpool office|work=The Jewish Chronicle|date=11 November 2014|accessdate=12 December 2016}}</ref> No further action was taken against them.<ref>{{cite news |last=Rouse |first=Alisha |url=http://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/news/liverpool-news/no-further-action-against-neo-nazis-8552340 |title=No further action against neo-Nazis arrested outside Wavertree MP Luciana Berger's office |work=Liverpool Echo |date=31 January 2015 |accessdate=12 December 2016}}</ref> National Action's campaign against Berger was supported by US-based neo-Nazi website ''[[The Daily Stormer]]'', which offered advice on how to set up untraceable Twitter accounts in order to send abuse.<ref>{{cite news|last=Dysch|first=Marcus|title=Neo-Nazi gave out internet abuse tips in campaign against Luciana Berger|url=http://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/124917/neo-nazi-gave-out-internet-abuse-tips-campaign-against-luciana-berger|accessdate=24 November 2014|work=[[The Jewish Chronicle]]|date=30 October 2014}}<br />- {{cite news |last1=Woolf |first1=Marie |last2=Henry |first2=Robin |url=http://www.thesundaytimes.co.uk/sto/news/uk_news/People/article1481397.ece?shareToken=cbcde614d249c6cb344e59bcb9038ff7 |title=Hate tweets fired across Atlantic at Jewish MP |newspaper=The Sunday Times |date=9 November 2014 |accessdate=12 December 2016 |url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2015, National Action organised a \"White Man March\" on the [[Quayside]] in Newcastle upon Tyne during which police arrested nine people; those attending included North East representatives of the [[British National Party]] (BNP) and neo-Nazis from Eastern Europe.<ref name=\"Evening Chronicle 22 March 2015\">{{cite news |last=Southern |first=Keiran |authorlink= |title=Newcastle Quayside brought to a standstill as neo-Nazis invade the city |url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/news/quayside-brought-standstill-neo-nazis-invade-8893069 |date=22 March 2015 |newspaper=[[Evening Chronicle]] |location=Newcastle upon Tyne |accessdate=5 September 2017}}</ref> In June of the same year, 26-year-old Zack Davies, who told police that he was a member of National Action, was found guilty of the attempted murder of Sarandev Bhambra, a Sikh man and trainee dentist, in [[Mold, Flintshire]]. Dr Bhambra was struck in the head and nearly lost a hand in the attack, suffering \"life changing injuries\". Davies claimed this was revenge for the [[murder of Lee Rigby]] and chanted \"white power\" as he launched the attack.<ref>{{cite news |last=Harley |first=Nicola |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/crime/11699384/Attacker-on-Lee-Rigby-revenge-mission-guilty-of-attempted-murder.html |title=Dentist attack: 'If my brother was white this would be called a terror attack' |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |date=25 June 2015 |accessdate=12 December 2016}}<br />- {{cite news |last=Whelan |first=Brian |url=http://www.channel4.com/news/national-actions-zack-davies-guilty-of-attempted-murder |title=National Action's Zack Davies guilty of attempted murder |work=[[Channel 4 News]] |date=25 June 2015 |accessdate=25 June 2015}}<br />- {{cite news |last1=Badshar |first1=Nadeem |title=Dentist attacked with machete in revenge for Lee Rigby |url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/news/uk/crime/article4477453.ece |work=The Times |url-access=subscription |date=23 June 2015}}</ref> Davies was given a life sentence the following September, and is to serve for 14 years before being considered for parole.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.channel4.com/news/zack-davies-life-sentence-for-lee-rigby-revenge-murder |title=Zack Davies: life sentence for Wales neo-Nazi attack |work=Channel 4 News |date=11 September 2015 |accessdate=12 December 2016}}</ref> National Action publicly denied any association with Davies or his actions.<ref name=\"BBCNye\" />\n\nIn August 2015, the group attempted to hold a second 'White Man March' in Liverpool. Strong opposition from the Anti-Fascist Network and local activists forced the organisers to cancel the march and take refuge in the lost luggage collection point at [[Lime Street Station]].<ref name=\"Liverpool Echo 16 August 2015\">{{cite news |last=Hughes |first=Lorna |authorlink= |title=Liverpool said no to Neo-Nazi march - and this is how the Internet reacted |url=http://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/news/liverpool-said-no-neo-nazi-9866502 |date=16 August 2015 |newspaper=[[Liverpool Echo]] |location=Liverpool |accessdate=5 September 2017}}</ref> Tensions were raised by a letter to Mayor [[Joe Anderson (politician)|Joe Anderson]] threatening race riots; National Action claimed this was a forgery by an ''[[agent provocateur]]''.<ref>{{cite news |title=Liverpool: White Man March Neo-Nazis Cower In Station Depot After Being Pelted With Rubbish, Then Cancel Event |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2015/08/15/white-man-march-in-liverpool-canceled_n_7992084.html |accessdate=15 August 2015 |website=Huffington Post |date=15 August 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2016, ''[[The Sunday Times]]'' reported that \"fears that far-right activists may be grooming a new generation of [[Hitler Youth]] in the UK emerged\" after stickers from National Action proclaiming parts of Liverpool to be a \"Nazi-controlled zone\" appeared. The group also held a number of marches and demonstrations on [[Armistice Day]] and [[Remembrance Sunday]] proclaiming that \"[[Hitler]] was right\", and celebrated the election of [[Donald Trump]] as [[President-elect of the United States]] under the slogan of \"[[white power]]\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gadher |first1=Dipesh |title=Warning over rise of Hitler youth |url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/edition/news/warning-over-rise-of-hitler-youth-79pkwnfkl |accessdate=19 December 2016 |work=The Sunday Times |url-access=subscription |date=20 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nNational Action has called for a \"white jihad\" to \"cleanse Britain of parasites\" using leaflets, stickers and video.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hopkins |first1=Steven |title=Bizarre 'White Jihad' Video, As They Begin Recruitment Drive |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2016/02/10/neo-nazi-group-release-bizarre-recruitment-video_n_9201944.html?guccounter=1&guce_referrer=aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZ29vZ2xlLmNvbS8&guce_referrer_sig=AQAAAFwz0z2-KHlw2f6JMPG8ciPBynyc_IBhSqpoWqZHuOIv7c8Zv-rSx2MyC-pdqCxU3SQbynQx0LqPJBbcCqRK6hu_i0EtZE3EJPxx5uHdRYvLGWee10sejdZSPYfpYJJkQw85wrTdNJkaDPtibUt-l8kqpD8ZIWRBm_Echq7Z7NA9 |accessdate=19 March 2019 |publisher= |work=Huffington Post |date=10 February 2016}}<br />- {{cite news |last1=Adil |first1=Muna |title=I'm not surprised most terror suspects in the UK are white \u2013 we've been expecting to see this change for a while |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/voices/most-uk-terror-suspects-white-not-surprised-muna-adil-quilliam-a8536436.html |accessdate=19 March 2019 |publisher= |work=The Independent |date=13 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Responses==\n\"Tom\" reported that the group was monitored by the [[West Midlands Police#Counter Terrorism Unit (CTU)|West Midlands Counter Terrorism Unit]].<ref name=huff/> [[Gerry Gable]], the former editor of the anti-fascist magazine [[Searchlight (magazine)|''Searchlight'']], said, \"National Action are highly organised with a lot of foreign money backing them up. They\u2019re not looking to attract thickos who just want a fight. They want thinkers who are prepared to die for National Socialism.\"<ref name=record>{{cite news|last1=Filfilan|first1=Karam|title=Hateful and here: German Anti-Islam extremists rally in Glasgow in bid to recruit Scots|url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/news/scottish-news/hateful-here-german-anti-islam-extremists-4998372|accessdate=30 August 2015|newspaper=[[Daily Record (Scotland)|The Daily Record]]|date=18 January 2015}}</ref> [[Scotland Yard]] is reported to be \"very concerned\" by the group, but gave the official response, \"We cannot discuss details of individuals or organisations that may or may not be the subject of an investigation.\"<ref name=mirror/>\n\n[[Ian Austin]], a [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] MP whose adoptive father fled [[German occupation of Czechoslovakia|Nazi-occupied Czechoslovakia]], said of National Action, \"Seventy years ago, British heroes were fighting to liberate Europe from the scourge of Nazis and fascism. It's absolutely disgusting to see young British people praise Hitler today.\"<ref name=mirror/>\n\nOn 5 September 2017, it was reported that four serving male members of the [[British Army]] had been arrested under the [[Terrorism Act 2000]] on suspicion of being members of National Action: a 22-year-old from [[Birmingham]], a 32-year-old from [[Powys]], a 24-year-old from [[Ipswich]] and a 24-year-old from [[Northampton]].<ref name=telegraph5917>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/09/05/four-alleged-members-neo-nazi-group-arrested-suspicion-planning/ |title=British soldiers arrested by terror police for allegedly being members of banned neo-Nazi group |work=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]] |date=5 September 2017 |accessdate=5 September 2017 |first1=Danny |last1=Boyle |first2=Hayley |last2=Dixon |lastauthoramp=yes}}</ref> A fifth man was reported to have been detained in Cyprus.<ref name=\"guardian5917\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2017/sep/05/four-held-on-suspicion-of-being-members-of-outlawed-neo-nazi-group-national-action |title=Five army men held over alleged membership of banned UK neo-Nazi group |last1=Grierson |first1=Jamie |work=The Guardian |accessdate=5 September 2017}}</ref> As a result, three men, including two British soldiers, were charged with terrorism offences.<ref name=bbc11917>{{cite news |author=Staff |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-41234539 |title=Neo-Nazi arrests: UK soldiers charged with terror offences |date=11 September 2017 |work=BBC News |accessdate=28 September 2017}}</ref> On 27 September 2017, eleven men were arrested in further raids across England and Wales.<ref name=\"huff27917\">{{cite web |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/entry/national-action-arrests_uk_59cb7d4ee4b05063fe0de646 |title=National Action: Eleven People Arrested As Part Of Probe Into Banned Far Right Group |last=Sommers |first=Jack |date=27 September 2017 |work=Huffington Post |accessdate=28 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 3 January 2018, six people \u2013 five men from Cambridge, Banbury, Wolverhampton, Leicester and Stockport, and a woman from Banbury \u2013 were arrested on suspicion of being concerned in the commission, preparation and instigation of acts of terrorism, namely on suspicion of being a member of a proscribed organisation, National Action. Those arrested were aged between 21 and 37.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-42552750 \"Six held in far-right group National Action investigation\"], BBC News, 3 January 2018. Retrieved 3 January 2018.<br />- [https://news.sky.com/story/six-people-arrested-over-suspected-membership-of-banned-national-action-group-11193980 \"National Action investigation: Six held over suspected membership of banned far-right group\"], ''[[Sky News]]'', 3 January 2018. Retrieved 3 January 2018.<br />- Dearden, Lizzie, [https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/crime/national-action-arrests-neo-nazi-terror-offences-uk-suspicion-latest-news-woman-man-midlands-police-a8139276.html \"National Action: Six alleged members of neo-Nazi group arrested on suspicion of terror offences\"], ''The Independent'', 3 January 2018. Retrieved 3 January 2018.</ref>\n\n==Lead-up to proscription==\nIn November 2016, ''The Sunday Times'' reported that National Action was supporting Thomas Mair, the [[Murder of Jo Cox|murderer of]] the Batley and Spen [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] MP [[Jo Cox]], posting \"only 649 MPs to go!\" on social media.<ref name=\"Home Office\">{{cite web |title=Proscribed Terrorist Organisations |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/578385/201612_Proscription.pdf |website=gov.uk |publisher=[[Home Office]] |page=15 |format=PDF document}}</ref> National Action also supported Mair personally, saying \"don't let this man's sacrifice go in vain\"<ref name=\"Home Office\" /> and altered its listing on Google to state: \"Death to traitors, freedom for Britain!\", a slogan Mair had said to a court when asked to give his name following Cox's murder.<ref name=\"GadherTimes\" /> The organisation also supported the [[2016 Orlando nightclub shooting]] and has called for graphic and violent attacks on police officers in the UK.<ref name=\"Home Office\" /> Mair, however, appeared to have little involvement with National Action or any other white supremacist groups within the UK.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Cobain |first1=Ian |title=The slow-burning hatred that led Thomas Mair to murder Jo Cox |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2016/nov/23/thomas-mair-slow-burning-hatred-led-to-jo-cox-murder |newspaper=The Guardian |accessdate=11 December 2016}}</ref>\n\nBefore it was banned, the organisation was the most active in Yorkshire, where half of the referrals to the government's anti-extremism strategy have been about the far-right.<ref name=\"GadherTimes\" /> In October, the ''[[Jewish Chronicle]]'' reported that the organisation's leaflets \"including swastikas, a Nazi salute and the phrase 'no tolerance'\" were spotted in Hull, Liverpool, Glasgow and Cardiff.<ref name=\"Hull Daily Mail\">[http://www.hulldailymail.co.uk/banned-neo-nazi-terrorist-group-national-action-active-in-hull/story-29979290-detail/story.html \"Banned neo-Nazi terrorist group National Action active in Hull\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161214171903/http://www.hulldailymail.co.uk/banned-neo-nazi-terrorist-group-national-action-active-in-hull/story-29979290-detail/story.html |date=14 December 2016 }}, ''Hull Daily Mail'', 14 December 2016.</ref> The ''[[Hull Daily Mail]]'' says that \"The first evidence of the group in the city was in July when graffiti appeared on a wall on George Street in the city centre with an incorrectly painted Swastika, the letters NA and a logo.\"<ref name=\"Hull Daily Mail\" /> In a newsletter, National Action claimed that although the group was \"not entirely sure who could {{sic|of}} done\" the graffiti, \"it seems we have got quite a following in Hull, with graffiti (even though backwards) of swastikas and an attempt at our logo and the initials NA popping up around Hull and triggering the reactionary left.\"<ref name=\"Hull Daily Mail\" />\n\nNational Action has promoted the [[antisemitic conspiracy theories]] that Jews were behind the [[September 11 attacks]] and has labelled Cox as the \"patron saint\" of grooming gangs, according to ''The Sunday Times''.<ref name=\"GadherTimes\" /> At a secret meeting of the Yorkshire Forum, Renshaw said (in a video seen by ''[[The Times]]'') that they need to adopt a \"killer instinct\". According to him: \"As nationalists we need to learn from the mistakes of the national socialists and we need to realise that, no, you do not show the Jew mercy\".<ref name=\"Hamilton28Nov\" />\n\nThe group was proscribed as a terrorist organisation under the [[Terrorism Act 2000]], making it a criminal offence to support or be a member after 16 December 2016.<ref>{{cite news|last=Elgot|first=Jessica|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/dec/12/neo-nazi-group-national-action-banned-by-uk-home-secretary|title=Neo-Nazi group National Action banned by UK home secretary|work=The Guardian|date=12 December 2016|accessdate=12 December 2016}}</ref> In laying an order for National Action's proscription, the Home Secretary, [[Amber Rudd]], described the group as \"a racist, antisemitic and homophobic organisation which stirs up hatred, glorifies violence and promotes a vile ideology\".<ref name=\"BBC Terror Org\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-38286708 |title=Far right group National Action to be banned under terror laws |work=BBC News |date=12 December 2016}}</ref> National Action is the first far-right organisation to be proscribed in the UK since the now-defunct British Union of Fascists in the 1940s.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://politicalscrapbook.net/2016/12/national-action-the-first-far-right-group-to-be-banned-in-britain-since-1940-but-it-is-not-enough/ |title=National Action the first far-right group to be banned in Britain since 1940, \u2018but it is not enough\u2019 |work=Political Scrapbook |date=12 December 2016 |accessdate=21 January 2018}}</ref> National Action is one of only three terrorist organisations based in [[Great Britain]] to be proscribed (the other two being radical Islamist organisations).<ref name=\"BBC Far-right rise\">De Simone, Samuel,  [https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-38293314 \"National Action ban highlights concern over far right\"], BBC News, 12 December 2016</ref> Its ban was seen as an acknowledgement by the UK government that the far-right was on the rise, and figures released by the [[National Police Chiefs' Council]] show that the number of far-right referrals to the anti-terror [[Prevent strategy|''Prevent'' programme]] increased from 323 cases in 2014\u201315 to 561 in 2015\u201316.<ref name=\"BBC Far-right rise\" />\n\n==Aliases==\n\n=== Scottish Dawn ===\nSuspicion that some National Action followers simply swapped membership of National Action for membership of the group Scottish Dawn in order to circumvent the ban prompted the [[Home Office]] to consider whether the new group should be outlawed too. Scottish Dawn was established shortly after National Action was banned and described itself as a \"new [[Identitarian movement|Identitarian]] social movement formed from various organisations in 2017 to develop a coherent conception of [[Scottish national identity|Scottish identity]] and secure its place within Scottish politics\".<ref>{{cite news |last=Kachroo |first=Rohit |title=Scottish far-right group could become second neo-Nazi organisation in Britain to be banned |url=https://www.itv.com/news/2017-09-14/far-right-group-in-scotland-could-become-second-neo-nazi-organisation-in-britain-to-be-banned/ |work=[[ITV News at Ten]] |publisher= [[ITN]] |date=14 September 2017 |accessdate=15 September 2017}} [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TCr9oMHlNQ4 Video.]<br />- {{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-41440467 |title=Who are the Scottish Dawn neo-Nazi group? |last=Nicolson |first=Stuart |date=29 September 2017 |work=BBC News |accessdate=5 February 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== NS131 ===\nNS131 (National Socialist Anti-Capitalist Action) was another group that appeared after National Action was proscribed and was \"a platform dedicated to promoting and spreading NS street art and physical propaganda\" according to its website. On 28 September 2017, after eleven suspected members across the country were arrested, the government announced that both Scottish Dawn and NS131 would be banned as aliases of National Action.<ref>{{cite news |author=Staff |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-41430740 |title=Two neo-Nazi groups added to banned list |date=28 September 2017 |work=BBC News |accessdate=28 September 2017}}<br />- {{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/crime/national-action-arrest-terror-terrorist-far-right-neo-nazi-police-counter-terror-soldiers-wales-a7969566.html |title=11 people arrested in neo-Nazi terror investigation |date=28 September 2017 |author=Dearden, Lizzie |newspaper=The Independent |accessdate=28 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== System Resistance Network ===\nSystem Resistance Network (SRN) is a group that is believed to have been putting up homophobic and anti-refugee posters in Dundee, Swansea, Cardiff and Bristol, and is claimed by [[Hope not Hate]] to be another alias of National Action.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://theferret.scot/system-resistance-network/ |title=Neo-Nazi outfit in Scotland linked to banned terrorist group |date=4 January 2018 |work=The Ferret |accessdate=5 February 2018}}<br />- {{cite news |url=https://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/news/scottish-news/banned-group-behind-new-neo-11754558 |title=Banned group behind new neo-Nazi campaign recruiting in Scotland, say activists |last=Briggs |first=Billy |date=27 December 2017 |work=Daily Record |accessdate=5 February 2018}}</ref> SRN was formerly known as Vanguard Britannia, the British chapter of American [[alt-right]], [[neo-Nazi]] group [[Vanguard America]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.vice.com/en_uk/article/j555p7/nazi-group-linked-to-charlottesville-attack-has-a-uk-chapter |title=Nazi Group Linked to Charlottesville Attack Has a UK Chapter |date=18 August 2017 |work=Vice |accessdate=5 February 2018}}<br />- {{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/crime/national-action-neo-nazis-banned-terrorist-groups-scottish-dawn-ns131-jews-gay-muslims-jo-cox-police-a7974836.html |title=Neo-Nazi terrorist groups still recruiting despite being banned as aliases of National Action |date=29 September 2017 |work=The Independent |accessdate=5 February 2018}}</ref> Former members of the SRN are suspected to have been involved in the creation of the [[Sonnenkrieg Division]], an offshoot of the American neo-Nazi terrorist organization the [[Atomwaffen Division]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-46460442 |work=BBC News |date=5 December 2018 |accessdate=6 December 2018|title=British Neo-Nazis suggest Prince Harry should be shot |author=Sanford, Daniel and DeSimone, Daniel}}</ref>\n\n=== TripleK Mafia ===\nDuring the 2018 trial of three people for being members of National Action, it emerged that a successor organization named the TripleK Mafia had been set up by the defendants. This rebrand was made in an attempt to \"shed one skin for another\"; the name was a reference to notorious American group the [[Ku Klux Klan]]. The group name was misspelled as \"TrippleK\" four times in new posters by member Joel Wilmore. Two of the defendants in the trial, Adam Thomas, 22, and Claudia Patatas, 38, had named their newborn baby Adolf in honour of Hitler and posed with the child while dressed in KKK robes and with [[Flag of Germany|swastika flags]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.sky.com/story/suspected-neo-nazi-father-posed-with-baby-adolf-while-wearing-kkk-robes-11522952 |title=Suspected neo-Nazi father 'posed with baby Adolf while wearing KKK robes' |work=Sky News |date=15 October 2018 |accessdate=20 October 2018}}<br />- {{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-oxfordshire-45814439 |title=Dad 'posed in KKK robes with baby Adolf' |date=10 October 2018 |work=BBC News |accessdate=20 October 2018}}</ref> The third defendant was a \"prominent member of National Action's Midlands chapter\", Daniel Bogunovic, 27. All three were convicted after a seven-week trial at the Crown Court in Birmingham.<ref>{{cite news |last=Barnes |first=Tom |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/crime/national-action-baby-adolf-hitler-terror-guilty-nazi-court-patatas-a8629846.html |title=National Action: Couple who named baby after Hitler found guilty of being part of neo-Nazi terror group |work=The Independent |date=12 November 2018 |accessdate=12 November 2018}}<br />- {{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-oxfordshire-46151838 |title=National Action trial: Three guilty of neo-Nazi group membership |work=BBC News |date=12 November 2018 |accessdate=12 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Combat 18]] (C18), a British neo-Nazi organization whose members are banned from joining the police or the [[Her Majesty's Prison Service|Prison Service]].\n* [[National Socialist Underground]] (NSU), a German neo-Nazi group\n* [[Atomwaffen Division]], an American neo-Nazi group\n* [[Atomwaffen Division#Sonnenkrieg Division|Sonnenkrieg Division]], another British neo-Nazi organization whose members have ties to National Action and two have been convicted for suggesting violence against [[Prince Harry, Duke of Sussex]], for his marriage to [[Meghan Markle]]\n\n==References== \n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Neo-Nazism}}\n{{UK far right}}\n{{Portal bar|Politics|United Kingdom}}\n\n[[Category:Illegal organizations]]\n[[Category:Banned far-right parties]]\n[[Category:2013 establishments in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Neo-Nazi organisations in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Youth organisations based in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Secret societies in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:British nationalism]]\n[[Category:Antisemitism in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Organisations designated as terrorist by the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Neo-fascist terrorism]]\n[[Category:White nationalist terrorism]]\n[[Category:Far-right parties in Europe]]\n", "text_old": "{{distinguish|National Action  (Australia)}}\n{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}} \n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}  \n{{Infobox militant organization\n| name = National Action\n|logo         = File:United Kingdom with National Action Flag.svg\n|logo_size    = 125px\n|leader = Chris Lythgoe\n|foundation    = 2013\n|dissolved    = \n|founders = Benjamin Raymond, Alex Davies<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.itv.com/news/2018-06-13/mp-murder-plotters-group-wanted-to-wipe-out-non-whites-by-any-means-court-told/ |title=MP murder plotter\u2019s group wanted to wipe out non-whites by any means, court told |publisher=[[ITV (TV network)]] |date=13 June 2018 |accessdate=14 June 2018}}</ref>\n|ideology     = {{unbulleted list|[[Neo-fascism]]|[[British fascism]]|[[Ultranationalism]]|[[Neo-Nazism]]||[[Anti-Semitism]]||[[Homophobia]]}}\n|position     = [[Far-right politics|Far-right]] \n|headquarters = Warrington, United Kingdom \n|size   = 60\u2013100<ref name=\"GadherTimes\">{{cite news |last1=Gadher |first1=Dipesh |title=Neo-Nazis face ban after Cox murder |url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/neo-nazis-face-ban-after-cox-murder-0hgm3r93q |newspaper=[[The Sunday Times]] |url-access=subscription |date=27 November 2016}}</ref> {{small|(2016 estimate)}}\n|status = Banned organisation\n|leader_title = \n|leader_name  = \n|key_people   =  \n|num_staff    = \n|budget       =\n|flag         = [[File:National_Action_flag.png|150px]]\n}}\n{{Neo-fascism |expanded=Movements and parties}}\n\n'''National Action''' is a [[far-right]] [[neo-Nazi]]<ref name=huff/><ref name=mirror>{{cite news |last1=Wright |first1=Simon |last2=Glaze |first2=Ben |last3=Cortbus |first3=Colin |title=Exposed: Rise of Hitler-loving National Action group who want to 'ethnically cleanse' the UK |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/uk-news/exposed-rise-hitler-loving-national-action-3659759#.U-YgoeNdVrI |accessdate=9 August 2014 |work=[[Daily Mirror]] |date=7 June 2014}}</ref> [[terrorism|terrorist]] organisation based in the United Kingdom. Founded in 2013, the group is secretive, and has rules to prevent members from talking openly about the organisation.<ref name=huff>{{cite news |last1=Sheriff |first1=Lucy |title=Meet New Neo-Nazi Group National Action Which Just Wants To 'Piss People Off' |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2014/03/06/new-neo-nazi-group-national-action_n_4910260.html |accessdate=9 August 2014 |work=[[Huffington Post]] |date=6 March 2014}}</ref> It has been a proscribed organisation in the United Kingdom under the [[Terrorism Act 2000]] since 16 December 2016,<ref>{{cite act |title=[[Terrorism Act 2000]] |number=11 |year=2000 |article=2 |articletype=Schedule |url=http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/2000/11/schedule/2}}</ref> the first far-right group to be proscribed since the [[Second World War]]. In March 2017, an undercover investigation by [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] found that its members were still meeting in secret.<ref>[http://www.itv.com/news/2017-03-20/exclusive-former-members-of-banned-terror-group-meet-at-far-right-training-camp/ \"Former members of banned terror group meet at far-right training camp\"], ''ITV News'', 20 March 2017</ref> It is believed that since its proscription, National Action has organised itself in a similar way to the also-banned [[Salafi jihadism|Salafi jihadist]] [[Al-Muhajiroun]] network.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-41768017 |title=Man charged over MP murder threat |date=26 October 2017 |work=[[BBC News]] |accessdate=21 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Members==\nA member known as \"Tom\", who was 18 years old at the time, was interviewed by ''[[The Huffington Post]]'' in March 2014. He named [[Jos\u00e9 Antonio Primo de Rivera]] of the Spanish [[Falange]], [[Alexander Raven Thomson]] and [[Oswald Mosley]] of the [[British Union of Fascists]], and writer [[Wyndham Lewis]] as inspiration for National Action.<ref name=huff/> The group's strategy document twice quoted [[Adolf Hitler]], which \"Tom\" called \"a bit dodgy\". He explained it by saying \"What has been a successful nationalist movement? Oh it was [the Nazis]...That's why we're using [the Nazis]. They used it and they were able to gain power...[[Gottfried Feder]], who was an economist and a member of the [[NSDAP]], he had some good ideas\".<ref name=huff/>\n\nDue to the secretive nature of National Action, it is not clear who the leadership of the organisation are. Former [[National Front (UK)|National Front]] member Ashley Bell ([[pseudonym]] Tommy Johnson) has been referred to as the organisation's leader, and is thought to be one of a number of activists behind National Action's founding document.<ref name=\"HnH Hate Files\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hopenothate.org.uk/hate-groups/na/|title=Hate Files: National Action|publisher=Hope not Hate|accessdate=12 December 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn an investigation by the ''[[Daily Mirror]]'', Benjamin Raymond, age 25 in June 2014, was found to be the leader of National Action. He is a former double-glazing salesman who graduated with a degree in Politics from the [[University of Essex]] in 2013.<ref name=\"Rosthorn\">{{cite news|last=Rosthorn|first=Andrew|url=http://www.tribunemagazine.org/2014/11/twitter-neo-nazis-brag-on-facebook-about-campaign-against-twitter-friendly-mp/|title=Twitter neo-Nazis brag on Facebook about campaign against Twitter-friendly MP|work=Tribune|date=9 November 2014|accessdate=12 December 2016}}</ref> By 2014, he had written on his blog: \"There are non-whites and Jews in my country who all need to be exterminated. As a teenager, ''[[Mein Kampf]]'' changed my life. I am not ashamed to say I love Hitler.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Porter|first=Tom|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/new-uk-far-right-group-national-action-led-by-student-former-double-glazing-salesman-1451795|title=New UK Far-Right Group National Action Led By Student and Former Double-Glazing Salesman|work=International Business Times|date=8 June 2014|accessdate=12 December 2016}}</ref> He has expressed admiration for [[Anders Behring Breivik|Anders Breivik]], the far-right terrorist, who is \"the hero Norway deserves\".<ref>{{cite news|last=James|first=Ben|url=http://www.theargus.co.uk/news/11264390.25_year_old_race_hate_group_leader_uncovered_in_Sussex/|title=23-year old race hate group leader uncovered in Sussex|work=The Argus|location=Southampton|date=4 June 2014|accessdate=12 December 2016}}</ref> Raymond told [[BBC News]] in 2015: \"The source of all of the conflict in society is all the different racial groups that have been brought here. They have been brought here to create a people who are [[wikt:deracinate|deracinated]] and easier to control\".<ref name=\"BBCNye\">{{cite news |last=Nye |first=Catrin |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-34119417 |title=Radicals: 'I'm a proud racist' |work=BBC News |date=3 September 2014 |accessdate=12 December 2016}}</ref>\n\nAnother member was found to be 19-year-old {{interlanguage link|Alex Davies (National Action)|lt=Alex Davies|cy|Alex Davies}} of [[Swansea]], who withdrew from a first-year course in philosophy at [[Warwick University]] in June 2014 after his involvement in National Action was revealed.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://theboar.org/2014/06/18/fascist-leader-leaves-warwick/|title=Fascist leader leaves Warwick|work=The Boar|date=18 June 2014}}</ref> A university spokesman said, \"Any such allegations are taken seriously.\"<ref name=mirror/> Davies had joined the [[Young BNP]] at 16, but found the group to be in \"disarray\". He describes the difference between the two groups as: \"We're targeting universities regularly. That's something the BNP never had. We've built something in a few months the BNP didn't have in 20 years.\"<ref name=mirror/>\n\n[[Jack Renshaw (far-right activist)|Jack Renshaw]], a former Youth BNP activist and a senior spokesperson for the organisation, faced criminal charges over [[incitement to racial hatred]],<ref name=\"Hamilton28Nov\">{{cite news |last1=Hamilton |first1=Fiona |title=Hitler's only fault showing mercy to Jews, youth leader told secret meeting |url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/edition/news/hitlers-only-fault-was-to-show-mercy-to-jews-far-right-youth-leader-told-meeting-3mm6fl35p |work=[[The Times]] |url-access=subscription |date=28 November 2016}}</ref> with his trial scheduled for 2 January 2018.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.southportvisiter.co.uk/news/southport-west-lancs/skelmersdale-man-face-trial-over-13448311 |title=Skelmersdale man to face trial over 'race hate' speeches |newspaper=Southport Visiter<!--sic--> |date=8 August 2017 |author=Press Association |accessdate=5 September 2017}}</ref> Renshaw had called for Jews to be \"eradicated\" as \"nature's financial parasite and nature's social vermin\", and had said that the UK had backed the wrong side in the Second World War, since the Nazis \"were there to remove Jewry from Europe once and for all.\" A person who had committed those same offences, whose name cannot be legally published in the UK, was found guilty at Preston Crown Court of inciting racial hatred on 8 January 2018.<ref>[https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/neo-nazi-called-for-eradication-of-jews-at-far-right-rally-mbt9n8nlx \"Neo-Nazi called for eradication of Jews at far-right rally\"], ''The Times'', 9 January 2018 {{subscription}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2017, six people \u2013 31-year-old Christopher Lythgoe, from [[Warrington]], Garron Helm, 24, of [[Seaforth, Merseyside]]; Matthew Hankinson, 23, of [[Newton-le-Willows]], Merseyside; and Andrew Clarke, 33, and Michael Trubini, 35, both of Warrington, along with Jack Renshaw, were charged with being members of National Action, which is banned in the UK. Two of the men, Lythgoe and Renshaw, were also charged with being involved in a plot to murder the [[West Lancashire (UK Parliament constituency)|West Lancashire]] [[Member of parliament|MP]] [[Rosie Cooper]] with a [[machete]], and of threatening to kill a police officer. In July 2017, a former National Action member, Robbie Mullen, reported the plot to the anti-racism organisation [[Hope not Hate|Hope Not Hate]], who reported the matter to the police.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-44873178 |title=Men jailed for neo-Nazi group membership |date=18 July 2018 |work=BBC News |accessdate=18 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe six faced trial on 11 June 2018 at the [[Old Bailey]] in London.<ref>Hirst, Lauren, [http://www.warringtonguardian.co.uk/news/16148218.Alleged_leader_of_National_Action_appears_in_crown_court/ \"Alleged leader of National Action appears in crown court\"] ''[[Warrington Guardian]]'', 10 April 2017.</ref> The next day, Renshaw pleaded guilty to plotting to murder Rosie Cooper, and to threatening to kill a police officer.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-44452529 |title=MP's murder was to be 'white jihad' |date=12 June 2018 |publisher= |accessdate=12 June 2018 |work=BBC News}}</ref> The following month, Hankinson and Lythgoe were found guilty of being members of National Action and jailed for six years and eight years, respectively. The presiding judge, Mr Justice Jay, told Hankinson: \"You are a neo-Nazi who glorifies and revels in a perverted ideology, has a deep hatred of ethnic minorities and Jews and has advocated violence to achieve your objectives.\" Helm was found not guilty of being a member of the group and Lythgoe was found not guilty of encouragement to murder for allegedly giving Renshaw permission to kill Ms Cooper on behalf of the group.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nAccording to the [[BBC]] and ''[[The Independent]]'', six people \u2013 five men and a woman \u2013 were arrested in co-ordinated raids by the West Midlands Counter Terrorism Unit, and were charged with being members of National Action. The six &ndash; Nathan Pryke, 26, from [[Cambridge]]; Adam Thomas, 21, and Claudia Patatas, 38, both of [[Banbury, Oxfordshire]]; Darren Fletcher, 28, of [[Wednesfield]], [[Wolverhampton]]; Daniel Bogunovic, 26, of [[Leicester]]; and Joel Wilmore, 24, of [[Hazel Grove]], [[Stockport]] &ndash; appeared in court in January 2018 and entered pleas of not guilty. All except Patatas gave their nationality as British; Patatas is Portuguese. Several of the group also faced additional charges.<ref>[https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-42625287 \"National Action: Six in court on terror group charges\"], BBC News, 9 January 2018<br />- Dearden, Lizzie, [https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/crime/national-action-trial-latest-updates-neo-nazis-terorrist-group-westminster-banned-white-supremacist-a8149931.html \"National Action: Six alleged neo-Nazis appear in court charged with joining banned terrorist group\"], ''[[The Independent]]'', 9 January 2018</ref> Thomas, Patatas and Bogunovic were convicted in November 2018. (''[[National Action (UK)#TripleK Mafia|see below]]'') In December 2018, the six received prison sentences varying between five and six-and-a-half years.<ref>Holliday, John (18 December 2018) [https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2018/dec/18/uk-couple-who-named-baby-after-hitler-jailed-for-terror-group-membership \"UK couple who named baby after Hitler jailed for terror group membership\"] ''[[The Guardian]]''</ref>\n\nTwo National Action members were imprisoned for eight years each at the Crown Court in Birmingham. In March 2018, Corporal Mikko Vehvilainen, 34, was described as a recruiter for National Action, a key part of whose strategy was to expand its membership within the armed forces. A self-confessed racist who believes in a coming \"race war\", Vehvilainen wanted to establish an all-white stronghold in the Welsh village of [[Llansilin]]. When arrested at his house there, police found a photograph of him giving a [[Nazi salute]] at a 1917 memorial to his native Finland's independence and an arsenal of weapons and swastika bunting. Another soldier, Private Mark Barrett, like Vehvilainen a member of the 2nd Battalion [[Royal Anglian Regiment]], was acquitted but is believed to have been dismissed by the Army. Alexander Deakin, 24, unemployed, was the Midlands regional organiser. He was seen on CCTV putting up racist stickers at [[Aston University]]. Deakin spread racist propaganda from his bedroom at his parents\u2019 house, telling fellow National Action members via encrypted chat that in a future \"race war\" they would have a \"KKK-themed death squad\". He bragged that counter-terrorism officers were incompetent and would never catch him, but he was found hiding in a cupboard when he was arrested. He was sentenced in April 2018.<ref>Haroon Siddique, [https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2018/nov/12/british-army-solider-recruited-far-right-group-national-action \"\"], ''The Guardian'', 12 November 2018. Retrieved 17 November 2018.</ref>\n\nIn May 2018, Wayne Bell, described as a \"poster boy\" for the organisation, pleaded guilty to two counts of stirring up racial hatred and three counts of possessing multiple items in order to destroy or damage property. The court heard that he had written neo-Nazi graffiti on pillars and lamp posts in his home town of [[Castleford]], and that he had made hundreds of racist and antisemitic posts on [[Twitter]] and the Russian social media site [[VKontakte]]. He was sentenced to four years and three months in prison.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-leeds-44226859 |work=BBC News |title=Wayne Bell jailed for neo-Nazi group social media posts |date=23 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Policy and actions==\n[[File:Mandela statue defaced.jpg|thumb|National Action held a protest at the [[Statue of Nelson Mandela, Parliament Square|statue of Nelson Mandela]] in London, defacing it with a banana.<ref name=\"Collins0315\"/>]] Davies described the group as \"like the BNP but more radical\".<ref name=mirror/> National Action self-styles itself as a \"revolutionary nationalist\" organisation which grew out of a failed offshoot within [[Resistance (YBNP)|the youth wing]] of the [[British National Party]] and has made effective, large-scale use of social media and blogging platforms.<ref name=\"HnH Hate Files\" />\n\nNational Action wanted to reintroduce [[Section 28]], which prohibited the \"[[promotion of homosexuality]]\" in schools.<ref name=huff/><ref name=mirror/> On immigration, \"Tom\" said \"With coloured people we'd say big no to them coming over. But with [white people] we'd be a bit more lenient\".<ref name=huff/>\n\nThe group has distributed its material on at least 12 university campuses.<ref name=huff/><ref name=mirror/> In an interview with ''[[The National Student]]'' in 2014, an anonymous organiser for National Action explained why they target universities: \"very soon they are going to find out just how hard the system has screwed them \u2013 if they knew what we know now we would have an army. The last Labour government aspired to send 50% of 18- to 21-year-olds to university and the total student population has grown exponentially over the past decade. That is 50% of youth who are going to be very angry burger flippers\".<ref name=student>{{cite news|last1=Filfilan|first1=Karam|title=\"This year will be a reign of terror\": Meet the white British Nationalists coming to your campus|url=http://www.thenationalstudent.com/Features/2014-04-25/This_year_will_be_a_reign_of_terror_Meet_the_white_British_Nationalists_coming_to_your_campus.html|accessdate=9 August 2014|work=[[The National Student]]|date=25 April 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140810112134/http://www.thenationalstudent.com/Features/2014-04-25/This_year_will_be_a_reign_of_terror_Meet_the_white_British_Nationalists_coming_to_your_campus.html|archivedate=10 August 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> He also promised \"This year will be a reign of terror\",<ref name=student/> and described people who are in [[interracial relationships]] as \"pathetic internet [[nerd]]s who can't get laid and [[Sexually transmitted disease|STD]]-infested [[sluts]]\".<ref name=\"student\"/>\n\nIn October 2014, Garron Helm, a National Action member from [[Merseyside]], was sentenced to four weeks in prison for sending a message via Twitter to MP [[Luciana Berger]] relating to her Jewish background, which was found to be \"an offensive, indecent or obscene message\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Perraudin |first1=Frances |title=Man jailed for antisemitic tweet to Labour MP |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2014/oct/20/man-jailed-antisemitic-tweet-labour-mp|accessdate=21 October 2014|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=21 October 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Collins0315\">{{cite news |last=Collins |first=Matthew |url=http://www.hopenothate.org.uk/get-hope/issue18/young-nazi-and-dangerous/ |title=National Action: Young, Nazi and Dangerous |work=Hope Not Hate |issue=18 |date=March\u2013April 2015 |accessdate=31 October 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161023195417/http://www.hopenothate.org.uk/get-hope/issue18/young-nazi-and-dangerous/|archivedate=23 October 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> \"I'm not a lunatic for embracing martyrdom, I've just accepted that I could be more use in death than life\", he wrote in early 2015.<ref name=\"Collins0315\"/> Helm served two weeks of his sentence before being released.<ref>{{cite news |last=Rouse |first=Alisha |url=http://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/news/liverpool-news/neo-nazi-not-sorry-slightest-vile-8558360 |title=Neo-Nazi \"not sorry in the slightest\" for vile abuse sent to Luciana Berger |work=[[Liverpool Echo]] |date=2 February 2015 |accessdate=12 December 2016}}</ref> In November 2014, 10 National Action activists were arrested in [[dawn raid]]s on suspicion of conspiring to cause [[criminal damage]] to Berger's office; they were all bailed.<ref name=\"Rosthorn\"/><ref>{{cite news|last=Dysch|first=Marcus|url=https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/ten-arrested-near-luciana-berger-s-liverpool-office-1.60959|title=Ten arrested near Luciana Berger\u2019s Liverpool office|work=The Jewish Chronicle|date=11 November 2014|accessdate=12 December 2016}}</ref> No further action was taken against them.<ref>{{cite news |last=Rouse |first=Alisha |url=http://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/news/liverpool-news/no-further-action-against-neo-nazis-8552340 |title=No further action against neo-Nazis arrested outside Wavertree MP Luciana Berger's office |work=Liverpool Echo |date=31 January 2015 |accessdate=12 December 2016}}</ref> National Action's campaign against Berger was supported by US-based neo-Nazi website ''[[The Daily Stormer]]'', which offered advice on how to set up untraceable Twitter accounts in order to send abuse.<ref>{{cite news|last=Dysch|first=Marcus|title=Neo-Nazi gave out internet abuse tips in campaign against Luciana Berger|url=http://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/124917/neo-nazi-gave-out-internet-abuse-tips-campaign-against-luciana-berger|accessdate=24 November 2014|work=[[The Jewish Chronicle]]|date=30 October 2014}}<br />- {{cite news |last1=Woolf |first1=Marie |last2=Henry |first2=Robin |url=http://www.thesundaytimes.co.uk/sto/news/uk_news/People/article1481397.ece?shareToken=cbcde614d249c6cb344e59bcb9038ff7 |title=Hate tweets fired across Atlantic at Jewish MP |newspaper=The Sunday Times |date=9 November 2014 |accessdate=12 December 2016 |url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2015, National Action organised a \"White Man March\" on the [[Quayside]] in Newcastle upon Tyne during which police arrested nine people; those attending included North East representatives of the [[British National Party]] (BNP) and neo-Nazis from Eastern Europe.<ref name=\"Evening Chronicle 22 March 2015\">{{cite news |last=Southern |first=Keiran |authorlink= |title=Newcastle Quayside brought to a standstill as neo-Nazis invade the city |url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/news/quayside-brought-standstill-neo-nazis-invade-8893069 |date=22 March 2015 |newspaper=[[Evening Chronicle]] |location=Newcastle upon Tyne |accessdate=5 September 2017}}</ref> In June of the same year, 26-year-old Zack Davies, who told police that he was a member of National Action, was found guilty of the attempted murder of Sarandev Bhambra, a Sikh man and trainee dentist, in [[Mold, Flintshire]]. Dr Bhambra was struck in the head and nearly lost a hand in the attack, suffering \"life changing injuries\". Davies claimed this was revenge for the [[murder of Lee Rigby]] and chanted \"white power\" as he launched the attack.<ref>{{cite news |last=Harley |first=Nicola |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/crime/11699384/Attacker-on-Lee-Rigby-revenge-mission-guilty-of-attempted-murder.html |title=Dentist attack: 'If my brother was white this would be called a terror attack' |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |date=25 June 2015 |accessdate=12 December 2016}}<br />- {{cite news |last=Whelan |first=Brian |url=http://www.channel4.com/news/national-actions-zack-davies-guilty-of-attempted-murder |title=National Action's Zack Davies guilty of attempted murder |work=[[Channel 4 News]] |date=25 June 2015 |accessdate=25 June 2015}}<br />- {{cite news |last1=Badshar |first1=Nadeem |title=Dentist attacked with machete in revenge for Lee Rigby |url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/news/uk/crime/article4477453.ece |work=The Times |url-access=subscription |date=23 June 2015}}</ref> Davies was given a life sentence the following September, and is to serve for 14 years before being considered for parole.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.channel4.com/news/zack-davies-life-sentence-for-lee-rigby-revenge-murder |title=Zack Davies: life sentence for Wales neo-Nazi attack |work=Channel 4 News |date=11 September 2015 |accessdate=12 December 2016}}</ref> National Action publicly denied any association with Davies or his actions.<ref name=\"BBCNye\" />\n\nIn August 2015, the group attempted to hold a second 'White Man March' in Liverpool. Strong opposition from the Anti-Fascist Network and local activists forced the organisers to cancel the march and take refuge in the lost luggage collection point at [[Lime Street Station]].<ref name=\"Liverpool Echo 16 August 2015\">{{cite news |last=Hughes |first=Lorna |authorlink= |title=Liverpool said no to Neo-Nazi march - and this is how the Internet reacted |url=http://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/news/liverpool-said-no-neo-nazi-9866502 |date=16 August 2015 |newspaper=[[Liverpool Echo]] |location=Liverpool |accessdate=5 September 2017}}</ref> Tensions were raised by a letter to Mayor [[Joe Anderson (politician)|Joe Anderson]] threatening race riots; National Action claimed this was a forgery by an ''[[agent provocateur]]''.<ref>{{cite news |title=Liverpool: White Man March Neo-Nazis Cower In Station Depot After Being Pelted With Rubbish, Then Cancel Event |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2015/08/15/white-man-march-in-liverpool-canceled_n_7992084.html |accessdate=15 August 2015 |website=Huffington Post |date=15 August 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2016, ''[[The Sunday Times]]'' reported that \"fears that far-right activists may be grooming a new generation of [[Hitler Youth]] in the UK emerged\" after stickers from National Action proclaiming parts of Liverpool to be a \"Nazi-controlled zone\" appeared. The group also held a number of marches and demonstrations on [[Armistice Day]] and [[Remembrance Sunday]] proclaiming that \"[[Hitler]] was right\", and celebrated the election of [[Donald Trump]] as [[President-elect of the United States]] under the slogan of \"[[white power]]\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gadher |first1=Dipesh |title=Warning over rise of Hitler youth |url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/edition/news/warning-over-rise-of-hitler-youth-79pkwnfkl |accessdate=19 December 2016 |work=The Sunday Times |url-access=subscription |date=20 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nNational Action has called for a \"white jihad\" to \"cleanse Britain of parasites\" using leaflets, stickers and video.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hopkins |first1=Steven |title=Bizarre 'White Jihad' Video, As They Begin Recruitment Drive |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2016/02/10/neo-nazi-group-release-bizarre-recruitment-video_n_9201944.html?guccounter=1&guce_referrer=aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZ29vZ2xlLmNvbS8&guce_referrer_sig=AQAAAFwz0z2-KHlw2f6JMPG8ciPBynyc_IBhSqpoWqZHuOIv7c8Zv-rSx2MyC-pdqCxU3SQbynQx0LqPJBbcCqRK6hu_i0EtZE3EJPxx5uHdRYvLGWee10sejdZSPYfpYJJkQw85wrTdNJkaDPtibUt-l8kqpD8ZIWRBm_Echq7Z7NA9 |accessdate=19 March 2019 |publisher= |work=Huffington Post |date=10 February 2016}}<br />- {{cite news |last1=Adil |first1=Muna |title=I'm not surprised most terror suspects in the UK are white \u2013 we've been expecting to see this change for a while |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/voices/most-uk-terror-suspects-white-not-surprised-muna-adil-quilliam-a8536436.html |accessdate=19 March 2019 |publisher= |work=The Independent |date=13 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Responses==\n\"Tom\" reported that the group was monitored by the [[West Midlands Police#Counter Terrorism Unit (CTU)|West Midlands Counter Terrorism Unit]].<ref name=huff/> [[Gerry Gable]], the former editor of the anti-fascist magazine [[Searchlight (magazine)|''Searchlight'']], said, \"National Action are highly organised with a lot of foreign money backing them up. They\u2019re not looking to attract thickos who just want a fight. They want thinkers who are prepared to die for National Socialism.\"<ref name=record>{{cite news|last1=Filfilan|first1=Karam|title=Hateful and here: German Anti-Islam extremists rally in Glasgow in bid to recruit Scots|url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/news/scottish-news/hateful-here-german-anti-islam-extremists-4998372|accessdate=30 August 2015|newspaper=[[Daily Record (Scotland)|The Daily Record]]|date=18 January 2015}}</ref> [[Scotland Yard]] is reported to be \"very concerned\" by the group, but gave the official response, \"We cannot discuss details of individuals or organisations that may or may not be the subject of an investigation.\"<ref name=mirror/>\n\n[[Ian Austin]], a [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] MP whose adoptive father fled [[German occupation of Czechoslovakia|Nazi-occupied Czechoslovakia]], said of National Action, \"Seventy years ago, British heroes were fighting to liberate Europe from the scourge of Nazis and fascism. It's absolutely disgusting to see young British people praise Hitler today.\"<ref name=mirror/>\n\nOn 5 September 2017, it was reported that four serving male members of the [[British Army]] had been arrested under the [[Terrorism Act 2000]] on suspicion of being members of National Action: a 22-year-old from [[Birmingham]], a 32-year-old from [[Powys]], a 24-year-old from [[Ipswich]] and a 24-year-old from [[Northampton]].<ref name=telegraph5917>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/09/05/four-alleged-members-neo-nazi-group-arrested-suspicion-planning/ |title=British soldiers arrested by terror police for allegedly being members of banned neo-Nazi group |work=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]] |date=5 September 2017 |accessdate=5 September 2017 |first1=Danny |last1=Boyle |first2=Hayley |last2=Dixon |lastauthoramp=yes}}</ref> A fifth man was reported to have been detained in Cyprus.<ref name=\"guardian5917\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2017/sep/05/four-held-on-suspicion-of-being-members-of-outlawed-neo-nazi-group-national-action |title=Five army men held over alleged membership of banned UK neo-Nazi group |last1=Grierson |first1=Jamie |work=The Guardian |accessdate=5 September 2017}}</ref> As a result, three men, including two British soldiers, were charged with terrorism offences.<ref name=bbc11917>{{cite news |author=Staff |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-41234539 |title=Neo-Nazi arrests: UK soldiers charged with terror offences |date=11 September 2017 |work=BBC News |accessdate=28 September 2017}}</ref> On 27 September 2017, eleven men were arrested in further raids across England and Wales.<ref name=\"huff27917\">{{cite web |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/entry/national-action-arrests_uk_59cb7d4ee4b05063fe0de646 |title=National Action: Eleven People Arrested As Part Of Probe Into Banned Far Right Group |last=Sommers |first=Jack |date=27 September 2017 |work=Huffington Post |accessdate=28 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 3 January 2018, six people \u2013 five men from Cambridge, Banbury, Wolverhampton, Leicester and Stockport, and a woman from Banbury \u2013 were arrested on suspicion of being concerned in the commission, preparation and instigation of acts of terrorism, namely on suspicion of being a member of a proscribed organisation, National Action. Those arrested were aged between 21 and 37.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-42552750 \"Six held in far-right group National Action investigation\"], BBC News, 3 January 2018. Retrieved 3 January 2018.<br />- [https://news.sky.com/story/six-people-arrested-over-suspected-membership-of-banned-national-action-group-11193980 \"National Action investigation: Six held over suspected membership of banned far-right group\"], ''[[Sky News]]'', 3 January 2018. Retrieved 3 January 2018.<br />- Dearden, Lizzie, [https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/crime/national-action-arrests-neo-nazi-terror-offences-uk-suspicion-latest-news-woman-man-midlands-police-a8139276.html \"National Action: Six alleged members of neo-Nazi group arrested on suspicion of terror offences\"], ''The Independent'', 3 January 2018. Retrieved 3 January 2018.</ref>\n\n==Lead-up to proscription==\nIn November 2016, ''The Sunday Times'' reported that National Action was supporting Thomas Mair, the [[Murder of Jo Cox|murderer of]] the Batley and Spen [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] MP [[Jo Cox]], posting \"only 649 MPs to go!\" on social media.<ref name=\"Home Office\">{{cite web |title=Proscribed Terrorist Organisations |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/578385/201612_Proscription.pdf |website=gov.uk |publisher=[[Home Office]] |page=15 |format=PDF document}}</ref> National Action also supported Mair personally, saying \"don't let this man's sacrifice go in vain\"<ref name=\"Home Office\" /> and altered its listing on Google to state: \"Death to traitors, freedom for Britain!\", a slogan Mair had said to a court when asked to give his name following Cox's murder.<ref name=\"GadherTimes\" /> The organisation also supported the [[2016 Orlando nightclub shooting|Orlando gun homicide]] and has called for graphic and violent attacks on police officers in the UK.<ref name=\"Home Office\" /> Mair, however, appeared to have little involvement with National Action or any other white supremacist groups within the UK.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Cobain |first1=Ian |title=The slow-burning hatred that led Thomas Mair to murder Jo Cox |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2016/nov/23/thomas-mair-slow-burning-hatred-led-to-jo-cox-murder |newspaper=The Guardian |accessdate=11 December 2016}}</ref>\n\nBefore it was banned, the organisation was the most active in Yorkshire, where half of the referrals to the government's anti-extremism strategy have been about the far-right.<ref name=\"GadherTimes\" /> In October, the ''[[Jewish Chronicle]]'' reported that the organisation's leaflets \"including swastikas, a Nazi salute and the phrase 'no tolerance'\" were spotted in Hull, Liverpool, Glasgow and Cardiff.<ref name=\"Hull Daily Mail\">[http://www.hulldailymail.co.uk/banned-neo-nazi-terrorist-group-national-action-active-in-hull/story-29979290-detail/story.html \"Banned neo-Nazi terrorist group National Action active in Hull\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161214171903/http://www.hulldailymail.co.uk/banned-neo-nazi-terrorist-group-national-action-active-in-hull/story-29979290-detail/story.html |date=14 December 2016 }}, ''Hull Daily Mail'', 14 December 2016.</ref> The ''[[Hull Daily Mail]]'' says that \"The first evidence of the group in the city was in July when graffiti appeared on a wall on George Street in the city centre with an incorrectly painted Swastika, the letters NA and a logo.\"<ref name=\"Hull Daily Mail\" /> In a newsletter, National Action claimed that although the group was \"not entirely sure who could {{sic|of}} done\" the graffiti, \"it seems we have got quite a following in Hull, with graffiti (even though backwards) of swastikas and an attempt at our logo and the initials NA popping up around Hull and triggering the reactionary left.\"<ref name=\"Hull Daily Mail\" />\n\nNational Action has promoted the [[antisemitic conspiracy theories]] that Jews were behind the [[September 11 attacks]] and has labelled Cox as the \"patron saint\" of grooming gangs, according to ''The Sunday Times''.<ref name=\"GadherTimes\" /> At a secret meeting of the Yorkshire Forum, Renshaw said (in a video seen by ''[[The Times]]'') that they need to adopt a \"killer instinct\". According to him: \"As nationalists we need to learn from the mistakes of the national socialists and we need to realise that, no, you do not show the Jew mercy\".<ref name=\"Hamilton28Nov\" />\n\nThe group was proscribed as a terrorist organisation under the [[Terrorism Act 2000]], making it a criminal offence to support or be a member after 16 December 2016.<ref>{{cite news|last=Elgot|first=Jessica|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/dec/12/neo-nazi-group-national-action-banned-by-uk-home-secretary|title=Neo-Nazi group National Action banned by UK home secretary|work=The Guardian|date=12 December 2016|accessdate=12 December 2016}}</ref> In laying an order for National Action's proscription, the Home Secretary, [[Amber Rudd]], described the group as \"a racist, antisemitic and homophobic organisation which stirs up hatred, glorifies violence and promotes a vile ideology\".<ref name=\"BBC Terror Org\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-38286708 |title=Far right group National Action to be banned under terror laws |work=BBC News |date=12 December 2016}}</ref> National Action is the first far-right organisation to be proscribed in the UK since the now-defunct British Union of Fascists in the 1940s.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://politicalscrapbook.net/2016/12/national-action-the-first-far-right-group-to-be-banned-in-britain-since-1940-but-it-is-not-enough/ |title=National Action the first far-right group to be banned in Britain since 1940, \u2018but it is not enough\u2019 |work=Political Scrapbook |date=12 December 2016 |accessdate=21 January 2018}}</ref> National Action is one of only three terrorist organisations based in [[Great Britain]] to be proscribed (the other two being radical Islamist organisations).<ref name=\"BBC Far-right rise\">De Simone, Samuel,  [https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-38293314 \"National Action ban highlights concern over far right\"], BBC News, 12 December 2016</ref> Its ban was seen as an acknowledgement by the UK government that the far-right was on the rise, and figures released by the [[National Police Chiefs' Council]] show that the number of far-right referrals to the anti-terror [[Prevent strategy|''Prevent'' programme]] increased from 323 cases in 2014\u201315 to 561 in 2015\u201316.<ref name=\"BBC Far-right rise\" />\n\n==Aliases==\n\n=== Scottish Dawn ===\nSuspicion that some National Action followers simply swapped membership of National Action for membership of the group Scottish Dawn in order to circumvent the ban prompted the [[Home Office]] to consider whether the new group should be outlawed too. Scottish Dawn was established shortly after National Action was banned and described itself as a \"new [[Identitarian movement|Identitarian]] social movement formed from various organisations in 2017 to develop a coherent conception of [[Scottish national identity|Scottish identity]] and secure its place within Scottish politics\".<ref>{{cite news |last=Kachroo |first=Rohit |title=Scottish far-right group could become second neo-Nazi organisation in Britain to be banned |url=https://www.itv.com/news/2017-09-14/far-right-group-in-scotland-could-become-second-neo-nazi-organisation-in-britain-to-be-banned/ |work=[[ITV News at Ten]] |publisher= [[ITN]] |date=14 September 2017 |accessdate=15 September 2017}} [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TCr9oMHlNQ4 Video.]<br />- {{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-41440467 |title=Who are the Scottish Dawn neo-Nazi group? |last=Nicolson |first=Stuart |date=29 September 2017 |work=BBC News |accessdate=5 February 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== NS131 ===\nNS131 (National Socialist Anti-Capitalist Action) was another group that appeared after National Action was proscribed and was \"a platform dedicated to promoting and spreading NS street art and physical propaganda\" according to its website. On 28 September 2017, after eleven suspected members across the country were arrested, the government announced that both Scottish Dawn and NS131 would be banned as aliases of National Action.<ref>{{cite news |author=Staff |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-41430740 |title=Two neo-Nazi groups added to banned list |date=28 September 2017 |work=BBC News |accessdate=28 September 2017}}<br />- {{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/crime/national-action-arrest-terror-terrorist-far-right-neo-nazi-police-counter-terror-soldiers-wales-a7969566.html |title=11 people arrested in neo-Nazi terror investigation |date=28 September 2017 |author=Dearden, Lizzie |newspaper=The Independent |accessdate=28 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== System Resistance Network ===\nSystem Resistance Network (SRN) is a group that is believed to have been putting up homophobic and anti-refugee posters in Dundee, Swansea, Cardiff and Bristol, and is claimed by [[Hope not Hate]] to be another alias of National Action.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://theferret.scot/system-resistance-network/ |title=Neo-Nazi outfit in Scotland linked to banned terrorist group |date=4 January 2018 |work=The Ferret |accessdate=5 February 2018}}<br />- {{cite news |url=https://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/news/scottish-news/banned-group-behind-new-neo-11754558 |title=Banned group behind new neo-Nazi campaign recruiting in Scotland, say activists |last=Briggs |first=Billy |date=27 December 2017 |work=Daily Record |accessdate=5 February 2018}}</ref> SRN was formerly known as Vanguard Britannia, the British chapter of American [[alt-right]], [[neo-Nazi]] group [[Vanguard America]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.vice.com/en_uk/article/j555p7/nazi-group-linked-to-charlottesville-attack-has-a-uk-chapter |title=Nazi Group Linked to Charlottesville Attack Has a UK Chapter |date=18 August 2017 |work=Vice |accessdate=5 February 2018}}<br />- {{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/crime/national-action-neo-nazis-banned-terrorist-groups-scottish-dawn-ns131-jews-gay-muslims-jo-cox-police-a7974836.html |title=Neo-Nazi terrorist groups still recruiting despite being banned as aliases of National Action |date=29 September 2017 |work=The Independent |accessdate=5 February 2018}}</ref> Former members of the SRN are suspected to have been involved in the creation of the [[Sonnenkrieg Division]], an offshoot of the American neo-Nazi terrorist organization the [[Atomwaffen Division]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-46460442 |work=BBC News |date=5 December 2018 |accessdate=6 December 2018|title=British Neo-Nazis suggest Prince Harry should be shot |author=Sanford, Daniel and DeSimone, Daniel}}</ref>\n\n=== TripleK Mafia ===\nDuring the 2018 trial of three people for being members of National Action, it emerged that a successor organization named the TripleK Mafia had been set up by the defendants. This rebrand was made in an attempt to \"shed one skin for another\"; the name was a reference to notorious American group the [[Ku Klux Klan]]. The group name was misspelled as \"TrippleK\" four times in new posters by member Joel Wilmore. Two of the defendants in the trial, Adam Thomas, 22, and Claudia Patatas, 38, had named their newborn baby Adolf in honour of Hitler and posed with the child while dressed in KKK robes and with [[Flag of Germany|swastika flags]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.sky.com/story/suspected-neo-nazi-father-posed-with-baby-adolf-while-wearing-kkk-robes-11522952 |title=Suspected neo-Nazi father 'posed with baby Adolf while wearing KKK robes' |work=Sky News |date=15 October 2018 |accessdate=20 October 2018}}<br />- {{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-oxfordshire-45814439 |title=Dad 'posed in KKK robes with baby Adolf' |date=10 October 2018 |work=BBC News |accessdate=20 October 2018}}</ref> The third defendant was a \"prominent member of National Action's Midlands chapter\", Daniel Bogunovic, 27. All three were convicted after a seven-week trial at the Crown Court in Birmingham.<ref>{{cite news |last=Barnes |first=Tom |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/crime/national-action-baby-adolf-hitler-terror-guilty-nazi-court-patatas-a8629846.html |title=National Action: Couple who named baby after Hitler found guilty of being part of neo-Nazi terror group |work=The Independent |date=12 November 2018 |accessdate=12 November 2018}}<br />- {{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-oxfordshire-46151838 |title=National Action trial: Three guilty of neo-Nazi group membership |work=BBC News |date=12 November 2018 |accessdate=12 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Combat 18]] (C18), a British neo-Nazi organization whose members are banned from joining the police or the [[Her Majesty's Prison Service|Prison Service]].\n* [[National Socialist Underground]] (NSU), a German neo-Nazi group\n* [[Atomwaffen Division]], an American neo-Nazi group\n* [[Atomwaffen Division#Sonnenkrieg Division|Sonnenkrieg Division]], another British neo-Nazi organization whose members have ties to National Action and two have been convicted for suggesting violence against [[Prince Harry, Duke of Sussex]], for his marriage to [[Meghan Markle]]\n\n==References== \n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Neo-Nazism}}\n{{UK far right}}\n{{Portal bar|Politics|United Kingdom}}\n\n[[Category:Illegal organizations]]\n[[Category:Banned far-right parties]]\n[[Category:2013 establishments in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Neo-Nazi organisations in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Youth organisations based in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Secret societies in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:British nationalism]]\n[[Category:Antisemitism in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Organisations designated as terrorist by the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Neo-fascist terrorism]]\n[[Category:White nationalist terrorism]]\n[[Category:Far-right parties in Europe]]\n", "name_user": "Aitch & Aitch Aitch", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLead-up to proscription", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/National_Action_(UK)"}
{"title_page": "Paul Ritter (actor)", "text_new": "{{short description|British actor}}\n{{EngvarB|date=November 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Paul Ritter\n| image              = https://vignette.wikia.nocookie.net/the-last-kingdom/images/8/8b/Paul_Ritter.png/revision/latest?cb=20170909211648\n| imagesize          = \n| alt                = \n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1966|03|05}}\n| birth_place        = [[Kent]], England\n| death_date         = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} Death date then birth -->\n| death_place        = \n| occupation         = Actor\n| years_active       = 1992\u2013present\n| spouse             = \n| domesticpartner    = \n| website            = \n}}\n\n'''Paul Ritter'''  (born 5 March 1966){{cn|date=June 2018}} is an English stage and screen actor who is very good at being a foot. He is best known for his roles in films including ''[[Quantum of Solace]]'', ''[[Son of Rambow]]'', ''[[Harry Potter and the Half-Blood Prince (film)|Harry Potter and the Half-Blood Prince]]'', and ''[[The Eagle (2011 film)|The Eagle]]'', as well as television programmes including ''[[Vera (TV series)|Vera]]'',<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/news/a182167/mckee-blethyn-sign-for-new-itv1-thriller.html |title=McKee, Blethyn sign for new ITV1 thriller |author=Dan French |date=15 October 2009 |work= |publisher=[[Digital Spy]] |accessdate=18 March 2010}}</ref> ''[[Friday Night Dinner]]'',<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/news/a203100/greig-bird-for-new-channel-4-comedy.html |title=Greig, Bird for new Channel 4 comedy |author=Catriona Wightman |date=13 February 2010 |work= |publisher=[[Digital Spy]] |accessdate=18 March 2010}}</ref> ''[[The Hollow Crown (TV series)|The Hollow Crown]],''<ref>{{cite press release |title=Cast confirmed for BBC Two's cycle of Shakespeare films |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/latestnews/shakespeare-cast.html |publisher=BBC Drama Publicity |date=24 November 2011 |accessdate=20 July 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/64JKhsWGc?url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/latestnews/shakespeare-cast.html |archivedate=30 December 2011 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Peredur in ''[[The Last Kingdom (TV series)|The Last Kingdom]]''<ref>http://www.radiotimes.com/episode/dvr5q5/the-last-kingdom--series-1---episode-6</ref> and [[Anatoly Dyatlov]] in ''[[Chernobyl (miniseries)|Chernobyl]]''.\n\n==Career==\nRitter's screen work has included roles in ''[[Nowhere Boy]]'', the 2007 television serial ''[[Instinct (TV serial)|Instinct]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationaltheatre.org.uk/discover-more/artists/paul-ritter|title=National Theatre : Company Members : Paul Ritter|author=Catriona Wightman|publisher=[[Royal National Theatre|National Theatre]]|accessdate=18 March 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141217013011/http://www.nationaltheatre.org.uk/discover-more/artists/paul-ritter|archivedate=17 December 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> the comedy drama ''[[Pulling (TV series)|Pulling]]'', the role of Pistol in ''[[Henry IV, Part I and Part II (film series)|Henry IV, Part II]]'' in [[BBC Two]]'s cycle of [[William Shakespeare]]'s history plays, ''The Hollow Crown'', comic actor [[Eric Sykes]] in ''[[Tommy Cooper: Not Like That, Like This]]'' and a lead role in [[BBC One]]'s 2014 serialised [[Cold War]] spy drama, ''[[The Game (UK TV series)|The Game]]''. ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' described Ritter as \"an actor who is surely destined for greatness very soon. His Pistol conveyed perfectly the shock of a man who reluctantly had left behind the rowdy cheer of Eastcheap, and found himself in middle age contemplating the melancholy of a medieval autumn.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Lawrence|first=Ben|title=The Hollow Crown: Henry V, BBC Two, review|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/9415849/The-Hollow-Crown-Henry-V-BBC-Two-review.html|accessdate=14 October 2012|newspaper=The Telegraph|date=22 July 2012}}</ref>\n\nFrom 2005 to 2006, Ritter played Otis Gardiner in the original [[Royal National Theatre]] production of [[Helen Edmundson]]'s ''[[Coram Boy (play)|Coram Boy]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nationaltheatre.org.uk/discover-more/artists/paul-ritter |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-03-18 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141217013011/http://www.nationaltheatre.org.uk/discover-more/artists/paul-ritter |archivedate=17 December 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> He was nominated for a [[Tony Awards|Tony Award]] in 2009 for his role in ''[[The Norman Conquests]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.playbill.com/news/article/128922-Nominations-for-2009-Tony-Awards-Announced-Billy-Elliot-Earns-15-Nominations |title=Nominations for 2009 Tony Awards Announced; Billy Elliot Earns 15 Nominations |author=Andrew Gans |date=5 May 2009 |publisher=[[Playbill]] |accessdate=18 March 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110604233106/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/128922-Nominations-for-2009-Tony-Awards-Announced-Billy-Elliot-Earns-15-Nominations |archivedate=4 June 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In 2012, he appeared as the protagonist's father in the stage version of [[Mark Haddon]]'s novel ''[[The Curious Incident of the Dog in the Night-Time (play)|The Curious Incident of the Dog in the Night-Time]]'' at the [[Royal National Theatre|National Theatre]]<ref>{{cite news|last=Geoghegan|first=Kev|title=National Theatre adapts Mark Haddon's Curious Incident|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-19099159|accessdate=14 October 2012|newspaper=BBC News|date=6 August 2012}}</ref> and in 2013 as [[John Major]] in the premiere of Peter Morgan's ''[[The Audience (2013 play)|The Audience]]''.\n\nAs of 2020 he is known for playing Martin Goodman in [[Channel 4]] comedy series [[Friday Night Dinner]], a role he has played since 2011.\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" ;\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Year\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Title\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Role\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Notes\n|-\n|1992 \n|''[[The Bill]] - Overdue''\n|Tony Walgrave\n|\n|-\n|1999\n|''G:MT Greenwich Mean Time''\n|Drug Buyer\n|\n|-\n|2000\n|''[[The Nine Lives of Tomas Katz]]''\n|Dave\n|\n|-\n|2002\n|''[[Esther Kahn]]''\n|Alman, the photographer\n|\n|-\n|2004\n|''[[The Libertine (2004 film)|The Libertine]]''\n|Chiffinch\n|\n|-\n|2005\n|''[[On a Clear Day (film)|On a Clear Day]]''\n|Mad Bob\n|\n|-\n|2007\n|''[[Son of Rambow]]''\n|Geography teacher\n|\n|-\n|2007\n|''[[Hannibal Rising (film)|Hannibal Rising]]''\n|Prisoner Louis\n|\n|-\n|2008\n|''[[The Other Man (2008 film)|The Other Man]]''\n|Guy\n|\n|-\n|2008\n|''[[Quantum of Solace]]''\n|Guy Haines\n|\n|-\n|2009\n|''[[Harry Potter and the Half-Blood Prince]]''\n|Eldred Worple\n|\n|-\n|2009\n|''[[Nowhere Boy]]''\n|Popjoy\n|\n|-\n|2010\n|''[[No Pressure (film)|No Pressure]]''\n|Office Manager\n| Short film\n|-\n|2011\u2013present\n|''[[Friday Night Dinner]]''\n|Martin Goodman\n|\n|-\n|2011\n|''[[Great Expectations (2011 miniseries)|Great Expectations]]''\n|[[John Wemmick]]\n|\n|-\n|2011\n|''[[Land Girls (TV series)|Land Girls]]''\n|Frank Tucker\n|\n|-\n|2011\n|''[[The Eagle (2011 film)|The Eagle]]''\n|Galba\n|\n|-\n|2011\u20132013\n|''[[Vera (TV series)|Vera]]''\n|Dr Billy Cartwright\n|\n|-\n|2011\n|''Eliminate: Archie Cookson''\n|Ennis Miller\n|\n|-\n|2012\n|''[[Comedy Showcase]]''\n|Jim Costello\n|\n|-\n|2012\n|''[[Dirk Gently (TV series)|Dirk Gently]]''\n|Oliver Reynolds\n|\n|-\n|2012\n|''[[Henry IV, Part I and Part II (film series)|Henry IV, Part II]]''\n|Pistol\n|\n|-\n|2014\n|''[[The Bletchley Circle]]''\n|Professor Masters\n|TV series (Episode: \"Blood on their hands - Part 2\")\n|-\n|2014\n|''[[Tommy Cooper: Not Like That, Like This]]''\n|[[Eric Sykes]]\n|\n|-\n|2014\n|''[[Chasing Shadows (TV series)|Chasing Shadows]]''\n|Leonard Vance\n|\n|-\n|2014\n|''[[The Game (UK TV series)|The Game]]''\n|Bobby Waterhouse\n|\n|-\n|2014\n|''[[Mapp and Lucia (BBC TV series)|Mapp and Lucia]]''\n|Reverend Kenneth Bartlett\n|\n|-\n|2014\n|''[[Suite Fran\u00e7aise (film)|Suite Fran\u00e7aise]]''\n|Monsieur Dubois\n|\n|-\n|2014\n|''[[The Bletchley Circle]]'' \n|Professor Masters\n|\n|-\n|2015\u2013present\n|''[[No Offence]]''\n|Randolph Miller\n|\n|-\n|2015\n|''[[Top Coppers]]''\n|Harry McCrane\n|\n|-\n|2015\n|''We're Doomed! The Dad's Army Story''\n|[[Jimmy Perry]]\n|\n|-\n|2016\n|''[[Their Finest]]''\n|Raymond Parfitt\n|\n|-\n|2016\n|''Neil Gaiman's Likely Stories''\n|Dr. Benham/Martyn/Mr. Alman\n|\n|-\n|2016\n|''[[Inferno (2016 film)|Inferno]]''\n|CRC Tech Arbogast\n|\n|-\n|2017\n|''[[Urban Myths]]''\n|Dave\n|Episode: \"Bob Dylan: Knockin' on Dave's Door\"\n|-\n|2017\n|''[[Philip K. Dick's Electric Dreams]]''\n|Franklyn\n|\n|-\n|2017\u20132019\n|''[[Cold Feet]]''\n|Benjamin Stevens\n|\n|-\n|2018\n|''[[Lovesick (TV series)|Lovesick]]''\n|Peter\n|\n|-\n|2018\n|[[Hang Ups (TV series)|''Hang Ups'']]\n|Werner Lienhard\n|\n|-\n|2019\n|[[Resistance (miniseries)|''Resistance'']]\n|General Ormonde Winter\n|\n|-\n|2019\n|[[Chernobyl (miniseries)|''Chernobyl'']]\n|[[Anatoly Dyatlov]]\n|\n|-\n|2019\n|[[The Capture (TV series)|''The Capture'']]\n|Marcus Levy\n|\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''[[The Trial of Christine Keeler]]''\n| Jeremy Hutchinson\n| Defence barrister of [[Christine Keeler]]\n|-\n| 2020\n| ''[[Belgravia (TV series)]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.radiotimes.com/news/tv/2020-03-15/belgravia-itv-cast/|title=Meet the cast of ITV's Belgravia|website=[[Radio Times]]}}</ref>\n| Turton\n| TV Series\n|-\n| TBA\n| ''[[Operation Mincemeat (film)|Operation Mincemeat]]''\n|\n| Filming\n|}\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Award/Event !! Category !! Work !! Result !! Ref\n|-\n| 2009 || [[Tony Awards]] || Best Performance by an Actor in a Featured Role in a Play || ''[[The Norman Conquests]]'' || {{nom}} ||<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.oftaawards.com/television-awards/23rd-annual-tv-awards-2018-19/|title=23rd Annual TV Awards (2018-19) - Online Film & Television Association|access-date=2020-01-25}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2019 || Online Film & Television Association || Best Ensemble in a Motion Picture or Limited Series<br><small>Shared with entire cast</small> || ''[[Chernobyl (miniseries)|Chernobyl]]'' || {{nom}} ||<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.broadwayworld.com/tonyawardspersoninfo.php?nomname=Paul%20Ritter|title=Paul Ritter Tony Awards Info|access-date=2020-01-25}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|728795|Paul Ritter}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ritter, Paul}}\n[[Category:1966 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century British male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century British male actors]]\n[[Category:British male film actors]]\n[[Category:British male stage actors]]\n[[Category:British male television actors]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n\n{{UK-film-actor-stub}}\n[[Category:Male actors from Kent]]\n[[Category:English male stage actors]]\n[[Category:English television actors]]\n[[Category:English male television actors]]\n[[Category:People from Kent]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British actor}}\n{{EngvarB|date=November 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Paul Ritter\n| image              = https://vignette.wikia.nocookie.net/the-last-kingdom/images/8/8b/Paul_Ritter.png/revision/latest?cb=20170909211648\n| imagesize          = \n| alt                = \n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1966|03|05}}\n| birth_place        = [[Kent]], England\n| death_date         = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} Death date then birth -->\n| death_place        = \n| occupation         = Actor\n| years_active       = 1992\u2013present\n| spouse             = \n| domesticpartner    = \n| website            = \n}}\n\n'''Paul Ritter'''  (born 5 March 1966){{cn|date=June 2018}} is an English stage and screen actor. He is best known for his roles in films including ''[[Quantum of Solace]]'', ''[[Son of Rambow]]'', ''[[Harry Potter and the Half-Blood Prince (film)|Harry Potter and the Half-Blood Prince]]'', and ''[[The Eagle (2011 film)|The Eagle]]'', as well as television programmes including ''[[Vera (TV series)|Vera]]'',<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/news/a182167/mckee-blethyn-sign-for-new-itv1-thriller.html |title=McKee, Blethyn sign for new ITV1 thriller |author=Dan French |date=15 October 2009 |work= |publisher=[[Digital Spy]] |accessdate=18 March 2010}}</ref> ''[[Friday Night Dinner]]'',<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/news/a203100/greig-bird-for-new-channel-4-comedy.html |title=Greig, Bird for new Channel 4 comedy |author=Catriona Wightman |date=13 February 2010 |work= |publisher=[[Digital Spy]] |accessdate=18 March 2010}}</ref> ''[[The Hollow Crown (TV series)|The Hollow Crown]],''<ref>{{cite press release |title=Cast confirmed for BBC Two's cycle of Shakespeare films |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/latestnews/shakespeare-cast.html |publisher=BBC Drama Publicity |date=24 November 2011 |accessdate=20 July 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/64JKhsWGc?url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/latestnews/shakespeare-cast.html |archivedate=30 December 2011 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Peredur in ''[[The Last Kingdom (TV series)|The Last Kingdom]]''<ref>http://www.radiotimes.com/episode/dvr5q5/the-last-kingdom--series-1---episode-6</ref> and [[Anatoly Dyatlov]] in ''[[Chernobyl (miniseries)|Chernobyl]]''.\n\n==Career==\nRitter's screen work has included roles in ''[[Nowhere Boy]]'', the 2007 television serial ''[[Instinct (TV serial)|Instinct]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationaltheatre.org.uk/discover-more/artists/paul-ritter|title=National Theatre : Company Members : Paul Ritter|author=Catriona Wightman|publisher=[[Royal National Theatre|National Theatre]]|accessdate=18 March 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141217013011/http://www.nationaltheatre.org.uk/discover-more/artists/paul-ritter|archivedate=17 December 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> the comedy drama ''[[Pulling (TV series)|Pulling]]'', the role of Pistol in ''[[Henry IV, Part I and Part II (film series)|Henry IV, Part II]]'' in [[BBC Two]]'s cycle of [[William Shakespeare]]'s history plays, ''The Hollow Crown'', comic actor [[Eric Sykes]] in ''[[Tommy Cooper: Not Like That, Like This]]'' and a lead role in [[BBC One]]'s 2014 serialised [[Cold War]] spy drama, ''[[The Game (UK TV series)|The Game]]''. ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' described Ritter as \"an actor who is surely destined for greatness very soon. His Pistol conveyed perfectly the shock of a man who reluctantly had left behind the rowdy cheer of Eastcheap, and found himself in middle age contemplating the melancholy of a medieval autumn.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Lawrence|first=Ben|title=The Hollow Crown: Henry V, BBC Two, review|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/9415849/The-Hollow-Crown-Henry-V-BBC-Two-review.html|accessdate=14 October 2012|newspaper=The Telegraph|date=22 July 2012}}</ref>\n\nFrom 2005 to 2006, Ritter played Otis Gardiner in the original [[Royal National Theatre]] production of [[Helen Edmundson]]'s ''[[Coram Boy (play)|Coram Boy]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nationaltheatre.org.uk/discover-more/artists/paul-ritter |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-03-18 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141217013011/http://www.nationaltheatre.org.uk/discover-more/artists/paul-ritter |archivedate=17 December 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> He was nominated for a [[Tony Awards|Tony Award]] in 2009 for his role in ''[[The Norman Conquests]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.playbill.com/news/article/128922-Nominations-for-2009-Tony-Awards-Announced-Billy-Elliot-Earns-15-Nominations |title=Nominations for 2009 Tony Awards Announced; Billy Elliot Earns 15 Nominations |author=Andrew Gans |date=5 May 2009 |publisher=[[Playbill]] |accessdate=18 March 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110604233106/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/128922-Nominations-for-2009-Tony-Awards-Announced-Billy-Elliot-Earns-15-Nominations |archivedate=4 June 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In 2012, he appeared as the protagonist's father in the stage version of [[Mark Haddon]]'s novel ''[[The Curious Incident of the Dog in the Night-Time (play)|The Curious Incident of the Dog in the Night-Time]]'' at the [[Royal National Theatre|National Theatre]]<ref>{{cite news|last=Geoghegan|first=Kev|title=National Theatre adapts Mark Haddon's Curious Incident|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-19099159|accessdate=14 October 2012|newspaper=BBC News|date=6 August 2012}}</ref> and in 2013 as [[John Major]] in the premiere of Peter Morgan's ''[[The Audience (2013 play)|The Audience]]''.\n\nAs of 2020 he is known for playing Martin Goodman in [[Channel 4]] comedy series [[Friday Night Dinner]], a role he has played since 2011.\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" ;\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Year\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Title\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Role\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Notes\n|-\n|1992 \n|''[[The Bill]] - Overdue''\n|Tony Walgrave\n|\n|-\n|1999\n|''G:MT Greenwich Mean Time''\n|Drug Buyer\n|\n|-\n|2000\n|''[[The Nine Lives of Tomas Katz]]''\n|Dave\n|\n|-\n|2002\n|''[[Esther Kahn]]''\n|Alman, the photographer\n|\n|-\n|2004\n|''[[The Libertine (2004 film)|The Libertine]]''\n|Chiffinch\n|\n|-\n|2005\n|''[[On a Clear Day (film)|On a Clear Day]]''\n|Mad Bob\n|\n|-\n|2007\n|''[[Son of Rambow]]''\n|Geography teacher\n|\n|-\n|2007\n|''[[Hannibal Rising (film)|Hannibal Rising]]''\n|Prisoner Louis\n|\n|-\n|2008\n|''[[The Other Man (2008 film)|The Other Man]]''\n|Guy\n|\n|-\n|2008\n|''[[Quantum of Solace]]''\n|Guy Haines\n|\n|-\n|2009\n|''[[Harry Potter and the Half-Blood Prince]]''\n|Eldred Worple\n|\n|-\n|2009\n|''[[Nowhere Boy]]''\n|Popjoy\n|\n|-\n|2010\n|''[[No Pressure (film)|No Pressure]]''\n|Office Manager\n| Short film\n|-\n|2011\u2013present\n|''[[Friday Night Dinner]]''\n|Martin Goodman\n|\n|-\n|2011\n|''[[Great Expectations (2011 miniseries)|Great Expectations]]''\n|[[John Wemmick]]\n|\n|-\n|2011\n|''[[Land Girls (TV series)|Land Girls]]''\n|Frank Tucker\n|\n|-\n|2011\n|''[[The Eagle (2011 film)|The Eagle]]''\n|Galba\n|\n|-\n|2011\u20132013\n|''[[Vera (TV series)|Vera]]''\n|Dr Billy Cartwright\n|\n|-\n|2011\n|''Eliminate: Archie Cookson''\n|Ennis Miller\n|\n|-\n|2012\n|''[[Comedy Showcase]]''\n|Jim Costello\n|\n|-\n|2012\n|''[[Dirk Gently (TV series)|Dirk Gently]]''\n|Oliver Reynolds\n|\n|-\n|2012\n|''[[Henry IV, Part I and Part II (film series)|Henry IV, Part II]]''\n|Pistol\n|\n|-\n|2014\n|''[[The Bletchley Circle]]''\n|Professor Masters\n|TV series (Episode: \"Blood on their hands - Part 2\")\n|-\n|2014\n|''[[Tommy Cooper: Not Like That, Like This]]''\n|[[Eric Sykes]]\n|\n|-\n|2014\n|''[[Chasing Shadows (TV series)|Chasing Shadows]]''\n|Leonard Vance\n|\n|-\n|2014\n|''[[The Game (UK TV series)|The Game]]''\n|Bobby Waterhouse\n|\n|-\n|2014\n|''[[Mapp and Lucia (BBC TV series)|Mapp and Lucia]]''\n|Reverend Kenneth Bartlett\n|\n|-\n|2014\n|''[[Suite Fran\u00e7aise (film)|Suite Fran\u00e7aise]]''\n|Monsieur Dubois\n|\n|-\n|2014\n|''[[The Bletchley Circle]]'' \n|Professor Masters\n|\n|-\n|2015\u2013present\n|''[[No Offence]]''\n|Randolph Miller\n|\n|-\n|2015\n|''[[Top Coppers]]''\n|Harry McCrane\n|\n|-\n|2015\n|''We're Doomed! The Dad's Army Story''\n|[[Jimmy Perry]]\n|\n|-\n|2016\n|''[[Their Finest]]''\n|Raymond Parfitt\n|\n|-\n|2016\n|''Neil Gaiman's Likely Stories''\n|Dr. Benham/Martyn/Mr. Alman\n|\n|-\n|2016\n|''[[Inferno (2016 film)|Inferno]]''\n|CRC Tech Arbogast\n|\n|-\n|2017\n|''[[Urban Myths]]''\n|Dave\n|Episode: \"Bob Dylan: Knockin' on Dave's Door\"\n|-\n|2017\n|''[[Philip K. Dick's Electric Dreams]]''\n|Franklyn\n|\n|-\n|2017\u20132019\n|''[[Cold Feet]]''\n|Benjamin Stevens\n|\n|-\n|2018\n|''[[Lovesick (TV series)|Lovesick]]''\n|Peter\n|\n|-\n|2018\n|[[Hang Ups (TV series)|''Hang Ups'']]\n|Werner Lienhard\n|\n|-\n|2019\n|[[Resistance (miniseries)|''Resistance'']]\n|General Ormonde Winter\n|\n|-\n|2019\n|[[Chernobyl (miniseries)|''Chernobyl'']]\n|[[Anatoly Dyatlov]]\n|\n|-\n|2019\n|[[The Capture (TV series)|''The Capture'']]\n|Marcus Levy\n|\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''[[The Trial of Christine Keeler]]''\n| Jeremy Hutchinson\n| Defence barrister of [[Christine Keeler]]\n|-\n| 2020\n| ''[[Belgravia (TV series)]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.radiotimes.com/news/tv/2020-03-15/belgravia-itv-cast/|title=Meet the cast of ITV's Belgravia|website=[[Radio Times]]}}</ref>\n| Turton\n| TV Series\n|-\n| TBA\n| ''[[Operation Mincemeat (film)|Operation Mincemeat]]''\n|\n| Filming\n|}\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Award/Event !! Category !! Work !! Result !! Ref\n|-\n| 2009 || [[Tony Awards]] || Best Performance by an Actor in a Featured Role in a Play || ''[[The Norman Conquests]]'' || {{nom}} ||<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.oftaawards.com/television-awards/23rd-annual-tv-awards-2018-19/|title=23rd Annual TV Awards (2018-19) - Online Film & Television Association|access-date=2020-01-25}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2019 || Online Film & Television Association || Best Ensemble in a Motion Picture or Limited Series<br><small>Shared with entire cast</small> || ''[[Chernobyl (miniseries)|Chernobyl]]'' || {{nom}} ||<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.broadwayworld.com/tonyawardspersoninfo.php?nomname=Paul%20Ritter|title=Paul Ritter Tony Awards Info|access-date=2020-01-25}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|728795|Paul Ritter}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ritter, Paul}}\n[[Category:1966 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century British male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century British male actors]]\n[[Category:British male film actors]]\n[[Category:British male stage actors]]\n[[Category:British male television actors]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n\n{{UK-film-actor-stub}}\n[[Category:Male actors from Kent]]\n[[Category:English male stage actors]]\n[[Category:English television actors]]\n[[Category:English male television actors]]\n[[Category:People from Kent]]\n", "name_user": "2a02:c7f:aebf:6f00:b00f:4f66:4197:b191", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Fixed typo)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paul_Ritter_(actor)"}
{"title_page": "Uddhav Thackeray", "text_new": "<br />{{short description|Indian politician and 19th Chief Minister of Maharashtra}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2015}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=December 2015}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Uddhav Thackeray\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1960|07|27}}<ref name=close/>\n| birth_name = Uddhav Bal Thackeray<ref>{{cite news |title=Uddhav Thackeray, first of his clan, takes oath as chief minister of Maharashtra |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/uddhav-thackeray-maharashtra-chief-minister-1623468-2019-11-28 |accessdate=17 December 2019 |work=India Today |date=28 November 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n| birth_place = [[Bombay]], [[Maharashtra]], [[India]] (present-day [[Mumbai]])\n| image = The Chief Minister of Maharashtra, Shri Uddhav Thackeray calling on the Prime Minister, Shri Narendra Modi, in New Delhi on February 21, 2020 (Uddhav Thackeray) (cropped).jpg\n| image_size = 250x250px\n| residence = Matoshree, [[Bandra]], Mumbai, Maharashtra, India\n| office = 19th [[Chief Minister of Maharashtra]]\n| term_start = 28 November 2019\n| predecessor = [[Devendra Fadnavis]]\n| governor = [[Bhagat Singh Koshyari]]\n| deputy = [[Ajit Pawar]]\n| office1 = [[Government of Maharashtra|Minister of General Administration, Law, Judiciary, Information, Public Relations and Information Technology<br/><small>''(Government of Maharashtra)''</small>]]\n| term_start1 = 28 November 2019\n| alma_mater =  [[Sir J.J. Institute of Applied Art]]\n| office2 = [[Shiv Sena|President of Shiv Sena]]\n| term_start2 = 23 January 2013\n| predecessor2 = [[Bal Thackeray]]\n| office3 = [[Editor-in-chief]], [[Saamana]]\n| term_start3 = June 2006\n| term_end3 = 28 November 2019\n| predecessor3 = [[Bal Thackeray]]\n| successor3 = [[Sanjay Raut]]\n| office4 = [[Shiv Sena|Working president of Shiv Sena]]\n| term_start4 = 2003\n| term_end4 = 2013\n| predecessor4 = Position established\n| successor4 = Position abolished\n| party = Shiv Sena\n| spouse = [[Rashmi Thackeray]]\n| children = 2, including [[Aditya Thackeray]]\n| father = [[Bal Thackeray]]\n| relatives = ''see [[Thackeray Family]]''\n| website = \n}}\nUddhav Bal Thackeray is an Indian politician serving as the 19th and current Chief Minister of Maharashtra.<ref name=close>{{cite web |url=http://www.rediff.com/election/2004/apr/22espec2.htm | title=Up close and personal with Uddhav Thackeray | publisher=[[Rediff.com]] | date=22 April 2004 | accessdate=25 April 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"IE28Nov\"/><ref name=\"FP29Nov\"/> \n\n== Early life and education==\nUddhav Thackeray was born on 27 July 1960 as the youngest of politician [[Bal Thackeray]] and his wife Meena Thackeray's three sons.<ref name=close/><ref>{{cite news |title=Uddhav Thackeray Oath Ceremony : \u0909\u0926\u094d\u0927\u0935 \u0920\u093e\u0915\u0930\u0947 \u092c\u0928\u0947 \u092e\u0939\u093e\u0930\u093e\u0937\u094d\u091f\u094d\u0930 \u0915\u0947 CM, \u091b\u0939 \u0915\u0948\u092c\u093f\u0928\u0947\u091f \u092e\u0902\u0924\u094d\u0930\u093f\u092f\u094b\u0902 \u0928\u0947 \u092d\u0940 \u0932\u0940 \u0936\u092a\u0925 |url=https://khabar.ndtv.com/news/india/maharashtra-government-oath-ceremony-live-updates-uddhav-thackeray-sharad-pawar-ajit-pawar-balasaheb-2139806 |accessdate=8 December 2019 |work=NDTVIndia |date=28 November 2019}}</ref> He did his schooling in [[Balmohan Vidyamandir]] and graduated from [[Sir J.J. Institute of Applied Art]].<ref>{{cite news | url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/uddhav-thackeray-sworn-in-19th-chief-minister-of-maharashtra/articleshow/72280087.cms?from=mdr | title=Uddhav Thackeray sworn in as the 18th chief minister of Maharashtra | newspaper=[[The Economic Times]] | date=28 November 2019 | accessdate=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Early political career ==\nIn 2002, Thackeray started his political career as campaign incharge of Shiv Sena in the [[Municipal Corporation of Greater Mumbai|Brihan Mumbai Municipal Corporation]] elections where the party performed well. In 2003, he was appointed as working president of Shiv Sena. Uddhav took over as chief editor of party mouthpiece ''[[Saamana]]'' (a daily [[Marathi language|Marathi]]-language newspaper published by Shiv Sena) in 2006 and resigned in 2019 before becoming chief minister of Maharashtra.<ref>{{cite news|title=Udhav Thackeray quite as Saamna editor|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/uddhav-thackeray-quits-as-saamana-editor-ahead-of-taking-over-as-maharashtra-chief-minister-1623340-2019-11-28|accessdate=29 November 2019|website=India}}</ref>\n\nA split in Shiv Sena happened when his cousin [[Raj Thackeray]] left the party in 2006 to form his own party named [[Maharashtra Navnirman Sena]].<ref>{{cite news |title=How A Murder Case Led To Raj Thackeray's Exit From Shiv Sena|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.in/entry/murder-case-raj-thackeray-exit-shiv-sena_in_5d88b9d3e4b070d468d03613 |accessdate=8 November 2019 |work=HuffPost India |date=25 September 2019 |language=en}}</ref> After the death of his father [[Bal Thackeray]] in 2012, he led the party and got elected as Shiv Sena president in 2013, and under his leadership Shiv Sena joined the [[National Democratic Alliance|NDA]] government in Maharashtra in 2014.<ref>{{cite web | work=Times of India|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/maharashtra-government-formation-news-live-uddhav-thackeray-swearing-in-as-cm/liveblog/72270170.cms| title=Maharashtra government formation news | date=22 April 2004 | accessdate=28 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Chief Minister of Maharashtra==\nThough Thackeray never took any constitutional post in his political career initially, however after a brief political crisis, on 28 November 2019 he took the oath as 19th Chief minister of Maharashtra after being elected as leader of the newly formed post-[[2019 Maharashtra Legislative Assembly election|poll]] coalition [[Maha Vikas Aghadi]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/maharashtra-government-formation-news-live-uddhav-thackeray-swearing-in-as-cm/liveblog/72270170.cms|title=Udhav Thackeray swearing in as CM|website=Times of India|access-date=28 November 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"IE28Nov\">{{cite news |title=Maharashtra swearing-in HIGHLIGHTS: Farmers first; Uddhav sets priority after first cabinet meet |url=https://indianexpress.com/article/india/maharashtra-live-updates-uddhav-thackeray-swearing-in-shiv-sena-ncp-congress-bjp-6140471/ |accessdate=29 November 2019 |work=The Indian Express |date=28 November 2019 |language=en-IN}}</ref><ref name=\"FP29Nov\">{{cite news |title=Uddhav Thackeray sworn in as 19th CM of Maharashtra: First of family to hold this office, 59-yr-old gets kudos from Modi, Sonia Gandhi |url=https://www.firstpost.com/politics/uddhav-thackeray-sworn-in-as-19th-cm-of-maharashtra-first-of-family-to-hold-this-office-59-yr-old-gets-kudos-from-modi-sonia-gandhi-7714171.html |accessdate=29 November 2019 |work=Firstpost |date=29 November 2019}}</ref> Since he is not an elected MLA from any constituency he may loose his chair if does not gets elected as mla within 6 months of power.\n\n==Personal life==\nThackeray is married to Rashmi Thackeray and has two sons, [[Aditya Thackeray|Aditya]] and Tejas.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/nation/Uddhav-May-Shift-to-New-House-After-LS-Elections/2014/04/09/article2157222.ece | title=Uddhav May Shift to New House After LS Elections | newspaper=[[Indian Express]] |place=Mumbai | date=9 April 2014 | accessdate=25 April 2014}}</ref>\n\nWhile elder son Aditya is the president of the Yuva Sena, younger son Tejas is believed to be studying in a college in [[Buffalo, New York]]. Tejas has maintained a very low profile unlike his father and elder brother. On 16 July 2012, Uddhav Thackeray was admitted to Lilavati Hospital after he reported chest pain. He underwent an [[angioplasty]] and all the three blockages in his arteries were successfully removed.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-07-23/india/32803671_1_shiv-sena-leader-uddhav-thackeray-maharashtra-navnirman-sena | title= Shiv Sena leader Uddhav Thackeray discharged from hospital | date= 23 July 2012}}</ref>\n\nThackeray is keen in photography and has exhibited his collection of aerial shots of various [[List of forts in Maharashtra|forts of Maharashtra]] at the [[Jehangir Art Gallery]] in 2004.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/exhibition-of-uddhay-thackeray-photographs-at-jehangir-art-gallery/1/196753.html | title=Thackeray's new conquest | magazine=[[India Today]] | date=26 January 2004 |place=Mumbai | accessdate=25 April 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.hindu.com/2004/01/14/stories/2004011401302200.htm | title=Uddhav Thackeray and those scenic forts | newspaper=[[The Hindu]] | date=14 January 2004 | accessdate=25 April 2014 | author=Vijapurkar, Mahesh}}</ref> He has also published [[photo-book]]s ''Maharashtra Desh'' (2010) and ''Pahava Vitthal'' (2011), capturing various aspects of Maharashtra and the [[varkari|warkari]]s during [[Shayani Ekadashi|Pandharpur Wari]] respectively in the two books.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/mumbai/raj-uddhav-slug-it-out-over-city-s-plight/article1-582470.aspx | title=Raj, Uddhav slug it out over city's plight | newspaper=[[Hindustan Times]] | date=5 August 2010 | accessdate=25 April 2014 | author=Kamath, Naresh}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.mid-day.com/articles/an-aerial-journey/121411 | title=An aerial journey | newspaper=[[Mid Day]] | date=10 May 2011 | accessdate=25 April 2014 | author=Chowdhury, Sudeshna}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Uddhav Thackeray ministry]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.maharashtra.gov.in/1137/1189/ Maharashtra Chief Minister's profile]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{Chief Ministers of Maharashtra}}\n{{Shiv Sena}}\n{{United Progressive Alliance}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Thackeray, Uddhav}}\n[[Category:1960 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Chief Ministers of Maharashtra]]\n[[Category:Marathi politicians]]\n[[Category:Maharashtra politicians]]\n[[Category:Shiv Sena politicians]]\n[[Category:Indian Hindus]]\n[[Category:Marathi people]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Mumbai]]\n[[Category:Bal Thackeray]]\n[[Category:Far-right politicians in India]]\n", "text_old": "Uddhav Bal Thackeray is an Indian politician serving as the 19th and current Chief Minister of Maharashtra. He is the president of Shiv Sena{{short description|Indian politician and 19th Chief Minister of Maharashtra}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2015}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=December 2015}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Uddhav Thackeray\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1960|07|27}}<ref name=close/>\n| birth_name = Uddhav Bal Thackeray<ref>{{cite news |title=Uddhav Thackeray, first of his clan, takes oath as chief minister of Maharashtra |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/uddhav-thackeray-maharashtra-chief-minister-1623468-2019-11-28 |accessdate=17 December 2019 |work=India Today |date=28 November 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n| birth_place = [[Bombay]], [[Maharashtra]], [[India]] (present-day [[Mumbai]])\n| image = The Chief Minister of Maharashtra, Shri Uddhav Thackeray calling on the Prime Minister, Shri Narendra Modi, in New Delhi on February 21, 2020 (Uddhav Thackeray) (cropped).jpg\n| image_size = 250x250px\n| residence = Matoshree, [[Bandra]], Mumbai, Maharashtra, India\n| office = 19th [[Chief Minister of Maharashtra]]\n| term_start = 28 November 2019\n| predecessor = [[Devendra Fadnavis]]\n| governor = [[Bhagat Singh Koshyari]]\n| deputy = [[Ajit Pawar]]\n| office1 = [[Government of Maharashtra|Minister of General Administration, Law, Judiciary, Information, Public Relations and Information Technology<br/><small>''(Government of Maharashtra)''</small>]]\n| term_start1 = 28 November 2019\n| alma_mater =  [[Sir J.J. Institute of Applied Art]]\n| office2 = [[Shiv Sena|President of Shiv Sena]]\n| term_start2 = 23 January 2013\n| predecessor2 = [[Bal Thackeray]]\n| office3 = [[Editor-in-chief]], [[Saamana]]\n| term_start3 = June 2006\n| term_end3 = 28 November 2019\n| predecessor3 = [[Bal Thackeray]]\n| successor3 = [[Sanjay Raut]]\n| office4 = [[Shiv Sena|Working president of Shiv Sena]]\n| term_start4 = 2003\n| term_end4 = 2013\n| predecessor4 = Position established\n| successor4 = Position abolished\n| party = Shiv Sena\n| spouse = [[Rashmi Thackeray]]\n| children = 2, including [[Aditya Thackeray]]\n| father = [[Bal Thackeray]]\n| relatives = ''see [[Thackeray Family]]''\n| website = \n}}\n[[Chief Minister of Maharashtra]].<ref name=close>{{cite web |url=http://www.rediff.com/election/2004/apr/22espec2.htm | title=Up close and personal with Uddhav Thackeray | publisher=[[Rediff.com]] | date=22 April 2004 | accessdate=25 April 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"IE28Nov\"/><ref name=\"FP29Nov\"/> \n\n== Early life and education==\nUddhav Thackeray was born on 27 July 1960 as the youngest of politician [[Bal Thackeray]] and his wife Meena Thackeray's three sons.<ref name=close/><ref>{{cite news |title=Uddhav Thackeray Oath Ceremony : \u0909\u0926\u094d\u0927\u0935 \u0920\u093e\u0915\u0930\u0947 \u092c\u0928\u0947 \u092e\u0939\u093e\u0930\u093e\u0937\u094d\u091f\u094d\u0930 \u0915\u0947 CM, \u091b\u0939 \u0915\u0948\u092c\u093f\u0928\u0947\u091f \u092e\u0902\u0924\u094d\u0930\u093f\u092f\u094b\u0902 \u0928\u0947 \u092d\u0940 \u0932\u0940 \u0936\u092a\u0925 |url=https://khabar.ndtv.com/news/india/maharashtra-government-oath-ceremony-live-updates-uddhav-thackeray-sharad-pawar-ajit-pawar-balasaheb-2139806 |accessdate=8 December 2019 |work=NDTVIndia |date=28 November 2019}}</ref> He did his schooling in [[Balmohan Vidyamandir]] and graduated from [[Sir J.J. Institute of Applied Art]].<ref>{{cite news | url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/uddhav-thackeray-sworn-in-19th-chief-minister-of-maharashtra/articleshow/72280087.cms?from=mdr | title=Uddhav Thackeray sworn in as the 18th chief minister of Maharashtra | newspaper=[[The Economic Times]] | date=28 November 2019 | accessdate=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Early political career ==\nIn 2002, Thackeray started his political career as campaign incharge of Shiv Sena in the [[Municipal Corporation of Greater Mumbai|Brihan Mumbai Municipal Corporation]] elections where the party performed well. In 2003, he was appointed as working president of Shiv Sena. Uddhav took over as chief editor of party mouthpiece ''[[Saamana]]'' (a daily [[Marathi language|Marathi]]-language newspaper published by Shiv Sena) in 2006 and resigned in 2019 before becoming chief minister of Maharashtra.<ref>{{cite news|title=Udhav Thackeray quite as Saamna editor|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/uddhav-thackeray-quits-as-saamana-editor-ahead-of-taking-over-as-maharashtra-chief-minister-1623340-2019-11-28|accessdate=29 November 2019|website=India}}</ref>\n\nA split in Shiv Sena happened when his cousin [[Raj Thackeray]] left the party in 2006 to form his own party named [[Maharashtra Navnirman Sena]].<ref>{{cite news |title=How A Murder Case Led To Raj Thackeray's Exit From Shiv Sena|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.in/entry/murder-case-raj-thackeray-exit-shiv-sena_in_5d88b9d3e4b070d468d03613 |accessdate=8 November 2019 |work=HuffPost India |date=25 September 2019 |language=en}}</ref> After the death of his father [[Bal Thackeray]] in 2012, he led the party and got elected as Shiv Sena president in 2013, and under his leadership Shiv Sena joined the [[National Democratic Alliance|NDA]] government in Maharashtra in 2014.<ref>{{cite web | work=Times of India|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/maharashtra-government-formation-news-live-uddhav-thackeray-swearing-in-as-cm/liveblog/72270170.cms| title=Maharashtra government formation news | date=22 April 2004 | accessdate=28 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Chief Minister of Maharashtra==\nThough Thackeray never took any constitutional post in his political career initially, however after a brief political crisis, on 28 November 2019 he took the oath as 19th Chief minister of Maharashtra after being elected as leader of the newly formed post-[[2019 Maharashtra Legislative Assembly election|poll]] coalition [[Maha Vikas Aghadi]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/maharashtra-government-formation-news-live-uddhav-thackeray-swearing-in-as-cm/liveblog/72270170.cms|title=Udhav Thackeray swearing in as CM|website=Times of India|access-date=28 November 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"IE28Nov\">{{cite news |title=Maharashtra swearing-in HIGHLIGHTS: Farmers first; Uddhav sets priority after first cabinet meet |url=https://indianexpress.com/article/india/maharashtra-live-updates-uddhav-thackeray-swearing-in-shiv-sena-ncp-congress-bjp-6140471/ |accessdate=29 November 2019 |work=The Indian Express |date=28 November 2019 |language=en-IN}}</ref><ref name=\"FP29Nov\">{{cite news |title=Uddhav Thackeray sworn in as 19th CM of Maharashtra: First of family to hold this office, 59-yr-old gets kudos from Modi, Sonia Gandhi |url=https://www.firstpost.com/politics/uddhav-thackeray-sworn-in-as-19th-cm-of-maharashtra-first-of-family-to-hold-this-office-59-yr-old-gets-kudos-from-modi-sonia-gandhi-7714171.html |accessdate=29 November 2019 |work=Firstpost |date=29 November 2019}}</ref> Since he is not an elected MLA from any constituency he may loose his chair if does not gets elected as mla within 6 months of power.\n\n==Personal life==\nThackeray is married to Rashmi Thackeray and has two sons, [[Aditya Thackeray|Aditya]] and Tejas.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/nation/Uddhav-May-Shift-to-New-House-After-LS-Elections/2014/04/09/article2157222.ece | title=Uddhav May Shift to New House After LS Elections | newspaper=[[Indian Express]] |place=Mumbai | date=9 April 2014 | accessdate=25 April 2014}}</ref>\n\nWhile elder son Aditya is the president of the Yuva Sena, younger son Tejas is believed to be studying in a college in [[Buffalo, New York]]. Tejas has maintained a very low profile unlike his father and elder brother. On 16 July 2012, Uddhav Thackeray was admitted to Lilavati Hospital after he reported chest pain. He underwent an [[angioplasty]] and all the three blockages in his arteries were successfully removed.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-07-23/india/32803671_1_shiv-sena-leader-uddhav-thackeray-maharashtra-navnirman-sena | title= Shiv Sena leader Uddhav Thackeray discharged from hospital | date= 23 July 2012}}</ref>\n\nThackeray is keen in photography and has exhibited his collection of aerial shots of various [[List of forts in Maharashtra|forts of Maharashtra]] at the [[Jehangir Art Gallery]] in 2004.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/exhibition-of-uddhay-thackeray-photographs-at-jehangir-art-gallery/1/196753.html | title=Thackeray's new conquest | magazine=[[India Today]] | date=26 January 2004 |place=Mumbai | accessdate=25 April 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.hindu.com/2004/01/14/stories/2004011401302200.htm | title=Uddhav Thackeray and those scenic forts | newspaper=[[The Hindu]] | date=14 January 2004 | accessdate=25 April 2014 | author=Vijapurkar, Mahesh}}</ref> He has also published [[photo-book]]s ''Maharashtra Desh'' (2010) and ''Pahava Vitthal'' (2011), capturing various aspects of Maharashtra and the [[varkari|warkari]]s during [[Shayani Ekadashi|Pandharpur Wari]] respectively in the two books.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/mumbai/raj-uddhav-slug-it-out-over-city-s-plight/article1-582470.aspx | title=Raj, Uddhav slug it out over city's plight | newspaper=[[Hindustan Times]] | date=5 August 2010 | accessdate=25 April 2014 | author=Kamath, Naresh}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.mid-day.com/articles/an-aerial-journey/121411 | title=An aerial journey | newspaper=[[Mid Day]] | date=10 May 2011 | accessdate=25 April 2014 | author=Chowdhury, Sudeshna}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Uddhav Thackeray ministry]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.maharashtra.gov.in/1137/1189/ Maharashtra Chief Minister's profile]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{Chief Ministers of Maharashtra}}\n{{Shiv Sena}}\n{{United Progressive Alliance}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Thackeray, Uddhav}}\n[[Category:1960 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Chief Ministers of Maharashtra]]\n[[Category:Marathi politicians]]\n[[Category:Maharashtra politicians]]\n[[Category:Shiv Sena politicians]]\n[[Category:Indian Hindus]]\n[[Category:Marathi people]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Mumbai]]\n[[Category:Bal Thackeray]]\n[[Category:Far-right politicians in India]]\n", "name_user": "Human45688", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Uddhav_Thackeray"}
